<HEAD>Record Prices Paid for Complex Watch, Stieglitz Photos</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Bethe in 7th graf is cq.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A series of 21 photos of clouds by photographer <PERSON> Alfred </PERSON> <PERSON> Stieglitz </PERSON> brought $ 396,000 at auction Monday and a watch sold for $ 539,000, both setting records, auction houses said. The watch sold to a private collector for the highest price ever paid for a watch at auction in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, said <ORGANIZATION> Sotheby </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION>. The photo sale was a record price for a single lot of photography, a spokeswoman for <PERSON> Christie </PERSON>'s auction house said. The watch, with a face measuring 1.4 inches, was made by Swiss craftsmen and took three years to complete. It was designed and commissioned in 1927 by <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Schulz </PERSON>, who worked for <PERSON> Tiffany </PERSON>'s before opening his own business and who also designed watches for <ORGANIZATION> Cartier </ORGANIZATION> `` It was the most complicated watch of its size ever to be made,'' said <PERSON> Daryn </PERSON> <PERSON> Schnipper </PERSON>, a watch expert for <ORGANIZATION> Sotheby </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION>. In addition to a standard dial that tells time, the watch face has four smaller dials. One gives the month, one gives the day of the week, one registers the date and has a second hand, and another gives the phases of the moon. The previous record for a watch sold at auction was set earlier this year when a wristwatch went for $ 275,000. <PERSON> Stieglitz </PERSON>' `` Equivalents _ Three Series of Seven Each'' was bought by an anonymous collector, said <PERSON> Bethe </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldberg </PERSON>, a publicist for <PERSON> Christie </PERSON>'s. The series consists of 21 different black-and-white photos of clouds, each measuring 3 -LCB- by 4 -LCB- inches, dating from the 1920s. <PERSON> Stieglitz </PERSON> signed the title page of the series, dedicating it to <PERSON> Alma </PERSON> <PERSON> Wertheim </PERSON>, a patron and friend. The series was sold by the <PERSON> Wertheim </PERSON> family, <PERSON> Goldberg </PERSON> said.
