<HEAD>Grenade Goes Off in Terrorist's Hands, Killing Him and Policeman</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A terrorist and a policeman were killed by a grenade that burst as the terrorist prepared to toss it at a passing police patrol Monday night, police said. They said an accomplice and a second police officer were wounded in the explosion in <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Minuto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> de </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dios </LOCATION>, a northwestern suburb of this capital city of 6 million people. Two other bombs exploded late Monday in south and central <LOCATION> Bogota </LOCATION>, but no casualties were reported, authorities said. One bomb destroyed part of a bank front and neighboring buildings and the other caused minor damage at the social security building. The latest incidents, following violence late Sunday that wounded two journalists, apparently came in response to a decision by the government of President <PERSON> Virgilio </PERSON> <PERSON> Barco </PERSON> to refuse to negotiate with drug traffickers. The government declared war against the drug lords and their hired killers on Aug. 19 after leading presidential candidate Sen. <PERSON> Luis </PERSON> <PERSON> Galan </PERSON> was assassinated. Since then, at least 237 bombings and bombing attempts have taken place throughout <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>, mostly in <LOCATION> Bogota </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Medellin </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Barranquilla </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Cartegena </LOCATION>, resulting in the deaths of 33 people. Earlier Monday, eight people were killed and 30 injured when a bus sped off the side of a ravine near <LOCATION> Bordo </LOCATION>, 340 miles south of <LOCATION> Bogota </LOCATION>, police said. The bus was traveling north from Ipiales near the border with <LOCATION> Ecuador </LOCATION>. Police said the bus apparently was traveling too fast.
