<HEAD>Police Recover 48 bodies After Clashes in India</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Forty-eight more bodies were recovered on Monday in <LOCATION> Bhagalpur </LOCATION>, a remote town in <LOCATION> Bihar </LOCATION> state hit by Hindu-Moslem violence, and another person was killed when police fired at an angry mob, news reports said. Since Sunday, 171 people have died in <LOCATION> Bhagalpur </LOCATION> and in three villages stretching across a 125-mile swath of <LOCATION> Bihar </LOCATION> state, one of the poorest and most violent in <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>, news media said. <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> India </ORGANIZATION> said the official death toll in <LOCATION> Bhagalpur </LOCATION> stood at 145 since clashes began last Tuesday. Press Trust of <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> put the Bhagalpur toll at 200. In a dispatch from the state capital of <LOCATION> Patna </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> UNI </ORGANIZATION> quoted <LOCATION> Bihar </LOCATION> Home Affairs Commissioner <PERSON> Jiya </PERSON> <PERSON> Lal </PERSON> <PERSON> Arya </PERSON> as saying police fired when the mob attacked homes. Police rescued at least 150 residents. Bhagalpur is on the <LOCATION> Ganges </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>, which is sacred to Hindus. The town is about 110 miles east of <LOCATION> Patna </LOCATION> and 220 miles northwest of <LOCATION> Calcutta </LOCATION>. Some clashes coincided with processions by Hindu militants who are collecting bricks to build a temple at <LOCATION> Ayodhya </LOCATION>, in neighboring <LOCATION> Uttar </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pradesh </LOCATION> state, where Hindus and Moslems lay claim to the same religious site.
