<FIRST>r p PM-CharterRevision     10-30 0727</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Charter Revision,0748</SECOND>
<HEAD>Voters' Challenge: To Make New York City `Normal'</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Tuesday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL STIEG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The cab drivers will still be surly. The Statue of Liberty will still light the harbor. The <LOCATION> Bronx </LOCATION> will still be up, the Battery down, and the folks will still ride in a hole in the ground. But <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> is on the edge of a momentous change _ one that will alter the way the nation's largest city is governed. In a referendum that has drawn little attention in the midst of a tumultuous mayoral campaign, city voters this Nov. 7 will have an opportunity to approve or reject a charter that would strengthen the mayor and <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> while wiping out an entire governing body, the Board of Estimate. The board is arguably the most powerful segment of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>'s government, with final say over the budget. But the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> has ruled that it is unconstitutional, so the city must change. `` I think one of the things we're doing is making <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> like normal governments in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> Frederick </PERSON> <PERSON> A.O </PERSON>. <PERSON> Schwarz </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, chairman of the commission that came up with the new, 393-page city charter. That means forming a bigger <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, changing the mayor's duties and responsibilities and creating new ways to award contracts, approve the budget and myriad other procedures Polls indicate the new charter will pass easily, despite considerable if disjointed opposition. The Board of Estimate dates back to 1901. It reflected a new <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>: In 1898, <LOCATION> Staten </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, the city of <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION> and what is now <LOCATION> Queens </LOCATION> joined <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Bronx </LOCATION> to become one consolidated city. Each of those five boroughs has a president, and those presidents sit on the <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Estimate </ORGANIZATION>, along with the three officials elected citywide: the mayor, comptroller and <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> president. For 89 years, the board has been approving contracts, deciding most land-use questions and approving the annual budget. The citywide officials have two votes each, while each borough president has one. So <LOCATION> Staten </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, with 350,000 residents, has the same voice as <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION>, with 2.2 million. That, the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruled last March, violated the principle of one-person, one-vote. The new plan is updated to suit a changing <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, where minorities account for more than half the population but only 25 percent of the council is black or Hispanic. `` We paid a lot of attention to making sure that minorities had fair representation,'' <PERSON> Schwarz </PERSON> said. The <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> would be expanded from 35 to 51 members under the new plan, and the smaller districts are expected to produce more minority members, perhaps as many as 20, or 40 percent of the council. With the <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Estimate </ORGANIZATION> dissolved, the council will become a true legislature, with final say on the budget and most land use and zoning questions. The mayor will continue running executive agencies, appointing commissioners, proposing the city budget and estimating revenues _ a crucial element in spending debates. `` What the city's doing is moving from a unique, screwball form of government to one that looks a lot more like what other cities do _ that's a strong mayor, strong council form of government,'' said <PERSON> Gene </PERSON> <PERSON> Russianoff </PERSON>, attorney for the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Interest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>. Supporters say the larger council and new requirements for public disclosure and a new independent budget office will check the mayor's power. But without the <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Estimate </ORGANIZATION>, critics contend, the mayor will be too powerful _ `` We will have an imperial mayor,'' said <PERSON> Ralph </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lamberti </PERSON>, borough president of <LOCATION> Staten </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Lamberti </PERSON> and his fellow borough presidents stand to lose the most power under the plan, and are among its most outspoken opponents. The other opponents come from a variety of sources that do n't necessarily have much else in common. `` There's the far left and the far right and we're sort of the center,'' <PERSON> Schwarz </PERSON> said. `` These people are utterly strange bedfellows. They could n't possibly come up with a solution.'' Most city residents seem only vaguely aware of the proposed changes, which are n't, after all, going to revolutionize life in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. The average resident, <PERSON> Schwarz </PERSON> said, `` is going to find government more responsive, and that will be a plus. But will it pave the streets with gold? No.''
</TEXT>
