<HEAD>Investigators Check Maltese Link in Pan Am Bombing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with newspaper report of link
to Palestinian terror group established. Picks up 5th pvs, `London's Sunday
...' TRIMS thereafter. ^By KEVIN COSTELLOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Investigators found a trail leading to <LOCATION> Malta </LOCATION> as the likely source of the bomb that blew up <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> Flight 103 over <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>, killing 270 people, prosecutor's spokesman <PERSON> Jochen </PERSON> <PERSON> Schroers </PERSON> said Monday Authorities said a Libyan man may have played a role in the Dec. 21 bombing. Schroers, of the prosecutor's office, said a suitcase coming from <LOCATION> Malta </LOCATION> aboard an <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Malta </ORGANIZATION> flight was the `` presumed'' container for the bomb. The suitcase was put aboard the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Malta </ORGANIZATION> flight on the tiny <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION> island nation before being transferred to the <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> flight at its originating point in <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION>, officials reported. Other evidence recently uncovered by investigators in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> adds to suspicion that the bombing was carried out by the <ORGANIZATION> Popular </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Palestine-General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Command </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> reported in its Tuesday editions. Sixteen members of the Palestinian group were arrested in raids in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> in October 1988 and a bomb similar to the one believed to have destroyed the plane was seized in that investigation. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> that <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON> <PERSON> Abu </PERSON> <PERSON> Talb </PERSON>, a Palestinian now being held on terrorism charges in <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION>, has told investigators he retrieved one bomb overlooked in the raids, and passed it to another person. Officials declined to identify to whom <PERSON> Talb </PERSON> said he passed the bomb. But they also said <PERSON> Talb </PERSON> was spotted in <LOCATION> Malta </LOCATION> in October 1988 in the company of <PERSON> Hafez </PERSON> <PERSON> Dalkamoni </PERSON>, a suspected leader of the Palestinian group who was arrested in the West German raids later that month. <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Sunday </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> first disclosed the evidence of a possible Maltese connection. It said the bomb was placed in a suitcase containing clothing made and purchased in <LOCATION> Malta </LOCATION>. Citing British sources, the newspaper said the baggage list showed one suitcase was transferred to Flight 103 from <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Malta </ORGANIZATION> Flight KM180, which originated in <LOCATION> Malta </LOCATION> on the morning of Dec. 21. No passenger accompanied the bag on the <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> flight, it said. All 259 people on the jumbo jet and 11 residents of <LOCATION> Lockerbie </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>, died as a result of the Dec. 21 bombing. In a statement sent by fascimile machine to news media, <PERSON> Schroers </PERSON> said West German investigators earlier informed <LOCATION> Scottish </LOCATION> investigators about suspicions regarding <LOCATION> Malta </LOCATION>. `` The suspicions were made more concrete, when the Scottish officials informed the Germans that clothing made in <LOCATION> Malta </LOCATION> was in the presumed bomb suitcase,'' the statement said. It said passengers on the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Malta </ORGANIZATION> flight were not under suspicion. The statement denied British news media reports of friction between West German and British investigators. <PERSON> Schroers </PERSON> said earlier in a telephone interview with The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> that West German investigators `` are in <LOCATION> Malta </LOCATION>, but the Scottish officials are taking the lead.'' `` It was possibly a man of Libyan extraction, but we ca n't say more than that,'' <PERSON> Schroers </PERSON> said of the person who investigators believe bought the clothes that were in the suitcase. `` The investigation into this lead has not been completed.'' Previous reports said the bomb was placed on board in luggage checked in at <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION>. West German investigators repeatedly denied any evidence existed to substantiate those claims. Pan Am Flight 103 originated in <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION>, taking on passengers and luggage flown in from other areas on international `` feeder flights.'' Passengers and bags were transferred to the doomed <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 747 at <LOCATION> Heathrow </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Willi </PERSON> <PERSON> Fundermann </PERSON>, a spokesman for the federal criminal investigations office in <LOCATION> Wiesbaden </LOCATION>, said investigators have a `` hot trail'' leading to <LOCATION> Malta </LOCATION>. `` There are clues that a suitcase from <LOCATION> Malta </LOCATION> may have played a part,'' said <PERSON> Fundermann </PERSON>. `` There are also clues that someone from <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION> _ or at least someone with a Libyan accent _ may have bought the items.'' The Flight 103 bomb was packed into a <ORGANIZATION> Toshiba </ORGANIZATION> radiocassette player, investigators have said. <LOCATION> Malta </LOCATION>, about 180 miles north of <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION>, enjoys good relations with the government of radical leader Col. <PERSON> Moammar </PERSON> <PERSON> Gadhafi </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Tripoli </LOCATION>. In <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>, the chief investigator and head of the judiciary both refused Monday to disclose any details of the hunt for the bomber. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Esson </PERSON>, chief constable of <LOCATION> Dumfries </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Galloway </PERSON> who is leading the international investigation, issued a statement saying investigators are pursuing a number of `` encouraging lines of inquiry'' in a number of countries. <PERSON> Lord </PERSON> <PERSON> Fraser </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>'s Lord Advocate and its top judicial officer, said in a separate statement that `` the investigation continues to make encouraging progress.'' He said he feared that premature disclosure of the progress of the investigation `` could cause grave prejudice to the investigation itself.'' <PERSON> Esson </PERSON> said: `` Since the outset of this inquiry there has been a close liaison between the Scottish police, the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> BKA </ORGANIZATION>. Information exchanged at regular meetings between these three agencies has contributed greatly to the ongoing and very active criminal investigation.''
