<HEAD>Memorial Service for Victims of Plant Explosion, Three More Bodies
Found</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL GRACZYK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PASADENA, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 About 25,000 people attended a memorial service Monday night for 22 workers who died in a series of explosions at a plastics plant last week, and three more bodies were recovered from the rubble. Among those attending the 45-minute service at the <ORGANIZATION> John </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ray </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Harrison </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Convention </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> were 259 relatives of those who died in the <ORGANIZATION> Phillips </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> plant disaster last Monday. `` No one can really explain why happenings such as this occur,'' said S.R. `` Buddy'' <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, chairman emeritus of Bank One of <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> here. `` I surely do n't know, but I do know this: a tragedy of this magnitude brings us all closer together and demonstrates the love, the care and the concern we have for one another.'' Sgt. <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Cluck </PERSON>, chaplain of the <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, asked <PERSON> Phillips </PERSON> employees to honor those who died by having the strength to return to work and live their lives `` the way they would want you to live.'' The recovery of three bodies brought the confirmed death toll to 17. The remains of five workers remain missing. The explosions injured 124 people. Despite thunderstorms and heavy rain, work crews continued moving tons of steel and concrete in hopes of recovering the last of the victims. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Rep. <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Andrews </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, whose district includes this city of 119,300, toured the plant and met with authorities. `` You really have to be here to see how absolutely devastating that blast was,'' <PERSON> Andrews </PERSON> said. `` Fully a quarter of the plant has been eliminated. There is still a safety factor at the plant site. There are still fires burning. It is an awesome sight to see.'' Much of the search has concentrated on the plant's control and finishing rooms, where debris is stacked as high as 40 feet, officials said. The polyethylene plant maufactured almost 20 percent of the nation's production of plastic pellets used to make milk jugs and grocery bags. <PERSON> Phillips </PERSON> officials believe flammable hydrocarbon vapor from ethylene and isobutane gases escaped from a leaking chemical reactor, triggering the explosion. But company officials have said they do n't know how the gases were ignited and wo n't concentrate on finding a cause until all the missing victims have been found.
