<HEAD>Former Radio Free Europe-Poland Leader Gets Hero's Welcome</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Before Solidarity took power in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Jan </PERSON> <PERSON> Nowak </PERSON> was the communist government's `` enemy No. 1'' because for 24 years he headed the Polish section of Radio Free <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, the U.S.-sponsored radio station that beams into the Soviet bloc. When <PERSON> Nowak </PERSON> returned to <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Aug. 28 for his first visit since 1945, he was stunned to find the airport crammed with senior Solidarity leaders. They took time out from forming the first non-communist government in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bloc </LOCATION> to welcome him as a hero. <PERSON> Lech </PERSON> <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> called <PERSON> Nowak </PERSON>'s return `` a visible symbol of change,'' said <PERSON> Nowak </PERSON>, and his warm reception was symbolic of an improved status for Radio Free Europe and Radio Liberty behind the crumbling Iron Curtain. The stations were created in 1950 and 1951 during the Cold War, and despite their ups and downs over the years, are thriving in the current thaw. <PERSON> Nowak </PERSON> headed the Polish section for 24 years starting in 1951. Official Polish television, which formerly condemned the so-called `` foreign voices'' that carried news censored from state-run media, not only reported <PERSON> Nowak </PERSON>'s triumphant return, it broadcast an interview with him. When <PERSON> Nowak </PERSON> stepped out the next day, `` to take a nostalgic walk through the city I had not visited for 45 years,'' a taxi driver veered over, took him around town, and refused to accept payment. `` The driver told me he had seen the airport arrival on television. He said, ` I listened to Radio Free Europe for so many years without paying anything. How can I take money from you?'' <PERSON> Nowak </PERSON>, 76, recalled during an interview after he returned to his home near <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. Like <PERSON> Nowak </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Free </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Europe </ORGANIZATION> and its sister station, <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberty </ORGANIZATION>, are enjoying their new role not only in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> but in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and other countries of the communist bloc. `` It has become a very exciting place to be ... The radios are on the cutting edge'' of the changes underway in the Soviet bloc, said <PERSON> Gene </PERSON> <PERSON> Pell </PERSON>, a former <ORGANIZATION> NBC-TV </ORGANIZATION> correspondent who now directs the twin radio stations. The stations were founded by the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intelligence </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>, and in 1971, after revelations of <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION> misdeeds, were separated from the spy agency and funded by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. Congressional reports requested by the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Relations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> in 1984-85 criticized the stations for sometimes broadcasting material considered abusive of communist and government officials in the Soviet bloc. Since <PERSON> Pell </PERSON> took over in November 1985, said a foreign relations committee aide, `` he has done a fine job in curbing the problems we saw four years ago.'' But media in the Soviet bloc continued to depict `` the voices'' as branches of the <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION>, jammed their broadcasts to major cities, and bitterly condemned emigres like <PERSON> Nowak </PERSON> who worked for them. Nevertheless, the stations had an audience estimated at 50 million, according to the 1985 congressional report. Under the reforms launched since then by Soviet President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, the vituperation has ended and the audience has expanded. `` The major breakthrough was in November of last year, when they turned the jammers off,'' <PERSON> Pell </PERSON> said in a recent interview in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. Taking advantage of the thaw, <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberty </ORGANIZATION>, which broadcasts to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, has hired reporters in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Leningrad </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kiev </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Novosibirsk </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Pell </PERSON>, who was the <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> correspondent in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> in the late 1970's, when most Soviets feared speaking with Westerners and could receive prison sentences of up to seven years for listening to <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Free </ORGANIZATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. Radio Free <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> _ which broadcasts to the rest of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> bloc </LOCATION> _ has received permission to open an office in <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>, and wants a bureau in <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION>. Official press criticisms have tapered off, and the weekly <ORGANIZATION> Moscow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> last year praised <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberty </ORGANIZATION>'s coverage of the December 1988 earthquake in <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>, calling it better than Radio <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>'s. `` In this case, we heard on a foreign band what we should have heard on our own,'' <PERSON> Vladimir </PERSON> <PERSON> Ostrogorsky </PERSON> wrote in the Dec. 18, 1988, <ORGANIZATION> Moscow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION>. Although <PERSON> Ostrogorsky </PERSON> said the `` voices'' in the past had broadcast `` rumors, misrepresentations and outright lies,'' and had `` pushed their own ideological goods packaged as information,'' he praised the end of the jamming as testimony `` to the progress of glasnost'' or greater openness. <PERSON> Pell </PERSON> said, `` Simultaneously, another thing happened, the most significant of all. The place opened up. We could call people, they could call us.'' Broadcasters in <LOCATION> Munich </LOCATION> tape reports from throughout the Soviet bloc, and transmit them back in. `` We now have a broadcast called ` at the kiosk,' in which our <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> correspondent reads excerpts from press reports the same day they are published,'' said <PERSON> Pell </PERSON>. The show is popular because the most interesting newspapers sell out quickly even in major cities, and may not be available at all elsewhere.
