<HEAD>Cleanup, Investigations in Wake of Week of Pennsylvania Prison Uprisings</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with new disturbance; picks up
4th graf, `Camp Hill's trouble ...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto HX1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL BLOOD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAMP HILL, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 State police and guards kept watch Sunday over the remaining inmates at a riot-torn state prison, and investigations were planned to determine what caused two nights of bloody violence at the overcrowded penitentiary. In <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>, a small fire broke out at a city prison Sunday night, forcing authorities to move about 100 inmates, said a police detective who spoke on condition of anonymity. No one was injured in the fire at <ORGANIZATION> Northeast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Detention </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, which came one night after a much more serious riot at another city prison and was the fifth disturbance to hit a <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> prison within a week. The 100 inmates were taken to a gymnasium as smoke from the fire cleared, the detective said. Four young men refused to return to their cells, and guards forced them to return, according to the officer. The prison near <LOCATION> Camp </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION>, where more than 100 people were injured in two nights of rioting last week, was calm Sunday, said <ORGANIZATION> Corrections </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON>. The uprising there and at other prisons resulted in injuries to at least 183 people. Camp <PERSON> Hill </PERSON>'s troubles came between a disturbance at the <LOCATION> Huntingdon </LOCATION> state prison that left 48 injured last Monday and one at a <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> prison Saturday night, which resulted in serious injuries to three guards and the hospitalization of nine inmates. The Camp Hill uprising left at least 123 injured, almost half of the facility's buildings destroyed or damaged by fire, and hundreds of inmates without cells. Five people taken hostage Thursday were released Friday when state police stormed the prison, restoring order after a building-by-building assault. <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> said 744 Camp <PERSON> Hill </PERSON> inmates had been transferred to other state prisons since Friday. He said 200 more inmates would be sent to a new federal prison in <LOCATION> Bradford </LOCATION> in northwest <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>, and as many as 600 others would be sent in groups of 50 to other federal jails. Hundreds of convicts had been forced to sleep on the ground at <LOCATION> Camp </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> under the eyes of guards and police officers. With the transfers and cleaning and repairing cells at <LOCATION> Camp </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION>, officials hoped to make cell space available for all inmates by Monday, <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> said. `` We've got a lot of people in there cleaning up cellblocks as well as the kitchen buildings,'' <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> said. The disturbance Saturday at <LOCATION> Holmesburg </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Prison </LOCATION>, a county jail in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>, was a `` copycat'' of the <LOCATION> Camp </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> riot, said city Prison Commissioner <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Gallagher </PERSON>. During the riot, which officials said began after an argument between several prisoners and a guard, inmates could be heard chanting, `` <LOCATION> Camp </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Camp </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION>.'' Forty-seven guards and 114 inmates were taken to hospitals, and nine inmates were admitted, three with head wounds, <PERSON> Gallagher </PERSON> said. Other convicts suffered broken bones and cuts, said hospital officials, who did not have an exact count. Three of the 47 guards suffered broken bones and deep cuts, but none were hospitalized, <PERSON> Gallagher </PERSON> said. Gov. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Casey </PERSON> said Saturday that he would appoint an independent commission to investigate why inmates rebelled at <LOCATION> Camp </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> on Wednesday and how they were able to get out of their locked cells to resume and escalate the violence Thursday. The state <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Judiciary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> and a state <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Judiciary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> subcommittee </ORGANIZATION> also planned to conduct their own reviews. At least one of the committees plans to study prison overcrowding, a problem at both state and county prisons. Officials say overcrowding may have been a contributing factor to the two state-prison problems as well as the <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> disturbance. <PERSON> Casey </PERSON> said he also would back a criminal investigation of the riot, accelerate plans to replace the lost prison space and lessen overcrowding elsewhere, move to punish the inmates behind the uprising and review the need for more corrections officers. After the first day of violence ended Wednesday, <LOCATION> Camp </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> superintendent <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Freeman </PERSON> said the prison did not have enough guards to deal with the prison population, which was 45 percent over capacity when the riots began. No damage estimate was available yet. <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> said four of the five hostages Thursday had been released from hospitals. The remaining guard was in fair condition. Three other prison staffers and six convicts also remained hospitalized Sunday.
