<HEAD>Congress Looking Into Decline in US Oats Production</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A decline in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> oats production is prompting <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to look into the situation, and <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> analysts say consumer demand for oatmeal is one of the many factors for consideration. Some believe the government's price support program for oats should be modified to encourage farmers to plant more oats instead of turning to other feed grains such as barley, corn or sorghum. Whatever remedies are forthcoming, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> since 1982 has been a net importer of oats instead of an exporter. <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Finland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> are the major foreign suppliers. `` The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> market share of all world -LRB- oats -RRB- imports rose to an annual average of 44 percent in 1985-88, largest of all importing countries,'' says the department's <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. The agency, in a new staff report prepared as background for 1990 farm legislation, said oats are grown in most states but are concentrated in the North Central region, including the <LOCATION> Dakotas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Nebraska </LOCATION>. In the 1950s, oats were grown on more than 40 million acres, and annual farm prices averaged 58 cents to 72 cents per bushel. In recent years, oats have been produced on 6 million to 10 million acres, with farm prices climbing from $ 1.21 per bushel in 1986 to $ 1.56 in 1987 and a record $ 2.67 in 1988. The value of oats production in 1987 ranked 16th among major <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> field crops at $ 606 million. By comparison, corn was $ 14 billion; soybeans, $ 11.3 billion; hay, $ 9 billion; and wheat, $ 5.5 billion. `` The principal domestic use of oats is for livestock feed, although it has recently become a specialty feed for race and pleasure horses,'' the report said. Oats as human food includes the traditional oatmeal, along with oat flour, natural cereals, meat product extenders, cookies and breads, granola, oat bran and baby food. `` Recent medical research has shown that certain fibrous plant materials in the diet can lower serum cholesterol concentrations,'' the report said. `` The fibers, however, must be water soluble. Oat bran is water soluble, but wheat bran is not. Water-soluble dietary fibers also lower post-meal blood glucose levels in insulin-dependent diabetics.'' The report added: `` Thus, oat bran or whole oats is beginning to play a larger role in improving health through diet. Oats consumption by humans appears to be increasing, as <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> diets seem to be shifting toward cereal-based foods and away from fatty, high-protein animal-based foods.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> scientists say they have developed a new lethal snack for cockroaches, grasshoppers, crickets and fire ants that smells too yummy to resist. The bait includes corn mash left over from the manufacture of fuel-grade alcohol, ethanol, and a water-absorbent gel. The mixture is laced with a slow-release insecticide. According to the department's <ORGANIZATION> Agricultural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, the new bait was initially designed to use against cockroaches. But researchers at the agencies insect laboratory in <LOCATION> Gainesville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, found it attracted the other species, too. Entomologist <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brenner </PERSON> said the combination of corn mash and gel tends to retain moisture and `` remains aromatic under high temperatures and dry conditions.'' That makes it particularly attractive to roaches, which become hungry and thirsty when the temperature rises. The bait has been tested in the field as well as in the laboratory, and is waiting on approval by the <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>, he said. Although the mash-gel combination was developed by <PERSON> Brenner </PERSON> and an agency colleague, <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Patterson </PERSON>, there are two other co-inventors: <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Pierce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, Cashier, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Marvin </PERSON> <PERSON> Hult </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Vent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Peoria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>. Air Vent and <ORGANIZATION> Pierce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> signed research agreements with the <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> agency in February 1988 and hold first rights to license the bait when a patent is granted <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON>, to protect the bait's aroma and moisture during storage, suggested wrapping the bait in wax film that a hungry cockroach can open easily. <PERSON> Hult </PERSON> recommended using a bait holder, which would extend the shelf life of the mixture and protect it until ready for use. <PERSON> Brenner </PERSON> said that while the corn mash attracts roaches, hoppers, crickets and fire ants, it does n't attract warm-blooded animals as do baits of fruit, bread, raisins or beer.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The world's rice production is expected to rise slightly in 1989-90 but will fall short of meeting global demands, according to <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> projections. Significant harvest increases are expected in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Indonesia </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, said the department's <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s production may drop 6 percent from last year's record level but still would be the second-largest Total foreign rice production was forecast at 326 million metric tons, and the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> crop at 4.93 million tons, milled equivalent. Analysts said that would be the fourth straight year that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> rice production has fallen short of total use, meaning another reduction in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> rice stockpile by next Aug. 1.
</TEXT>
