<HEAD>Accident on Flight Deck Leaves Five Dead, Two Injured</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 9th graf, `The Lexington ...,' to UPDATE with expected
time of arrival for ship.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY19</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL KACZOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PENSACOLA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A trainer jet crash-landed Sunday afternoon on the flight deck of the aircraft carrier <LOCATION> Lexington </LOCATION> in the <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, killing five people and injuring at least two, the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> said. The 3:30 p.m. CST crash of the two-seat T-2 <LOCATION> Buckeye </LOCATION> caused several fires on the World War II-era ship that sailors quickly brought under control, officials said. The <LOCATION> Lexington </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>'s oldest aircraft carrier, was 30 miles south of its home port of <LOCATION> Pensacola </LOCATION> when the accident occurred, said <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> White </PERSON>, a civilian spokesman at <LOCATION> Pensacola </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Naval </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Air </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Station </LOCATION>. Officers on the ship said five people were killed in the crash-landing and at least two were injured, said White. The jet was assigned to <ORGANIZATION> Training </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Squadron </ORGANIZATION> 19, based at the <LOCATION> Meridian </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Miss. </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Naval </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Station </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> White </PERSON> said. The victims' identities were being withheld pending notification of their relatives In addition to destroying the jet, the crash did major damage to two aircraft on the flight deck and minor damage to another, said Army Maj. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, a spokesman at the Pentagon. <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> helicopters took the dead and injured to the <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Florida </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Regional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGA