<HEAD>Supreme Court to Hear Arguments on Kansas City Desegregation Case</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Prenoon lead planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY MASSEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> is being asked to decide whether a federal judge may impose a tax increase to pay for court-ordered school desegregation in <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mo </LOCATION>. At issue in today's oral arguments is a federal judge's 1987 order doubling the property tax of residents in the <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> school district to finance a court-ordered plan for racially desegregating the public schools. Legal scholars and education officials say the court's decision could shape future school desegregation plans across the country and define the federal courts' power to remedy constitutional violations involving issues from prison overcrowding to fair housing. The state of <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> is asking the justices to overturn a decision by the 8th <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> that upheld the property tax increase ordered by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Russell </PERSON> <PERSON> Clark </PERSON>. The state contends that the federal courts lack the power to order higher taxes even to correct a constitutional violation such as racial discrimination in schools. The school district and a group of school children, who brought the original desegregation case in 1977, are urging the high court to uphold the tax decision. The district contends that state property tax law and local voters can not be allowed to frustrate the constitutional rights of <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>'s minority schoolchildren to an equal educational opportunity. <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> ordered the tax increase in September 1987 after the local school district was unable to pay its share of a more than $ 400 million desegregation plan he had approved for capital improvements in buildings and establishment of special `` magnet'' schools. State law says local property taxes may be raised only with voters' approval, and in some instances only with a two-thirds majority. District voters had not approved a levy increase since 1969, with four tax increase proposals rejected in 1986 and 1987 to finance the desegregation plan. In addition to doubling the property tax, <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> imposed an income tax surcharge on those people living or working in the school district. The appeals court struck down the income surcharge in August 1988, but upheld the district court's authority to order an increase in the property tax. However, the appeals court modified the procedure for imposing the higher tax levy. The appeals court found that state law had effectively prevented the school district from levying the necessary taxes to pay for the desegregation plan. It upheld <PERSON> Clark </PERSON>'s order as one that `` set aside levy limitations,'' and empowered the elected local school board to set the needed tax levels within certain limits.
