<FIRST>r p PM-SeattleMayoral     10-30 0577</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Seattle Mayoral,0600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Busing a Major Issue in Seattle's Mayoral Race</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM KLASS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An anti-busing initiative figures strongly in the Nov. 7 mayoral election that will result in either the city's first black or first Republican mayor in more than two decades. Polls have shown strong support for Initiative 34, which is backed by Republican <PERSON> Doug </PERSON> <PERSON> Jewett </PERSON>. They also give a slight edge to his opponent, City Councilman <PERSON> Norm </PERSON> <PERSON> Rice </PERSON>, who is against the measure. <PERSON> Rice </PERSON>, 46, would be the first black mayor in a city where blacks comprise only about 10 percent of the population. `` If I win, it's going to say that people in <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION> recognize how hard people work and how well they do their jobs,'' <PERSON> Rice </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Jewett </PERSON>, the 42-year-old city attorney, would be the first Republican to win the non-partisan office since Dorm <PERSON> Braman </PERSON> in 1965. The anti-busing measure asks, but does not require, the independently elected and budgeted city <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> to switch from a `` controlled choice'' attendance plan that requires busing of about 10 percent of the 40,000 students for racial balance to a completely open enrollment system. In exchange for abandoning mandatory busing, schools would get about $ 4.5 million in annual sales tax revenue that now goes to the city, with that money reserved for `` magnet'' programs designed to encourage racial balance. <PERSON> Jewett </PERSON> and <PERSON> Rice </PERSON> finished one-two among 13 candidates in September's primary. <PERSON> Rice </PERSON> has trumpeted his Democratic credentials, including endorsements from the Rev. <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, Gov. <PERSON> Booth </PERSON> <PERSON> Gardner </PERSON>, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Rep. <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> McDermott </PERSON>, and outgoing Mayor <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Royer </PERSON>, who decided not to run for a fourth term. A random telephone survey of 400 likely voters taken Oct. 13-16 for <ORGANIZATION> KIRO-TV </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Seattle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post-Intelligencer </ORGANIZATION>, showed <PERSON> Rice </PERSON> leading by 46-39 percent with the rest undecided. In the poll, which had a 4.8 point margin of error, 46 percent favored the initiative, 32 percent were opposed and the rest undecided. Many observers believe the <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> did Rice a favor by refusing to strike the initiative from the ballot. Opponents claimed the initiative violated the state Constitution, but the court decided to hear that claim only if the measure were passed. As a result, the overwhelmingly Democratic electorate can reject busing while voting for <PERSON> Rice </PERSON>. <PERSON> Rice </PERSON> sees crime as the top issue. <PERSON> Jewett </PERSON> says the schools are tops in his campaign but he accuses the news media of downplaying his positions on crime, growth and other issues. <PERSON> Jewett </PERSON> helped draft the measure and has been its leading advocate. City council and school board members generally are opposed. So is <PERSON> Rice </PERSON>, who says the plan is racist in effect if not in intent. He rejects suggestions that <PERSON> Jewett </PERSON> is racially biased. On Oct. 9, <PERSON> Rice </PERSON> announced his own plan for assuring racial balance in schools with magnet programs, stronger city support for education and incentives for housing integration. The plan would eliminate any need for mandatory busing within four years, he said. <PERSON> Jewett </PERSON> promptly accused his opponent of a near-flip-flop to woo voters. `` The political issue is that of leadership,'' he said. `` They've watched <PERSON> Norm </PERSON> <PERSON> Rice </PERSON> go from adamant opposition to ending mandatory busing to embracing it.' <PERSON> Rice </PERSON> admits a considerable change of heart `` because of what busing does to working families'' but said that if nothing else keeps the schools racially balanced, mandatory measures must continue. `` I still think that integrated, quality education is important to the future of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>,'' he said.
</TEXT>
