<HEAD>Four Dissidents Captured in China's Sichuan Province</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Chinese police arrested four leaders of a dissident group that was active in the pro-democracy movement and worked to set up an underground armed force, an official Chinese report said today. The report indicates <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> authorities are continuing the crackdown on people involved in the protests that swept the nation last spring. The `` <ORGANIZATION> Chongqing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Patriotic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democracy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION>'' in <LOCATION> Sichuan </LOCATION> province of southwestern <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> was formed May 21 after martial law was declared in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>, the official <ORGANIZATION> China </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> said in a report appearing in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>. Police arrested the group's leader, <PERSON> Dai </PERSON> <PERSON> Weiping </PERSON>, and three other key members, the news service said. The brief report did not say when the arrests were made. The report from <LOCATION> Chongqing </LOCATION> called the organization a `` counterrevolutionary group,'' a label that Chinese officials have been using for the pro-democracy protests. The news service said league members participated in illegal marches supporting the student-led protests in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>, gave reactionary speeches, and incited turmoil. After Chinese troops crushed the pro-democracy movement in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> on June 4, the league remained active by calling secret meetings and scheming to steal guns to set up an underground fighting force, the report said. Hundreds of unarmed civilians were killed during the military's June assault in the capital Today's report also claimed that the league tried to get foreign support, but did not elaborate. The <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> China </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Morning </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION>, an English-language newspaper in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, quoted unidentified analysts in <LOCATION> Sichuan </LOCATION> as saying they believed the league was an organization of workers, including the unemployed. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> annnounced thousands of arrests at the beginning of the crackdown. However, few arrests have been publicized recently, probably reflecting in part government sensitivity over foreign criticism.
