<HEAD>Eds: Omard cq in 2nd graf</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ASPEN, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Rescuers rappelled 60 feet down a tow cable into an icy mountain river to rescue a month-old girl from a car that plunged off a road and was mostly submerged for 45 minutes. The infant's mother and grandparents were killed in the crash Sunday at Independence Pass, said <LOCATION> Pitkin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> Sheriff's spokesman <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Crockett </PERSON>. The victims, Omard and <PERSON> Marjorie </PERSON> <PERSON> Harrison </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>, and their daughter, <PERSON> Kary </PERSON> <PERSON> Venable </PERSON>, 19, of <LOCATION> Kingwood </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, had hitchhiked a ride with two teen-age girls after their van was disabled in an accident on state Highway 82 outside this ski resort town, <PERSON> Crockett </PERSON> said. The teens survived. The car slid off the snowy highway and down a 60-foot cliff into a stretch of the <LOCATION> Roaring </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Fork </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> called `` Devil's <LOCATION> Punchbowl </LOCATION>.'' The first volunteer firefighters on the scene spotted the car, upside down and up to its wheels in the frigid water, <PERSON> Crockett </PERSON> said. The used a truck-mounted winch to pull the car near the shore, then two of the volunteers, Dr. <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Ayers </PERSON> and <PERSON> Rick </PERSON> <PERSON> Dean </PERSON>, rappelled down the tow cable and pulled month-old <PERSON> Samantha </PERSON> <PERSON> Venable </PERSON> from the car. The child was in critical condition today at <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mary </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> in </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Grand </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Junction </ORGANIZATION>, a nursing supervisor said. The driver, <PERSON> Britt </PERSON> <PERSON> Rosen </PERSON>, 17, of <LOCATION> Aspen </LOCATION>, and her passenger, <PERSON> Maelle </PERSON> <PERSON> Deschutter </PERSON>, 16, of <LOCATION> Snowmass </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Village </LOCATION>, managed to kick out the car's front windows and escape to hail a passing motorist, <PERSON> Crockett </PERSON> said Ms. <PERSON> Rosen </PERSON> was treated for hypothermia and Ms. <PERSON> Deschutter </PERSON> for a broken arm. <PERSON> Harrison </PERSON>, 64, and Mrs. <PERSON> Harrison </PERSON>, 61, were found dead in the back seat, <PERSON> Crockett </PERSON> said. A dog also was killed.
