<HEAD>Dollar, Gold Rise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar rose against most major foreign currencies in early European trading today. Gold prices rose as much as $ 4.25 an ounce. Currency dealers said trading was calm, and the market's attention had shifted to cross-currency trading They said the dollar moved up from its lows of late Friday on short-covering, but that interest in dollar trading was minimal. `` It's very quiet so far this morning,'' said one trader in <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION>. `` I do n't see much space for the dollar to decline.'' The Bank of <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> reportedly intervened in the market to prop up the British pound, which fell last week following <PERSON> Nigel </PERSON> <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON>'s resignation as Chancellor of the Exchequer At midmorning, it cost $ 1.5715 to buy one pound, cheaper for buyers than $ 1.5750 late Friday. Other dollar rates at midmorning compared with late Friday: _ 1.8350 West German marks, up from 1.8300 _ 1.6053 Swiss francs, up from 1.6005 _ 6.2318 French francs, up from 6.2190 _ 2.0713 Dutch guilders, down from 2.0820 _ 1,345.50 Italian lire, up from 1,342.00 _ 1.1745 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1746 In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, where trading ends before <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s business day begins, the dollar fell 0.58 yen Later, in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, it was quoted at 142.05 yen. Gold opened in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> at a bid price of $ 379 a troy ounce, compared with late Friday's $ 374.25. At midmorning, the city's five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $ 378.50. In <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION>, the bid price was $ 377, up from $ 373 late Friday. Earlier, in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, gold rose $ 1.46 to close at a bid of $ 378.75. Silver was quoted in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> at a bid price of $ 5.27 a troy ounce, up from Friday's $ 5.19.
