<HEAD>Court Turns Away Dispute Over Anti-Bias Laws</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today turned away a dispute over how to apply federal anti-bias laws to foreign-owned businesses operating in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The court, over one dissenting vote, let stand a ruling challenged both by <ORGANIZATION> Korean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lines </ORGANIZATION> and a <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> man replaced in his <ORGANIZATION> KAL </ORGANIZATION> job by a Korean citizen. Justice <PERSON> Byron </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> White </PERSON> voted to hear arguments in the case but four votes are needed to grant such review. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> MacNamara </PERSON> was fired in 1982 as <ORGANIZATION> KAL </ORGANIZATION>'s Philadelphia-based district sales manager for <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> and southern <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> He was replaced by <PERSON> Wan </PERSON> <PERSON> Gin </PERSON> <PERSON> Chung </PERSON>, who is in this country on a visa. <PERSON> MacNamara </PERSON> said the airline violated that portion of the Civil Rights Act of 1964 banning discrimination based on race or national origin. <PERSON> MacNamara </PERSON>, 57 when he was fired, also said <PERSON> KAL </PERSON> violated a federal law against age bias. <PERSON> Chung </PERSON> was 42 in 1982. The 3rd U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION>, in its ruling last December, gave partial victories to both <PERSON> MacNamara </PERSON> and KAL. The appeals court ordered that <PERSON> MacNamara </PERSON>'s lawsuit go to trial, but said he could prevail only if proving KAL intentionally discriminated against him based on some illegal criterion. The appeals court said that to win, <PERS