<HEAD>Court Leaves Intact $4.25 Million Award to Navy Divers' Families</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today left intact a $ 4.25 million award to the families of five <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> divers killed in an accident aboard the submarine USS Grayback in the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> seven years ago. The court, without comment, rejected an appeal by <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dynamics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, designer of the diving chamber in which the men died. The accident occurred near <LOCATION> Subic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> the night of Jan. 16, 1982, when the divers were trapped inside the diving chamber without adequate air. A ventilation valve that allows air to enter the flooded chamber was not fully open, creating a vacuum as the water drained. The victims were <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Cassopolis </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Bond </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Bremerton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wash. </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Bloomer </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Middleton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ky. </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Rodney </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitz </PERSON> <PERSON> of </PERSON> <PERSON> Hixson </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Tenn. </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Leslie </PERSON> <PERSON> Shelton </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Goldsboro </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C </LOCATION>. The Grayback, originally a missile-carrying sub, was converted in the late 1960s to dispatch divers underwater. General Dynamics designed the diving chamber, which then was built by the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>. Court records said the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> was aware of a problem with the ventilation valve. It was difficult to turn and there were no warning devices to tell the divers it was not open completely. But the sub operated safely for 13 years as the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>, rather than redesigning the system, chose to compensate for the problem by training divers to cope. A federal judge in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> ordered <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dynamics </ORGANIZATION> to pay $ 4.25 million to the victims' families. The <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> was not ordered to pay any money. The 5th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> upheld the damage judgment in February. The appeals court, interpreting a key 1988 <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruling, refused to shield General Dynamics from the award. The high court last year ruled that a military contractor is protected from being sued when the government approves equipment conforming to `` reasonably precise'' Pentagon specifications and the company warns the government about any potential dangers of which it is aware. The 5th Circuit court said that ruling does not protect <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dynamics </ORGANIZATION> because the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>, in effect, rubber-stamped the contractor's design plans. Thus, the appeals court said, it was the company rather than the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> that exercised discretion over the chamber's design. `` The government does not exercise a discretionary function by merely approving the contractor's work,'' the appeals court said. `` If the government delegates its design discretion to the contractor and allows the contractor to develop the design, the government contractor defense -LRB- against being sued -RRB- does not apply.'' Major military contractors and business groups joined <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dynamics </ORGANIZATION> in urging the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> to overturn the 5th Circuit court ruling. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chamber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> said the appeals court ruling undermines the 1988 <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> decision and could discourage companies from competing for military contracts. The case is <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dynamics </ORGANIZATION> vs. <PERSON> Trevino </PERSON>, 89-376.
