<HEAD>Court Won't Revive Libel Suit Against Iowa Senator</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A retired Marine lieutenant colonel who worked for former Sen. <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Jepsen </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Iowa </LOCATION>, lost a <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> bid today to revive a libel lawsuit against Sen. <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Harkin </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Iowa </LOCATION>, and two others. The court, without comment, let stand a ruling that threw out <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Secrist </PERSON>'s suit. <PERSON> Secrist </PERSON>, while still an active-duty <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION>, was assigned to <PERSON> Jepsen </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> office staff in 1983. The arrangement was a controversial one, with <PERSON> Secrist </PERSON> continuing to be paid his $ 45,000 annual salary by the <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Harkin </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> member at the time who ran against and defeated <PERSON> Jepsen </PERSON> a in a 1984 Senate race, criticized his Republican opponent's appointment of <PERSON> Secrist </PERSON>. <PERSON> Harkin </PERSON> distributed a statement to the news media that said <PERSON> Secrist </PERSON> helped raise funds for <PERSON> Jepsen </PERSON>'s campaign. The statement disputed <PERSON> Jepsen </PERSON>'s claim that <PERSON> Secrist </PERSON> was hired to help procure defense contracts for <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> businesses. <PERSON> Secrist </PERSON> retired from the <ORGANIZATION> Marines </ORGANIZATION> in 1985 to become a <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> lobbyist for defense contractor <ORGANIZATION> Rockwell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION>. In 1986 he sued <PERSON> Harkin </PERSON>; <PERSON> Pam </PERSON> <PERSON> McKinney </PERSON>, the senator's press secretary; and <PERSON> Harkin </PERSON>'s campaign manager, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Frew </PERS