<HEAD>Court Let Stand Rulings on `Adult' Magazines</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note contents</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today let stand rulings that may allow <LOCATION> Urbana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, officials to ban as obscene five `` adult'' magazines generally not considered hard-core pornography. The court, without comment, rejected an appeal by store owners who said their free-speech rights were violated by the ban. Store owners <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Downing </PERSON> and <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Veneroni </PERSON> said the magazines are known in the publications industry as `` adult sophisticate'' magazines, similar to <ORGANIZATION> Playboy </ORGANIZATION> and Penthouse. `` Magazines of this genre generally contain erotic photographs of a woman or a man or couples in various poses, often fully nude, but avoid explicit depictions of sexual activity,'' the store owners said. The magazines are Nuggets, Velvet, Juggs, Oui and Big Boobs. Copies were puchased by <LOCATION> Urbana </LOCATION> Law Director <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Newlin </PERSON> on Nov. 25, 1985, at the Main News and Smoke Shop run by Downing and <LOCATION> Veneroni </LOCATION>. A municipal judge ruled that the magazines are obscene, opening the way for city officials to ban their sale in <LOCATION> Urbana </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Ohio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, by a 5-2 vote, upheld the ruling in May. `` Courts are not bound by the magazine industry's determination of what is explicit,'' the state court said. `` All five magazines contain either in the text, photographs or their advertisements numerous depictions or descriptions of ultimate sexual acts. -LRB- They -RRB- are legally obscene under <LOCATION> Urbana </LOCATION> ordinances.'' For example, the state court said, there are ads in the magazines showing sexual activity in which small black dots were used to obscure sexual organs. The dots would `` not preclude a jury from finding'' the pictures are obscene, the state court said. The store owners said the ban violates a 1973 <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruling that says material is obscene if the average person using contemporary community standards finds it appeals to prurient interests and depicts sexual acts in a patently offensive manner. That ruling said the work must be judged as a whole, and must be found to lack serious literary, artistic, political or scientific value. The case is Downing vs. <LOCATION> Urbana </LOCATION>, 89-298.
