<HEAD>Drug Manufacturers Lose Appeal of New York Liability Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today refused to hear appeals by three drug manufacturers fighting lawsuits over the effects of DES, a drug once used by pregnant women to prevent miscarriages. The court, without comment, left intact a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> ruling aimed at forcing all manufacturers of the drug to share in paying damages for injuries allegedly caused by DES. DES, the common name for the synthetic female hormone diethylstilbestrol, was made and sold by some 300 phramaceutical companies from 1947 until 1971. Up to 3 million women used it to help prevent miscarriages. But in 1970 researchers discovered a connection between DES and cancer in the daughters of women who used the drug. There was evidence the cancer often did not develop until the daughter of the DES user was from 15 to 25 years old. In the cases acted on today, E.R. <ORGANIZATION> Squibb </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Sons, <ORGANIZATION> Eli </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lilly </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Rexall </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> challenged a ruling last April by the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION>. The state court said it is generally impossible to identify the manufacturer of the DES ingested in any particular case. Druggists usually filled prescriptions from whatever was on hand _ and one brand of DES pretty much resembled the next, the state court said. Also, it said, because years or decades passed before the cancer developed, it is practically impossible to trace the producer of DES in any particular case. The state court rejected manufacturers' claims that they should not be held liable for potentially millions of dollars in damages when there is no proof they made the drug that caused any injury. But, the appeals court said: `` It would be inconsistent with the reasonable expectations of a modern society to say to these -LRB- women -RRB- that because of the insidious nature of an injury that long remains dormant, and because so many manufacturers, each behind a curtain, contributed to the devastation, the cost of injury should be borne by the innocent and not the wrongdoers.'' The state court said damage awards against each company should be paid based on its percentage of national DES sales. This so-called market theory corresponds `` to the overall culpability of each defendant, measured by the amount of risk of injury each defendant created to the public at large,'' the state court said. That court also upheld a 1986 <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> law that suspended the deadline for filing damage claims allegedly caused by DES. The law permitted suits to be filed for one year, regardless of when the injury occurred. Because of the latent nature of DES injuries, `` we believe that ... an injustice has been rectified'' by creating the one-year window, the state court said. The cases are <ORGANIZATION> Rexall </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> vs. <PERSON> Tigue </PERSON>, 89-168; E.R. <ORGANIZATION> Squibb </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Sons vs. <PERSON> Hymowitz </PERSON>, 89-204; <ORGANIZATION> Eli </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lilly </ORGANIZATION> vs. <PERSON> Hymowitz </PERSON>, 89-397.
</TEXT>
