<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today refused to make it easier for police pursuing people suspected of minor crimes to enter their homes without court warrants. The justices, without comment, let stand a ruling that a <LOCATION> Moorestown </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, man accused of numerous motor vehicle offenses was arrested unlawfully in his home two years ago. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bolte </PERSON> was arrested at his home in the predawn hours of April 6, 1987. Police officer <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Liss </PERSON> had followed a car he noticed swerving on and off the road. He tried to pull the car over by activating his squad car's lights and siren. The swerving car ignored the officer's signals and made four loops through a residential neighborhood before pulling into a private driveway and into a garage. <PERSON> Liss </PERSON> stopped his car in the driveway and ran into the garage. He told <PERSON> Bolte </PERSON> to stop, but <PERSON> Bolte </PERSON> entered the house. <PERSON> Liss </PERSON> followed him, telling <PERSON> Bolte </PERSON> that he was under arrest. When taken to a police station, <PERSON> Bolte </PERSON> refused to take a breathalyzer test. He was charged with reckless driving, driving while intoxicated, refusal to submit to a breathalyzer test, driving with an expired license, failure to maintain a single lane, eluding and resisting arrest, and disorderly conduct. <PERSON> Bolte </PERSON> sought to have his refusal to submit to a breath test thrown out as trial evidence, claiming that it was based on an unlawful arrest. A trial judge turned down <PERSON> Bolte </PERSON>'s request, but a state appeals court and the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jersey </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruled that the evidence must be suppressed. The state's highest court ruled that <PERSON> Bolte </PERSON>'s warrantless arrest in his home amounted to an unreasonable police seizure banned by the Constitution's Fourth Amendment. In the appeal acted on today, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> Attorney General <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Perretti </PERSON> relied on previous rulings in which the justices allowed such warrantless arrests in cases of `` hot pursuit'' by police of criminal suspects. But the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> court said the hot-pursuit exception to the Fourth Amendment's warrant requirement `` has been interpreted to apply only to the pursuit of fleeing felons'' _ not people suspected of relatively minor crimes, or misdemeanors. The case is <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> vs. <PERSON> Bolte </PERSON>, 89-417.
