<HEAD>Court Orders Further Study in Alabama Racial Bias Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today ordered further study in a lawsuit that's been in federal court for 18 years, in which black workers allege racial bias at a railroad freight car plant in <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION>. The justices, in a brief order, said the 11th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> should restudy the case in light of three of their recent civil rights rulings. In one key decision last summer, the justices made it harder to win on-the-job bias cases by using statistics to show racial disparities in an employer's workforce. The <LOCATION> Bessemer </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ala. </LOCATION>, plant was at one time the world's largest for building railroad freight cars. It employed 2,000 in 28 departments before being shut down in 1981. The appeals acted on today stem from a 1971 lawsuit accusing Pullman-Standard and the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steelworkers </ORGANIZATION> union of agreeing to a contract that discriminated against blacks in hiring, training, temporary assignments, promotions and in the company's seniority system. The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in 1982 overturned a federal appeals court ruling that the seniority system violated the federal Civil Rights Act of 1964. The justices said the appeals court exceeded its authority in determining the seniority system intentionally was biased. But the dispute was far from over. The high court left many questions unanswered, including whether blacks seeking damages proved the seniority rules had the effect of discriminating against them even if unintentional. After ensuing lower court hearings, the 11th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> last year handed down a lengthy ruling that in part favored the blacks and in part favored the company and the union. The appeals court said the workers proved the company's procedures for picking supervisors had a discriminatory impact against blacks The appeals court also said the seniority system was not created or maintained with discriminatory intent and that any discrimination in department assignments ended by February 1969. But the appeals court, overturning part of a trial judge's decision, said <PERSON> Pullman-Standard </PERSON> may be forced to pay damages for racially discriminatory department assignments before February 1969 <PERSON> Pullman-Standard </PERSON> asked the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> to dismiss the suit. The company said the appeals court relied incorrectly on statistical evidence to show discriminatory effects. The company's lawyers also said the class-action suit on behalf of all black workers at the plant was defective because some employees who served as representatives of the class were ineligible to sue. The black workers asked the justices to revive their attack on the seniority system, and to make it easier to prove their claims and win damages. The cases are <PERSON> Pullman-Standard </PERSON> vs. <PERSON> Swint </PERSON>, 88-1601, and <PERSON> Swint </PERSON> vs. Pullman-Standard, 88-1602.
