<HEAD>Court Rejects Appeal in Maine Marijuana Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today rejected an appeal by law enforcement officials who discovered marijuana growing on a <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION> couple's heavily wooded property. The court, without comment, let stand a ruling that officers violated the couple's privacy rights when they entered the grounds without a search warrant. The appeal stems from a search by officers from the <ORGANIZATION> Kennebec </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sheriff </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Paul </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wing </ORGANIZATION>'s 4.5-acre property in <LOCATION> Litchfield </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>, on Aug. 19, 1987. <PERSON> Patricia </PERSON> <PERSON> Magagnoli </PERSON> lived there with Wing. The officers, after getting a tip that marijuana was being grown in the area, flew over it in an airplane and spotted what they believed to be marijuana plants in a grassy clearing. Without a court warrant, they entered Wing's property using a driveway that splits into a Y about 100 feet from the road. The left leg of the driveway leads to Wing's home and the right ends at a grassy area where the officers said they discovered the marijuana. The grassy area turned out not to be the same clearing the officers observed from the airplane. That clearing was on a neighbor's property where marijuana also was growing. The officers got a warrant before seizing the marijuana plants and searching the home where Wing and Ms. <PERSON> Magagnoli </PERSON> lived. A state judge ruled the plants could not be used as evidence against the couple. The judge said Wing preserved the heavily wooded nature of the property to guard his privacy, in effect using trees as a substitute for a fence. The judge emphasized that Wing and Ms. <PERSON> Magagnoli </PERSON> said they sunbathed in the nude and made love in the grassy clearing. The couple reasonably expected their `` intimate activities'' there would be as private as if they took place in the home, the judge said. The ruling was upheld by a 3-3 vote of the <ORGANIZATION> Maine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Judicial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> last June. <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION> prosecutors said the judge's decision conflicts with a 1987 <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruling that allowed police without a warrant to enter fenced-in _ but unwooded _ property and look into a barn located about 60 yards from a ranch house. The justices ruled in that case that the barn was not part of the homeowner's `` curtilage'' _ the area of land occupied by a dwelling, its yard and other nearby buildings that are protected against warrantless searches by the Constitution's Fourth Amendment. The high court in 1984 reaffirmed a long-standing legal doctrine that police may enter and search even fenced-in `` open fields'' without a court warrant. The case acted on today is <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION> vs. Wing, 89-381.
