<HEAD>GE Goes On Trial On Defense Fraud Charges</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE LINDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 For the second time in four years, <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> went to court today to face charges of defrauding the <ORGANIZATION> defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> department </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> and two employees were accused of cheating the Pentagon of $ 10 million. The company, the country's second-largest defense contractor, faces a fine of $ 71.9 million if convicted. Since the 321-count indictment was returned in November, <ORGANIZATION> GE </ORGANIZATION> consistently denied shortchanging the government in a $ 270 million contract to make a battlefield computer system. The company has acknowledged, however, that an internal investigation uncovered discrepancies totaling $ 3.69 million. GE refunded that money before the indictment was handed up in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Court. <PERSON> Clayton </PERSON> <PERSON> Undercoffler </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> GE </ORGANIZATION> attorney, said the trial is expected to last at least two months. According to the Pentagon, officials at a <ORGANIZATION> GE </ORGANIZATION> subsidiary, <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Techinical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, based in suburban King of <LOCATION> Prussia </LOCATION>, padded costs and failed to notify the Pentagon of savings negotiated with subcontractors. In May 1985, the company pleaded guilty to illegally claiming $ 800,000 in cost overruns on Minuteman intercontinental ballistic missiles and paid a $ 1.04 million fine. GE does approximately $ 6 billion annually in <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> business that ranges from jet engines and electronic warfare equipment to highly classified strategic work. Jury selection began this m