<HEAD>Court Using Chicago Case to Consider Expanding Search Powers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today agreed to use a <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> drug prosecution to consider expanding police search powers. The justices said they will hear arguments that police, acting without a warrant, should be allowed to use evidence seized after they were allowed into a man's apartment by his girlfriend. The defendant, <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Rodriguez </PERSON>, was arrested on July 26, 1985, on charges he possessed cocaine and marijuana with intent to distribute the drugs. Police said the drugs and drug paraphernalia were in plain view at <PERSON> Rodriguez </PERSON>'s apartment. <PERSON> Gale </PERSON> <PERSON> Fisher </PERSON>, who lived with <PERSON> Rodriguez </PERSON> part-time, summoned police to her mother's home on July 26. She told them <PERSON> Rodriguez </PERSON> had beaten her at the couple's apartment and she wanted to make a complaint. The police then accompanied her to <PERSON> Rodriguez </PERSON>'s apartment and she opened the door with a key. She later testified that she took the key from <PERSON> Rodriguez </PERSON>'s dresser after the two argued earlier that day. An <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> appeals court said police violated the defendant's rights because Ms. <PERSON> Fisher </PERSON> lacked authority to let the police into the apartment Police may not enter and search a home without a warrant `` if the party who consented to the entry had apparent authority to do so but lacked actual authority,'' the state appeals court said. The appeals court noted that Ms. <PERSON> Fisher </PERSON>'s name was not on the apartment lease and she did not help pay the rent. Also, the state court said, she was an infrequent visitor and did not have access to the apartment when <PERSON> Rodriguez </PERSON> was not there. She also had moved her clothes and children to her mother's home, the state court noted. `` All of these factors indicate that <PERSON> Fisher </PERSON> did not have the common authority over the defendant's apartment that was necessary to make her consent to enter valid,'' the state court added. The <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> attorney general's office, in appealing to the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, said police acted in good faith when they relied on Ms. <PERSON> Fisher </PERSON>'s `` apparent authority to permit entry into the home.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in 1974 ruled that when one occupant of a home consents to a search of the premises, evidence police find may be used against another occupant. The case is <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> vs. <PERSON> Rodriguez </PERSON>, 88-2018.
