<HEAD>Court Will Review Pension Ruling</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts grafs 5-19, In other action, with other cases.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today agreed to review a ruling government lawyers say threatens the federal program protecting the pensions of 30 million American workers. The justices said they will decide what authority the <ORGANIZATION> Pension </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Benefit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guaranty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corporation </ORGANIZATION>, a federal agency, has to order employers to restore terminated pension plans. A federal appeals court limited such authority by setting aside the agency's order that <ORGANIZATION> LTV </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and its subsidiary, <ORGANIZATION> LTV </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, restore three pension plans with unfunded liabilities of $ 2.3 billion. The appeal acted on today said the ruling, if not overturned, could make the agency `` an open-ended source of industry bailouts'' and `` could lead to a financial crisis similar to that currently facing'' the government's insurance program for the savings and loan industry. In other action, the court: _ Turned away an appeal by a <LOCATION> Nebraska </LOCATION> state agency that wants to test its employees for AIDS. The court, without comment, let stand rulings that blocked the <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nebraska </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> from imposing mandatory blood testing of employees who come into direct contact with the mentally retarded people the agency serves. _ Agreed to use a <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> drug prosecution to consider expanding police search powers. The justices said they will hear arguments that police, acting without a warrant, should be allowed to use evidence seized after they were allowed into a man's apartment by his girlfriend. _ Barred a lawsuit against the <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Science </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> church </ORGANIZATION> in the death of a 15-month-old <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> boy who died of meningitis. The justices, without comment, let stand a ruling that a suit against the church and its members over faith healing would violate their religious freedom. _ Rejected an appeal by an <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Humanist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> member who says he should have as much right as an ordained minister to perform marriage ceremonies. The court, without comment, refused to hear arguments that a <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> law favoring ministers violates religious freedom and the constitutionally required separation of church and state. _ Refused to hear appeals by three drug manufacturers fighting lawsuits over the effects of DES, a drug once used by pregnant women to prevent miscarriages. The court, without comment, left intact a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> ruling aimed at forcing all manufacturers of the drug to share in paying damages for injuries allegedly caused by DES. _ Turned away an appeal by a former <ORGANIZATION> Beech-Nut </ORGANIZATION> executiv e fighting his conviction for selling adulterated apple juice. The court, without comment, left intact <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lavery </PERSON>'s sentence of a year and a day in prison and a $ 100,000 fine _ Turned down an appeal by <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Earl </PERSON> <PERSON> Ray </PERSON>, who is serving a 99-year prison sentence for the assassination of the Rev. <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Luther </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr </PERSON>. The court, without comment, let stand a ruling that <PERSON> Ray </PERSON>'s rights were not violated 20 years ago when he pleaded guilty to first-degree murder. The <ORGANIZATION> Pension </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Benefit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guaranty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corporation </ORGANIZATION>, modeled after the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Deposit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Savings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, is wholly owned by the federal government. Its board of directors is comprised of the secretaries of labor, treasury and commerce. The agency protects the pension benefits of the 30 million Americans who participate in single-employer defined benefit pension plans. When a pension plan is ended with insufficient money to satisfy promised benefits, the federal agency becomes the pension plan's trustee, taking over its assets and liabilities The agency then pays all benefits workers had earned as of the date the pension plan ended. In fiscal year 1988, the <ORGANIZATION> Pension </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Benefit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guaranty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corporation </ORGANIZATION> paid $ 324.7 million in insured benefits to 113,000 retirees who participated in 1,476 terminated pension plans. The cost of the pension insurance is paid primarily by employers with active pension plans, and by employers who terminate underfunded pension plans. The agency has money problems of its own. In its most recent annual report, the <ORGANIZATION> PBGC </ORGANIZATION> listed liabilities of $ 4 billion and assets of $ 2.4 billion. The Dallas-based <ORGANIZATION> LTV </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> LTV </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION>, after filing for reorganization under federal bankruptcy law in 1986, advised the <ORGANIZATION> PBGC </ORGANIZATION> that they could not and would not fund the three pension plans they sponsored. The plans, which have about 100,000 participants, were terminated in 1987. In a deal with the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steelworkers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> union, however, <ORGANIZATION> LTV </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION> agreed to what government lawyers contend is a `` follow-on'' arrangement. Under it, <ORGANIZATION> LTV </ORGANIZATION> agreed to make up any benefits lost to employees because of the pension plans' termination _ those benefits not covered by the federal pension insurance program The result: employees continued to receive the same benefits they did before the plans were terminated, and payment of unfunded pension liabilities was shifted to the <ORGANIZATION> PBGC </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> LTV </ORGANIZATION> was responsible for $ 75 million in annual supplemental retirement benefits, and the federal agency was making good on some $ 400 million in annual obligations to <ORGANIZATION> LTV </ORGANIZATION> pensioners. The <ORGANIZATION> PBGC </ORGANIZATION> contends such arrangements are abusive, and the agency ordered <ORGANIZATION> LTV </ORGANIZATION> to reassume responsibility for the three pension plans. When <ORGANIZATION> LTV </ORGANIZATION> refused, the agency sought to enforce its order in federal court. A federal judge threw out the <ORGANIZATION> PBGC </ORGANIZATION>'s order for restoration of the pension plans, and the 2nd <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> upheld that ruling last May 12. Federal law `` reveals no indication that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> intended the establishment of successive benefit plans to be a ground for restoration,'' the appeals court ruled. It also said the <ORGANIZATION> PBGC </ORGANIZATION>'s action was `` arbitrary and capricious'' because it failed to consider the goals of federal bankruptcy and labor laws when issuing its restoration order. The <ORGANIZATION> PBGC </ORGANIZATION> then sought <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> review, contending that the 2nd Circuit court's ruling `` places the pension insurance program in serious financial jeopardy'' and ignores what <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> attempted to achieve in passing the Employee Retirement Income Security Act of 1974 -LRB- ERISA -RRB-. `` Other companies will follow <ORGANIZATION> LTV </ORGANIZATION>'s example and use pension insurance as a subsidy to reduce costs and gain a competitive edge,'' the appeal said. <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> lawyers sided with the <ORGANIZATION> PBGC </ORGANIZATION>, telling the high court, `` The <ORGANIZATION> PBGC </ORGANIZATION> has reasonably concluded that restoration is an appropriate response to the adoption of abusive follow-on plans.'' They said the appeals court ruling `` threatens to undermine ... a program already seriously in debt.'' But lawyers for <ORGANIZATION> LTV </ORGANIZATION> said <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> `` specifically rejected proposed prohibitions on follow-on plans'' when substantially amending ERISA in 1987. The case is <ORGANIZATION> PBGC </ORGANIZATION> vs. <ORGANIZATION> LTV </ORGANIZATION>, 89-390.
