</TEXT>
<HEAD>EDS: Top 10 grafs new with oral arguments; picks up 6th graf pvs,
Clark ordered.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY MASSEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> was urged today to strike down a federal judge's order doubling local property taxes to pay for school desegregation in <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mo </LOCATION>. Calling the judge's 1987 order `` taxation without representation,'' an attorney for the state of <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION>, <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bartow </PERSON> <PERSON> Farr </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>, argued that federal courts lack the power to order higher taxes even to correct a constitutional violation such as racial discrimination in schools. `` There is no power to tax, period,'' <PERSON> Farr </PERSON> told the justices in oral arguments. The state asked the high court to overturn a decision by the 8th <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> that upheld the property tax increase ordered by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Russell </PERSON> <PERSON> Clark </PERSON>. Lawyers for both sides spent perhaps a third of the 60-minute argument session answering questions by several of the justices about a possible procedural flaw that could preclude any constitutional ruling in the case. The school district and a group of school children, who brought the original desegregation case in 1977, urged the court to uphold the tax decision. The district also maintained that the state waited too long to file a <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> appeal, rendering it unnecessary for the justices to address the tax issue. <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> <PERSON> Snyder </PERSON>, an attorney for the district, contended that state property tax law and local voters must not be allowed to frustrate the constitutional rights of <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>'s minority schoolchildren to an equal educational opportunity. <PERSON> Snyder </PERSON> said it was `` dangerously wrong'' to assume that federal courts lack powers to implement their orders to correct constitutional violations. The courts, he said, `` have the powers and have the duty to use their equitable discretion'' to remedy such wrongs as racial segregation in schools. The court is expected to issue a decision in the case by next July. Legal scholars and education officials say the court's decision could shape future school desegregation plans across the country and define the federal courts' power to remedy constitutional violations involving issues from prison overcrowding to fair housing. <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> ordered the tax increase in September 1987 after the local school district was unable to pay its share of a more than $ 400 million desegregation plan he had approved for capital improvements in buildings and establishment of special `` magnet'' schools. State law says local property taxes may be raised only with voters' approval, and in some instances only with a two-thirds majority. District voters had not approved a levy increase since 1969, with four tax increase proposals rejected in 1986 and 1987 to finance the desegregation plan. In addition to doubling the property tax, <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> imposed an income tax surcharge on those people living or working in the school district. The appeals court struck down the income surcharge in August 1988, but upheld the district court's authority to order an increase in the property tax. However, the appeals court modified the procedure for imposing the higher tax levy. The appeals court found that state law had effectively prevented the school district from levying the necessary taxes to pay for the desegregation plan. It upheld <PERSON> Clark </PERSON>'s order as one that `` set aside levy limitations,'' and empowered the elected local school board to set the needed tax levels within certain limits.
