<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, in a case likely to affect other multi-state agencies, agreed today to decide whether a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York-New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> transportation authority may be sued in federal court. The justices said they would hear arguments by the <ORGANIZATION> Port </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authority </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> seeking to kill lawsuits by two employees. The authority was created in 1921 in a Congress-approved compact between the two states. It operates airports, trains linking <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> and other transportation facilities. The authority is run by 12 commissioners, six each appointed by the governors of the respective states. The governors also have veto power over actions by the commissioners. The 2nd U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> based in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> ruled in April that <ORGANIZATION> Port </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authority </ORGANIZATION> employees <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Foster </PERSON> and <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Feeney </PERSON> may sue the agency in federal court. The appeals court said the 11th Amendment to the Constitution shielding states from federal court suits does not apply to the interstate agency. The 2nd Circuit court said the authority may be sued for money damages largely because any judgment it would be forced to pay would come from its revenues rather than the taxpayer-supported treasuries of the two states. `` We believe that this insulation of state treasuries from the liabilities of the <ORGANIZATION> Port </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authority </ORGANIZATION> outweighs both the methods of -LRB- commisioner -RRB- appointment and gubernatorial veto,'' the appeals court said. The appeals court invited the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> to review the ruling, noting that the Philadelphia-based 3rd U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> has issued a conflicting ruling on the authority's immunity from suit The 2nd Circuit court said the 3rd Circuit was in error in concluding that the taxpayers of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> could be forced to pay damages if a suit depleted the agency's resources. <PERSON> Feeney </PERSON> is seeking $ 3 million for injuries he suffered while working at a maintenance shop run by the authority in 1986. The case is <ORGANIZATION> Port </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authority </ORGANIZATION> vs. <PERSON> Feeney </PERSON>, 89-386.
