 A socially active inner-city <PERSON> Episcopal </PERSON> priest who sued his diocese and its bishop lied when he accused them of conspiring to control his parish's money, a church panel concluded today. In the first ecclesiastical trial ever held in the <LOCATION> Newark </LOCATION> diocese, the five priests on the panel unanimously recommended that the Rev. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Swanson </PERSON> be suspended for two years from ministerial or administrative involvement in the church. Bishop <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Spong </PERSON> must still approve the recommendation, and <PERSON> Swanson </PERSON>'s attorney said he would appeal. <PERSON> Swanson </PERSON>, who filed the lawsuit in 1988 accusing <PERSON> Spong </PERSON> and the diocese of engaging in a conspiracy against his tiny <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> parish, did not show any emotion as the recommendation was read. The lawsuit was dismissed from <ORGANIZATION> Superior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> on the grounds it was a church matter, but <PERSON> Swanson </PERSON> is appealing that decision. About 20 <ORGANIZATION> Ascencion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> parishioners, who had gathered at diocesean headquarters for the verdict, appeared stunned but remained quiet. <PERSON> Swanson </PERSON>, 56, a <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> native, has headed the church in a poverty-stricken <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> neighborhood for 12 years. <PERSON> Teresa </PERSON> <PERSON> Russell </PERSON>, a parishioner for eight years, said Sunday that <PERSON> Swanson </PERSON> had drawn her back into the Episcopal church with social activism and efforts to make religion relevant to current problems. <PERSON> Swanson </PERSON> wore a button at today's announcement of the verdict urging <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> to