<HEAD>Engineers Back at Work on Arms Programs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A handful of Chinese engineers in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to aid a $ 600 million arms sale to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> have returned to work on the program, but the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Monday that weapons deliveries suspended by President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> in June have not resumed. Officials, responding to a report in the <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION>, stressed that <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> had suspended shipments _ not ended them _ after the <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> government cracked down on pro-democracy demonstrators. The Chinese engineers, who apparently did not leave the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> over the summer, returned during the last few weeks to the Grumman factory in <LOCATION> Bethpage </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, `` to provide technical support which will enable <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> work to continue during the suspension,'' a <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> official said. The main parts of the deal with <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> are a program to improve avionics on F-8 jets and the manufacture of torpedos, radar and artillery ammunition. `` In view of the long-term interest of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, it has always been the president's intention to suspend _ not terminate _ US-People's <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> FMS -LRB- foreign military sales -RRB- programs, with the hope that circumstances would permit a resumption of normal relations,'' said the official, who spoke on condition of anonymity. Still, the official added: `` There are no deliveries. The president's decision remains in effect.'' The sanctions imposed by <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> were considered inadequate by several members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> who called for harsher measures as an expression of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> human rights convictions. The bloody June 4 crackdown on students in <LOCATION> Tiananmen </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Square </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> was seen by millions of Americans on television, contributing to public criticism here of the Communist government as it reversed a moderating trend. But <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and Secretary of State <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> emphasized then that maintaining strong ties with <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> was in the strategic interest of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Two other sanctions, apart from a halt to weapons deliveries, have been reversed or watered down since June. The president's ban on the visit of high-level <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> did not preclude <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> from meeting with <PERSON> Qian </PERSON> <PERSON> Qichen </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> foreign minister, at a conference on <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> at the end of July. Also, dependents of American diplomats who were evacuated from the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> consulates returned weeks later. On Monday, former President <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON>, the most prominent American to visit <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> since the military crackdown, called on the two nations to restore good relations and urged Chinese leaders to shun the `` backwater of oppression and stagnation'' and respect the yearnings of their people. White House spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> spoke with <PERSON> Bus