<HEAD>Brzezinski: Soviets Should Take Responsibility for Katyn Massacre</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KATYN, U.S.S.R. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Former <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> National Security Adviser <PERSON> Zbigniew </PERSON> <PERSON> Brzezinski </PERSON> visited the site where more than 4,300 Polish officers were slain in World War II, and he called on the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> to take responsibility for the massacre. At the same time of <PERSON> Brzezinski </PERSON>'s visit to the memorial to the officers in the <LOCATION> Katyn </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Forest </LOCATION>, 17 miles south of the <LOCATION> Byelorussian </LOCATION> city of <LOCATION> Smolensk </LOCATION>, a group of more than 400 Polish relatives of the dead arrived for a commemorative Mass. `` It's purely a coincidence,'' <PERSON> Brzezinski </PERSON> said when asked if he knew the Polish group was coming. He was visiting <LOCATION> Katyn </LOCATION> while in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> to participate in an East-West conference. A monument at the site pays tribute to the `` victims of Fascism _ Polish officers shot by the <ORGANIZATION> Nazis </ORGANIZATION> in 1941.'' However, most Poles and Western historians believe the officers, the cream of the Polish intelligentsia, were killed by the <ORGANIZATION> NKVD </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>'s secret police, in 1940 after they were deported to <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> following the outbreak of World War II. The <ORGANIZATION> Nazis </ORGANIZATION> discovered the graves in 1943 and blamed the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, but the Soviets said the <ORGANIZATION> Nazis </ORGANIZATION> had murdered the men in 1941, during the German army's march on <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. `` We owe it to the families of the victims to say that this was done by <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> and the <ORGANIZATION> NKVD </ORGANIZATION>,'' <PERSON> Brzezinski </PERSON> said. `` These victims represented a community of suffering shared by the Polish and Soviet people ... the truth of what happened should be a point of reconciliation for both countries,'' he said. A Soviet-Polish historical commission set up by President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> and Polish leader Gen. <PERSON> Wojciech </PERSON> <PERSON> Jaruzelski </PERSON> to clear up historical `` blank spots'' has yet to deliver a final verdict on the controversy, which for Poles remains their most painful wartime memory. Soviet Foreign Minister <PERSON> Eduard </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> said in <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> last week that the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> was still conducting investigations and searching for documents, but that it was interested in finding `` the truth.'' Many Poles hope the matter will be cleared up by the time Prime Minister <PERSON> Tadeusz </PERSON> <PERSON> Mazowiecki </PERSON> makes his first visit to <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> in November. The Polish side pre-empted a joint declaration on responsibility in August when the Polish head of the commission, <PERSON> Jarema </PERSON> <PERSON> Macizewski </PERSON>, said that documents show the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> was responsible. <PERSON> Brzezinski </PERSON>, known for his staunch anti-communist views, indicated he believed the Soviets would ultimately change their version of the massacre. `` The fact that the Soviet government has enabled me to be here _ and the Soviets know my views _ is symbolic of the breach with Stalinism that perestroika represents,'' <PERSON> Brzezinski </PERSON> said, referring to <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s political and economic reform program. Until the Solidarity trade union was born in 1980-81, <LOCATION> Katyn </LOCATION> was officially a taboo subject in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>. But a group calling itself the Families of <LOCATION> Katyn </LOCATION> Victims has thousands of members throughout <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>. More than 400 arrived in <LOCATION> Smolensk </LOCATION> on the first special train organized by the Polish and Soviet tourist agencies. It was the largest group of Poles ever to visit <LOCATION> Katyn </LOCATION> since Soviet authorities began allowing Poles to visit in groups about one year ago. `` We never thought we would be able to come here,'' said <PERSON> Agnieszka </PERSON> <PERSON> Stawowczyk </PERSON>, whose father was killed at <LOCATION> Katyn </LOCATION>. Three priests celebrated Mass in front of a wooden cross, which was surrounded by wreaths and Solidarity banners.
