<HEAD>Witness: People `Were Just Running in the Air'</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to UPDATE county wants to rebuild bridge;
picks up 9th graf pvs: `If we ...</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LR2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES JEFFERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HEBER SPRINGS, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A local official said today he is considering rebuilding a bridge that collapsed, plunging five people to their deaths, even though he has not obtained a professional opinion about the tragedy's cause. The dead were among more than 30 people who witnesses said were rocking the bridge back and forth just before it collapsed, spilling the group into the <LOCATION> Little </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Red </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>. Officials have speculated that the swinging motion put tension on the cables supporting the 77-year-old wood-decked structure and contributed to the collapse. People `` were just running in the air,'' said <PERSON> Jennifer </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, who was driving to her nearby home when she saw the accident. Of the 18 people injured, seven remained hospitalized today, with conditions ranging from satisfactory to serious, authorities said. The dead, who had gathered in a nearby town for a church meeting, included three children. County officials as yet have not had an expert test the debris to determine what happened. County Judge <PERSON> Harvey </PERSON> <PERSON> Adcock </PERSON> said today that he would seek a historic preservation grant or some other funds to aid in rebuilding the bridge, which has been on the National Register of Historic Places since 1986. In <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION>, the county judge has no judicial power, but is chief administrator of county government. `` Everybody feels a great sense of loss now that it's gone,'' <PERSON> Adcock </PERSON> said. He said a state police investigator had looked at the site with county officers, but <PERSON> Adcock </PERSON> did n't know whether the officer was an engineer. The judge said he `` had the name and address of a private engineer that will probably look at it.'' A state Highway and <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> engineer and an engineer from the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZAT