<TEXT>
 A launch team and five astronauts successfully concluded a practice countdown Monday for a November launch of the space shuttle Discovery, which will carry a secret military payload. The exercise, which began Sunday, covered the final 24 hours of an actual count and provided training for both ground controllers and the astronauts, who were in the shuttle cockpit for the final two hours. <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Diller </PERSON> said the exercise went well. In honor of Halloween, the astronauts wore costume hats and carried artificial jack-o' - lanterns as they arrived at the launch pad in their bulky orange Some pad workers wore masks for the occasion. Discovery is scheduled to be launched Nov. 20 on the fifth of 32 shuttle flights assigned entirely to the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. For security reasons, officials will not disclose the nature of the cargo or what experiments the space crew plans. Earlier military missions have deployed reconnaissance and intelligence-gathering satellites. Discovery's crew members are <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> Col. <PERSON> Frederick </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gregory </PERSON>, the first black astronaut named to command a space shuttle mission; <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> Col. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Blaha </PERSON>, the pilot; and three mission specialists, <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> Capt. <PERSON> Manley </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>; <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Story </PERSON> <PERSON> Musgrave </PERSON>; and <PERSON> Kathryn </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Thornton </PERSON>. <PERSON> Blaha </PERSON> replaced <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> Rear Adm. <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Griggs </PERSON>, who was ki