<HEAD>Maryland Man Loses Wedding Appeal</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Scotus Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> on Monday rejected the appeal of a member of a secular group who argued that he should have the same right to perform marriages as does a priest or rabbi. <PERSON> Roy </PERSON> <PERSON> Torcaso </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Wheaton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Md. </LOCATION>, won an important victory in 1971, when the high court held that <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> violated his rights by barring him from becoming a state-commissioned notary public because he refused to declare a belief in God. In the current case, the justices, without comment, refused to disturb a <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> law favoring ordained ministers in officiating at weddings. The court rejected <PERSON> Torcaso </PERSON>'s arguments that the law violates religious freedom and separation of church and state. He contended that his constitutional rights are being denied because he is a counselor with the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Humanist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, an educational and philosophical organization. <PERSON> Torcaso </PERSON> said he is similar to a priest, minister or rabbi and should have comparable rights. He has been allowed to officiate at weddings in other states, he said. However, he was rejected in 1988 when he applied to <LOCATION> Prince </LOCATION> <LOCATION> William </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, to perform weddings there. A <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> judge refused to overturn the county clerk's rejection Lawyers with the <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> attorney general's office said the state law requires a $ 500 bond by anyone who is not an ordained minister and wants to officiate at a wedding. Ministers are exempt from posting the bond because `` ordination creates a presumption that the officiant is trustworthy and responsible,'' lawyers for the state said. <PERSON> Torcaso </PERSON> said he would have been barred under <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> law from performing the wedding even if he posted the bond. The bond requirement, he said, applies only to judges or others who reside in the county where they seek to perform the marriage. <PERSON> Torcaso </PERSON> said other states have similar laws, but that they more liberally create exemptions that allow non-ministers to officiate at weddings. The Constitution `` prohibits states from establishing religious qualifications for persons who perform state functions,'' his appeal said. `` States can not impose religious affiliation and belief requirements upon persons who solemnize marriages.'' The case is <PERSON> Torcaso </PERSON> vs. <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>, 89-375.
