<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Four people shouting `` burn, baby, burn,'' torched three <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> flags on the central steps of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Capitol today in a bid to test the new federal law protecting the national symbol from desecration. All four demonstrators were arrested by Capitol police. `` We defy your law,'' said <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Kent </PERSON>, a spokeswoman for the flag burners, reading from a prepared statement. `` We challenge you Arrest us. Test your statute. Take it back to the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> and try once again to claim it is all consistent with your constitutional standards of free speech.'' The law, which President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> allowed to take force without his signature, went into effect at midnight on Friday. The flag-burning demonstration had been scheduled for noon on the marble plaza of the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>. Organizers announced it had been moved and led photographers and television cameras to the Capitol steps. One demonstrator produced a flag and ripped it. Two policemen tore the pieces of the flag from his hands. Behind them another man produced a flag and set it afire. Two other flags also were set ablaze as the four demonstrators chanted, `` Burn, baby, burn.'' `` Another shouted: `` Stop the fascist flag law. Oppose it.'' Policemen first attempted to extinguish the flames by stamping on the flags, them aimed fire extinguishers at the burning remnants, dousing them in a chemical stream and shrouding the scene in white smoke. Police spokesman <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Nichols </PERSON> said the four were identified as <PERSON> Shawn </PERSON> <PERSON> Eichner </PERSON>, 24, of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>; <PERSON> Gregory </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, 33, of <LOCATION> Richmond </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ind </LOCATION>.; <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Blalock </PERSON>, 39, of <LOCATION> Johnstown </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> <PERSON> Tyler </PERSON>, 24, of <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. The four were charged with violating the Flag Protection Act of 1989, demonstrating without a permit and diorderly conduct, <PERSON> Nichols </PERSON> said. Violation of the flag statute provides a maximum penalty of one year in jail and a $ 1,000 fine. The other two charges are misdemeanors and carry respective maximum penalties of $ 300 and 90 days in jail and $ 250 and 90 days in jail.
