<HEAD>National Safety Council Offers Halloween Safety Tips</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Tampered Treats, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> has issued the following guidelines for parents and children at Halloween: _ Children's costumes should be large enough so that warm clothing can be worn underneath, yet short enough so that a child wo n't trip. Avoid shoes that make walking difficult. _ For visibility, use light colors in costumes and attach reflective tape to them. Have children use reflective treat bags. _ Attach a small child's name, address and phone number inside his sleeve in case he gets lost. But do n't openly display the personal information on the child's costume. _ Masks can obscure a child's vision. Use non-toxic makeup instead. _ Be sure children travel only in familiar neighborhoods and that they do n't enter strangers' homes. They should follow a designated travel route with a definite return time and not trick-or-treat past dark. Give them coins to call home if any problems arise. _ Remind children not to eat any treat before it's been inspected by a parent. _ Teach children pedestrian safety. _ Motorists should slow down in residential areas and watch for children.
