<BYLINE>By DAVID FOSTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A World Series victory gave earthquake-battered <ORGANIZATION> Oakland </ORGANIZATION> something to celebrate today, and thousands of hedonistic Halloween partyers helped <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> return `` to abnormal.'' `` A little happiness will help us bounce back,'' baseball fan <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Mead </PERSON> said after the <ORGANIZATION> Oakland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Athletics </ORGANIZATION> beat the <ORGANIZATION> San </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Francisco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Giants </ORGANIZATION> 9-6 Saturday night to sweep the Bay Bridge World Series. About 300 A's fans showed up for a victory rally held this morning in downtown <ORGANIZATION> Oakland </ORGANIZATION>'s Jack London Square. A parade was originally planned but the route down Broadway would have passed several quake-damaged buildings and organizers did not want to tax an already strained police department. The rally, featuring a moment of silence for quake victims, was too subdued for some fans. `` I prefer a parade, but we'll take anything we can get,'' said <PERSON> Theresa </PERSON> <PERSON> Held </PERSON>, whose childhood home in <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Cruz </LOCATION> was destroyed by the quake. `` People need to get back on with everything, they should n't dwell on the quake. I thought that's why they let the series continue in the first place.'' The A's opted for the rally after winning the series and avoided the traditional champagne-spray locker room festivities out of respect for the quake victims. The celebration was unabashed at this weekend's 10th annual Exotic Erotic Ball in at the <ORGANIZATION> Concourse </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exhibition </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>, where the popular attire was lace, leather, chains and whips or next to nothing. `` The scare's over with. People want to get b