lose to heaven'' because rent on a new place would be too high. Crews labored to replace gas lines in a system that once served 5,700 customers. Water and electricity were restored, but residents were asked to limit use of appliances to avoid straining the system. `` There's only one guy out of 16 people staying here,'' psychologist <PERSON> Lori </PERSON> <PERSON> Rifkin </PERSON> said as friends lugged boxes to her car. `` I'm not staying here,'' she said, pointing to buckled concrete and building cracks. Seventy miles to the south, hundreds of poor people left homeless by the quake marched through <LOCATION> Watsonville </LOCATION> on Sunday to demand that low-income housing be built to replace lost homes. City Manager <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Radin </PERSON> said the city does not have the money to build replacement housing. After the two-hour march, <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Farm </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> leader <PERSON> Cesar </PERSON> <PERSON> Chavez </PERSON> addressed several hundred people on a hill overlooking a park where the homeless have been living in tents. `` We know that as soon as the publicity about the quake ends that you could be abandoned. We do n't want to let that happen,'' <PERSON> Chavez </PERSON> said.
