<HEAD>Supreme Court Hears Arguments on Kansas City Desegregation Case</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Scotus Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY MASSEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, in a case closely watched by civil rights groups, was asked Monday to decide whether federal courts can order higher taxes to finance school desegregation. The state of <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> urged the justices to invalidate a federal judge's 1987 order that doubled local property taxes in <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, saying it was `` taxation without representation.'' <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bartow </PERSON> <PERSON> Farr </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>, an attorney for the state, argued that courts lack the power to impose or authorize higher taxes even to correct a constitutional violation such as racial discrimination in schools. `` There is no power to tax, period,'' <PERSON> Farr </PERSON> told the justices. Although constitutional issues dominated the 60-minute session, lawyers for both sides answered questions by several justices about a possible procedural flaw that could preclude a ruling on the tax issue in the case. The school district and parents of a group of school children, who brought the original desegregation case in 1977, contend the state waited too long to file a <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> appeal. The school district asked the court to affirm a decision by the 8th <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> upholding the property tax increase ordered by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Russell </PERSON> <PERSON> Clark </PERSON>. The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> is expected to issue a decision in the case by next July. <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> <PERSON> Snyder </PERSON>, the school district's attorney, said it would be `` dangerously wrong'' to deny federal courts the broad powers needed to implement their orders to correct constitutional violations. Striking down the tax order, he contended, would permit state property tax law and local voters to frustrate the constitutional rights of <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>'s minority schoolchildren to an equal educational opportunity. Federal courts, <PERSON> Snyder </PERSON> argued, `` have the powers and have the duty to use their equitable discretion'' to remedy constitutional wrongs. Several justices questioned whether there were any limits on the powers of the federal courts to correct racial segregation in schools. At one point, Justice <PERSON> Antonin </PERSON> <PERSON> Scalia </PERSON> asked if a court could order higher taxes to `` gold plate all the schools?'' <PERSON> Snyder </PERSON> discounted the justice's example but said a court's remedy to constitutional violations was limited to what was `` feasible and practicable. Justice <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> described the judge's tax order as a `` drastic remedy'' and questioned whether the district court should have made an `` explicit finding'' that higher taxes were the only reasonable solution. The state, in response to questions by Justice <PERSON> Sandra </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON>, maintained that the judge had failed to consider other options, such as scaling back the desegregation plan. One alternative opposed by the state, <PERSON> Farr </PERSON> conceded, was to require the state of <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> to pay all of the costs. <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> ordered the tax increase in September 1987 after the local school district was unable to pay its share of a $ 400 million desegregation plan he had approved for capital improvements in buildings and establishment of special `` magnet'' schools. State law says local property taxes can be raised only with voters' approval, and in some instances only with a two-thirds majority. District voters had not approved a levy increase since 1969, with four tax increase proposals rejected in 1986 and 1987 to finance the desegregation plan. The appeals court, in August 1988, upheld the district court's authority to order an increase in the property tax but changed the procedure for imposing the higher tax levy in the future
