<SECOND>AM-Hungary,0578</SECOND>
<HEAD>Parliament Passes Laws on Amnesty, Creates State Auditor's Office</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE JAHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Parliament on Monday approved legislation granting amnesty to many people convicted of crimes punishable by less than three years in prison, and it created an office to control government and party finances. The laws, to take effect in November, were among several items on the agenda on the opening day of the legislature's first session since it rewrote the communist constitution to reflect democratic ideals. <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>'s rapidly evolving reform course has put it in the vanguard of democratic change within the Soviet bloc, along with <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, the first <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact nation with a government not dominated by the communists. At its last sitting, which ended Oct. 20, <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> adopted a series of laws and constitutional amendements establishing the legal framework for the first multiparty elections since the now defunct Communist party consolidated power in 1948. The <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> _ formally known as the <ORGANIZATION> Hungarian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ' </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> _ dissolved itself Oct. 7 at a historic congress that gave birth to its successor, the <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. The new party, which professes democratic ideals, retains political control, but its leaders have promised to hand over power if defeated at the polls next year. In another major move to break with the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> past, acting President <PERSON> Matyas </PERSON> <PERSON> Szueroes </PERSON> proclaimed the existence of the Republic of <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> Oct. 23, the 33rd anniversary of the 1956 anti-Stalinist revolt. The proclamation, which formally terminated the Communist-created People's Republic of <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>, was cheered by more than 100,000 Hungarians. The amnesty law applies to those serving terms of three years or less who are in the following categories: pregnant women, women with children under 14 living with them, women over 55 and men over 60, and those suffering from terminal illness. The terms are halved for those in these categories serving sentences exceding three years. The amnesty does not apply to those facing or serving sentences for violent or sexual crimes. Creation of an auditor's office was meant to re-establish impartial control over government and party spending which was effectively abolished after the communists took over. The office, which also has jurisdiction over the finances of state enterprises, is responsible to <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>. The number of legislators present to vote on the two bills differed, accounting for the different totals. Tuesday's agenda included a decision on when and how to chose a president, whose responsibilities include command of the armed forces and other major tasks. The newly created post was originally to be filled Nov. 26 by popular vote, but two opposition groups have collected more than 100,000 opposing signatures, enough to force a plebiscite on the issue. The groups _ the <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Free </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democrats </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Young </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democrats </ORGANIZATION> _ say the early date favors <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> candidate <PERSON> Imre </PERSON> <PERSON> Pozsgay </PERSON> because it does n't give the opposition enough time to organize and make their candidates well known. In addition, legislators planned Tuesday to discuss and vote on government proposals on a suspended <LOCATION> Danube </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> hydroelectric project with <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>, a <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact ally increasingly at odds with <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> over its reforms. In declaring a moratorium in May on the Gabcikovo-Nagymaros dam project, <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> expressed concern about potential enviromental damage. <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION> has said it will continue construction and will demand compensation if work is permanently suspended by the Hungarians.
