<HEAD>Bush Sending Three Cabinet Members to Poland</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said Monday he will send three Cabinet members and his chief economic adviser to <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> to help its non-communist government develop a strategy for overhauling the country's battered economy. `` <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s struggle has always been <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s struggle,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said. `` Maybe that's why it seems that Polish hearts and <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> hearts beat as one.'' The delegation named by <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> will include government, business, labor and academic officials. It will be led by <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Clayton </PERSON> <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Mosbacher </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> and <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Boskin </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Advisers </ORGANIZATION>. They will depart <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> on Nov. 29 and return on Dec. 2. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> announced their selection in a Rose Garden ceremony marking the end of October as Polish American heritage month. Saluting <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> for forming a non-communist government, the first in <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> in more than 40 years, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said, `` <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> herself has moved toward a new beginning.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said that in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> and elsewhere, `` the tide toward oppression is running out. The tide toward liberty is running in. `` The voice of freedom is the voice of <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, and the voice of <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> is the voice of tomorrow.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has proposed a $ 400 million, multiyear aid program for <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, but congressional Democrats are pushing for a package of more than $ 1 billion. Discussing the mission with reporters following the president's announcement, <PERSON> Mosbacher </PERSON> said that the travel group would be working to speed up the process of getting assistance to <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> `` They obviously have some serious fiscal and financial problems. We just want to get as much in place as quickly as possible,'' <PERSON> Mosbacher </PERSON> said, noting that winter is approaching. Among those accompanying the Cabinet officials will be <ORGANIZATION> AFL-CIO </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Lane </PERSON> <PERSON> Kirkland </PERSON> and various chief operating officers from American companies, <PERSON> Mosbacher </PERSON> said. The business executives would be exploring the possibility of starting joint ventures in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, he said. `` We need a combination of people who have the expertise, people who have the equipment, people who have the money and the know-how,'' said <PERSON> Mosbacher </PERSON>.
