<HEAD>Aquino Says Boycott of Moslem Autonomy Referendum a Mistake</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MLA4</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ZAMBOANGA CITY, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Corazon </PERSON> <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> on Monday urged people to vote in next month's plebiscite for self-rule in the southern <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>, saying a boycott would be a mistake. It was the second time in three days that Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> has gone to <LOCATION> Mindanao </LOCATION>, the second largest <LOCATION> Philippine </LOCATION> island, to campaign for the ratification of a plan to grant limited self-rule in 13 southern provinces. On Saturday, Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> visited <LOCATION> Cotabato </LOCATION> to start the campaign, but made no categorical appeal for voters to ratify the autonomy act, which was passed by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. Voters in <LOCATION> Mindanao </LOCATION> and other southern islands go to the polls Nov. 19 to decide whether their provinces will join an autonomous regional government. The move is aimed at satisfying demands for self-rule for the 4 million-member Moslem minority. Christians form the majority in the provinces of <LOCATION> Mindanao </LOCATION> and other southern islands. The bill, which Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> signed in August, has been facing public opposition even from Moslem secessionist groups. `` I understand that some groups are organizing a boycott of the plebiscite, Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> told hundreds of people at a rally. `` I think this would be a serious mistake. A boycott position is meaningless.'' She refused to say whether she was for ratification or rejection of the bill, adding that she was adopting a position of `` active neutrality.'' `` I have refused to dictate how people should vote for the plebiscite,'' she said. She said she had been accused by her foes as being indecisive, but she defended her stand, saying she upheld the principle of `` popular consultation.''
