<FIRST>r w AM-SchoolReforms     10-30 0424</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-School Reforms,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report: Decade of School Reforms Had ``Modest Success''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TAMARA HENRY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 States have had only modest success in classroom reforms, although there was a greater effort at improving public education in the 1980s than ever before, a consortium of universities said Monday. `` State legislators introduced an unsurpassed number of education-related bills, increased state aid, and examined the findings of hundreds of state-level task forces and commission,'' said the <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Policy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> in Education. Local initiatives had the most progress on restructuring schools, said the report, `` The Progress of Reform: An Appraisal of State Education Initiatives.'' The report was based on research conducted in <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> and used as its benchmark goals set forth in `` A Nation At Risk,'' the 1983 landmark government report that prompted efforts to improve learning in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. `` It is true that high school curricula are more academically oriented, standards for entering the teaching profession are more selective, teachers' salaries are higher and state and local governments have boosted educational funding,'' said the report. `` But the reforms met with only modest success in achieving their goals,'' the report continued. `` Doubts still linger about the rigor and challenge of some of the new courses in academic subjects, the impact of reform on at-risk students, the quality of teachers and teaching and the equitable funding of schools.'' The report said states tended to reject complicated reform recommendations in favor of more manageable ones. The most popular reform of the last five years was increasing graduation requirements, a relatively uncomplicated procedure, the report said. At least 45 states have modified high school graduation requirements since 1980, primarily by increasing the number of credits and academic courses needed to earn a diploma, it said. The easy reforms that were adopted have stayed in place, the report said. But more complicated reforms such as teacher assessments, career ladders and mentor teacher programs have been modified or diluted, it found. Reforms adopted by most states lacked coherence, `` sending a barrage of signals to schools and districts without setting clear priorities,'' the study said. The report said most of the progress resulted from initiatives at the local school district level. During the 1980s, several states encouraged school restructuring by providing seed money for local experiments, but some districts were developing changes without state support, it said. The federally funded <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Policy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> in </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> is a consortium of <ORGANIZATION> Rutgers </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> <LOCATION> State </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Stanford </ORGANIZATION> universities and the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wisconsin </ORGANIZATION> at Madison.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
