<HEAD>Amateur Astronomer Discovers Asteroids</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JESSICA BALDWIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An amateur astronomer using a homemade telescope said Monday he has discovered three new asteroids, and the editor of Astronomer magazine said he's the first Briton to make such a find in 80 years. <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Manning </PERSON> said he spotted the asteroids between the orbits of Jupiter and Mars using a 10-inch reflector telescope set up in his back yard in <LOCATION> Kidderminster </LOCATION>, 95 miles northwest of <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>. Editor <PERSON> Guy </PERSON> <PERSON> Hurst </PERSON>, who keeps track of all European astronomical discoveries, said <PERSON> Manning </PERSON>'s sightings were run through the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Astronomical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> computer in <LOCATION> Cambridge </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass. </LOCATION>, and found to be previously unknown. `` To go for 80 years with no discovery, it is very important for British astronomy,'' <PERSON> Hurst </PERSON> said. `` <PERSON> Manning </PERSON>'s work, although he is an amateur, is rated as high as professional.'' Manning, 63, said astronomy has been his hobby since he was a boy. `` I'm delighted and did not expect it really,'' he said. `` You always hope you might find something ... but it's a surprise since the chance of discovery is rather remote.'' <PERSON> Manning </PERSON>'s discovery was his first attempt to identify an asteroid, and was sparked by the September issue of Astronomer, which challenged British amateurs to find an asteroid, <PERSON> Hurst </PERSON> said. Manning, a retired technician from <ORGANIZATION> Birmingham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Metrology </ORGANIZATION>, which is the science of accurate measurements, said he made a 20-minute photographic exposure of the sky on Oct. 4 He did n't discover the asteroids until Oct. 5 when he developed the telescopic image and scanned it with a binocular microscope. `` My garden is not a very good spot. It's down in a hollow with trees all around,'' he said. `` The night of the fourth was quite good, despite the millions of street lamps everywhere, which are a big problem to amateur astronomers.'' Although <PERSON> Manning </PERSON> discovered the asteroids they will be named by the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Astronomical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>. The international society voted last year to name asteroid 3,698, discovered by another scientist, after <PERSON> Manning </PERSON> `` for his contribution to astronomy,'' <PERSON> Hurst </PERSON> said. Asteroids are thought to be the remnants of planets that were partly formed or destroyed in the early days of the solar system. The first asteroid, named <LOCATION> Ceres </LOCATION>, was discovered in 1801. At 621 miles in diameter, it is still the largest ever found. <PERSON> Manning </PERSON> said he believes his asteroids are about 10 miles wide.
