<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A lawsuit filed Monday alleges that the <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> has failed to develop national standards for discharging toxic pollution into public waterways as required by law. As a result, according to the lawsuit filed in U.S. District Court by the <ORGANIZATION> Natural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> and Public Citizen, millions of pounds of toxic wastes are unregulated. The lawsuit asks the federal courts to direct the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> to develop a plan for limiting a broader range of toxic pollution than is covered by federal regulations. `` Over two-thirds of the industrial facilities that release toxics into our waterways are not covered by nationwide <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> regulations, but by a weak system of site-specific permits,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Adler </PERSON>, an attorney for the <ORGANIZATION> NRDC </ORGANIZATION>, a Washington-based environmental organization. <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Alicia </PERSON> <PERSON> Tenuta </PERSON> said the agency had no immediate comment on the lawsuit because officials have not seen it. The suit, using data filed by industry to the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> on 1987 toxic emissions, said an estimated 70 million pounds of unregulated toxic wastes are released annually into surface waters and sewers from a variety of industries ranging from parmaceutical companies to mining, iron and steel and texile operations. <PERSON> Eric </PERSON> <PERSON> Glitzenstein </PERSON>, an attorney for Public Citizen, said many of those toxic releases come from companies that are in business to treat hazardous wastes. `` The hazardous waste treatment industry is perhaps the most astonishing example of an industry that escapes nationwide toxic pollution controls,'' <PERSON> Giltzenstein </PERSON> said. `` Ironically, these facilities are cleaning up polluted land and groundwater at hazardous waste sites, only to release equally dangerous wastes into our waters.'' The lawsuit alleges that the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> has failed to live up to requirements under the Clean Water Act and the Resource Conservation and Recovery Act to establish in a timely fashion a regulatory plan for controlling the discharge of hazardous waste into public waterways.
