<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> broke ground Monday for a memorial to slain police officers and said cop killers should pay `` the ultimate price'' for committing `` the ultimate crime.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> drew loud applause from a large crowd that included hundreds of police officers, widows and other relatives of some of the 30,000 officers whose names will eventually be carved on granite walls at the memorial site. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> prodded <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to act quickly on the $ 1.2 billion anti-crime package he unveiled last May, including stiffer penalties for gun-related crimes, limits on semiautomatic weapons and no plea bargaining with those who used guns in violent crimes. `` It is time to act because these improvements are a vital part of our national drug strategy,'' said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, adding, `` Before any more names are added to that wall, the protection you deserve should be added to the books.'' `` For cop killers, for those who commit the ultimate crime, I feel strongly that they should pay the ultimate price,'' said the president. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> is expected to vote later this year on <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s crime package. The House is awaiting <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> action before it takes up the measure. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, who keeps in his desk the shield of a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> rookie policeman, <PERSON> Eddie </PERSON> <PERSON> Byrne </PERSON>, murdered last year while protecting a drug witness, said the toll from police killings `` rivals those of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s overseas wars.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> made the speech behind bullet-proof glass on a stage erected at the Judiciary Square site where the National Law Enforcement Officers Memorial will be erected. It will consist of an oval, tree-lined `` pathway of remembrance'' on a three-acre site with the names of the