<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> on Monday signed legislation that gives a break to farmers who are growing substitute crops on land where drought destroyed or damaged earlier plantings. The measure eases restrictions that were part of a previous federal farm-disaster aid package. The revision protects winter wheat and cotton farmers who otherwise might have been denied disaster payments for their lost crops under an <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> plan _ even though the producers expect to earn little or no profit on replacement crops such as grain sorghum or soybeans. The <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, trying to prevent farmers from reaping double benefits, has been planning to deduct 75 percent of the gross value of any replacement crop from the disaster payment a farmer would have otherwise received for losses on his first crop. Under the bill, approved by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> last week, that system would be modified. Farmers would have no payment deductions if the replacement crops failed to produce more than 50 percent of the county average yield for the second crop. But if the yield exceeded 50 percent of average yield, the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s formula for deductions would kick in and be applied only to the portion of the crop that exceeded the 50 percent mark. Under the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s initial plan, even farmers who had replanted only a few acres would have to wait until harvesting their second crop before obtaining disaster benefits for damage to the first crop. That provision was canceled by the new legislation.
