<HEAD>Officials: X-Rays Not Effective in Detecting Tampered Treats</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 14th graf, `While the...' to restore first reference to
Harvit.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID WILKISON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Most of the nation's hospitals have pulled the plug on offers to X-ray Halloween goodies, saying the once popular way to detect pins and needles is too costly and is ineffective in preventing poisoning. `` It cost a fortune,'' said <PERSON> Rose </PERSON> <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Soloway </PERSON>, of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Capital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Poison </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> at <ORGANIZATION> Georgetown </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION> `` Someone calculated the cost in health care dollars, and it's an enormous amount of money nationwide,'' Ms. <PERSON> Soloway </PERSON> said `` It's money that's probably not well spent `` If candy is going to be tampered with, there's any number of ways of doing it,'' she said. `` X-rays can only detect foreign objects, especially metallic objects. X-rays ca n't detect chemicals or anything that could be put on or into foods.'' <PERSON> Donna </PERSON> <PERSON> Siegfried </PERSON>, technical safety specialist for the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, said hospitals began using X-ray machines to examine Halloween treats in the mid-1970s, when reports of glass and pins lodged in goods became more frequent. But some officials said hospitals are just providing parents with a false sense of security. `` We were concerned that parents who brought candy in to the emergency room to have it X-rayed and were told that there was nothing in it were led to believe it was safe,'' said <PERSON> Janet </PERSON> <PERSON> Ferguson </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Cabell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Huntington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman in <LOCATION> Huntington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> W. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>. Not all hospitals are taking the advice of the nation's poison <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Blackburn </PERSON>, chief technician for <ORGANIZATION> Logan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Logan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> W. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, said the hospital has X-rayed candy for the past several years and will do so again this year `` There is no way to detect poisons, but we try to detect a metallic foreign body. At least we're giving the child a chance,'' <ORGANIZATION> Blackburn </ORGANIZATION> said. `` In the past, we have found different things, pins stuck into fruit and candy,'' he said. `` We caution the people when we do the candy for the kids. We caution them that we ca n't detect any poison.'' <ORGANIZATION> Cabell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Huntington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> examined youngsters' treats until two years ago, when the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Poison </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Centers </ORGANIZATION> suggested hospitals no longer X-ray candy. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Baldwin </PERSON>, head nurse of <ORGANIZATION> Cabell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Huntington </ORGANIZATION>'s emergency department, said experts can detect foreign bodies by X-rays only 14 percent of the time, `` which means most of the time they could n't detect it even if it were there.'' Ms. <PERSON> Soloway </PERSON> said it's important that parents inspect each piece of candy themselves rather than depending on X-rays at hospitals. While the X-raying process often disrupted hospital routines, it was offered with good intentions and an eye on public relations, said <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Virginia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Poison </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Pam </PERSON> <PERSON> Harvit </PERSON>. But by last year, concerns about liability outstripped the benefits, she said. `` The problem we saw is that parents would take the candy to get it X-rayed and then give the kids the candy and assume it was safe,'' she said. While parents still have concerns about tampered candy, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON> Siegfried </PERSON> said the number of reported incidents is low. `` It's not a big problem. Rumors start and the media gets hold of it, and it's usually just some individual that wanted attention,'' she said. `` Falls are the number one cause of injury because of masks, running up and down stairs ... tripping over their costumes,'' she said.
