 to roam the streets following the main clash with police, hurling stones, breaking shop windows and driving away Yugoslav and foreign journalists. Some used cars and trash cans to erect street barricades. There were no reports of injuries but police were seen taking away several people. In <LOCATION> Pristina </LOCATION>, police battled groups of protesters throughout the city, including hundreds of students gathered around their school dormitories. Police used tear gas in the pedestrian zone in the downtown area, driving people screaming in panic down side streets. At the start of Monday's session in the <LOCATION> Titova </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mitrovica </LOCATION> courthouse, defense lawyers demanded that presiding Judge <PERSON> Ismet </PERSON> <PERSON> Emra </PERSON> and prosecutor <PERSON> Spasone </PERSON> <PERSON> Zamfirovic </PERSON> be removed on grounds of bias. <PERSON> Vlasi </PERSON>, 42, described the proceedings as a `` show trial staged with clear political goals'' and claimed he was the victim of a plot by archrival <PERSON> Slobodan </PERSON> <PERSON> Milosevic </PERSON>, president of <LOCATION> Serbia </LOCATION>. Until his arrest in March, <PERSON> Vlasi </PERSON> publicly opposed <PERSON> Milosevic </PERSON>'s efforts to increase control over <LOCATION> Kosovo </LOCATION>, an autonomous province in which 85 percent of the 1.9 million people are ethnic Albanians At least 24 people were killed in the March violence. <PERSON> Milosevic </PERSON> and the <LOCATION> Serbian </LOCATION> leadership argued the changes were necessary because of alleged harassment of the Serbian minority in <LOCATION> Kosovo </LOCATION>, the heartland of ancient <LOCATION> Serbia </LOCATION>. Some analysts call the <PERSON> Vlasi </PERSON> case <PERSON> Yugoslaviaq </PERSON>'s most important political trial since that of <PERSON> Milovan </PERSON> <PERSON> Djilas </PERSON> in the 1950s. <PERSON> Djilas </PERSON>, once heir apparent to the late President <PERSON> Tito </