<HEAD>Charlotte Begins Citywide Cleanup of Hugo Debris</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An army of workers assembled Monday for the first citywide cleanup since the remnants of Hurricane Hugo struck this inland city more than a month ago. Officials said the crews were prepared to stay on the job seven days a week for at least five weeks to clean up the tons of debris left behind by <PERSON> Hugo </PERSON>. `` They'll work until we get out from under the emergency,'' said <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON>, operations supervisor for street maintainence for the city of <LOCATION> Charlotte </LOCATION>. Employees will have to be released for vacations, he said. `` But we're going to keep it running until it's all finished,'' <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON> said. The only day off for employees in the next several weeks will be Thanksgiving Day, he said. Hurricane Hugo hit the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> mainland on Sept. 22, dealing its strongest blow to <LOCATION> Charleston </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> S.C. </LOCATION> By the time it reached <LOCATION> Charlotte </LOCATION>, its winds had slowed from 135 mph to a steady 70 mph and it had been downgraded from a hurricane to a tropical storm. Still, it was powerful enough to uproot thousands of trees, knock down power lines and flood low-lying areas. Three people died in the <LOCATION> Charlotte </LOCATION> area and preliminary estimates put the damage at $ 300 million. A thorough, citywide cleanup was delayed while local officials waited for federal damage estimates to be made, and for bids to come in from various contractors who would do the cleanup. The workers who assembled to begin the job Monday came from 80 of the state's 100 counties and found a city still choked with storm debris. <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON> said there was enough debris left to fill about 160,000 dump trucks, each carrying 10 cubic yards of trash. `` It's going real well,'' he said. `` This morning it was kind of chaotic. But we've got them all together now and from now on, it should be a routine type thing and we should have no more trouble.'' About 300 state workers in about 200 <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> trucks arrived Sunday. They'll help about 250 city workers and employees of 16 private companies. Storm debris is still causing problems in <LOCATION> Charleston </LOCATION> as well. Parents there have been urged not to send their youngsters trick-or-treating on Halloween, for fear that debris on curbsides might create a safety hazard. `` We do n't think it's safe for children to go trick-or-treating with all the debris on city streets. It's safer for parents to have Halloween parties,'' police Sgt. <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Hamilton </PERSON> said.
