 <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration officials said Monday that candidates for top medical jobs will not be rejected because of their views on abortion or other political issues. Medical and scientific experts have been concerned recently that an ideological `` litmus test'' centering on abortion and related issues was prompting qualified candidates to withdraw from consideration for top federal jobs, including the directorship of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institutes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION>. In a speech Sunday, <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> said he took these concerns to the White House last week. The administration has agreed, he said, that people being considered for jobs below the level of assistant secretary do not have to pass an ideological test. `` It has been our policy that standards of scientific and administrative excellence and leadership prevail in the selection process'' for scientific jobs, including heads of <ORGANIZATION> NIH </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Centers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disease </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION>, he said. However, he said, it was `` necessary and proper'' for <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> to use the litmus test to fill positions at the level of assistant secretary and above to select people who share his views. Conservative right-to-life groups have pressed the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration to appoint to positions at <ORGANIZATION> HHS </ORGANIZATION> people who share the president's opposition to abortion. <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Right </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> to </ORG