<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Former <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>'s lawyer accused the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> Monday of giving an `` off-the-wall'' reason for not paying <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON>'s legal expenses from a congressional investigation A <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokesman said it was just an interpretation of law. <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON> twice refused to answer questions when he appeared before the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Employment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Subcommittee </ORGANIZATION>, which has been investigating allegations of political favoritism at the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Urban </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION>, which he headed during the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration. He contended that because the hearings related to his tenure at the department, <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> should pay his fees. The department forwarded <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON>'s request to the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> for a ruling on whether the former secretary qualified for reimbursement under the regulations. Two weeks later, the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> replied that it had no responsibility to represent <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON> and therefore would not rule on whether he qualified for reimbursement. The department said it was up to <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> whether to represent <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON> or pay his fees. `` It's a hot potato,'' said <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON> attorney <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Plotkin </PERSON>. `` HUD hands off to Justice, Justice hands off back to <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION>.'' <PERSON> Plotkin </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> defied a plain reading of government regulations when it determined it was n't responsible for expenses <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON> incurred during the subcommittee investigation. `` I could n't believe that of several potential grounds that perhaps they might have used to justify not paying it, the one they used seemed so off-the-wall,'' <PERSON> Plotkin </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Runkel </PERSON> said `` our decision was based on the civil division's interpretation of the law. The lawyers took a look at it and that's their decision.'' <PERSON> Plotkin </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> stretched hard to formulate an interpretation of the regulations that allowed it to avoid making a politically difficult decision on <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON>'s request. The regulation states that current and former federal officials `` may be provided representation in civil and congressional proceedings and in state criminal proceedings ... when the actions for which representation is requested reasonably appear to have been performed within the scope of the employee's employment and providing representation would otherwise be in the interest of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>.'' `` One would think that clearly, on it's face we are eligible,'' <PERSON> Plotkin </PERSON> said. `` And then they have to exercise their discretion as to whether or not they want to pay it.'' But in an Oct. 25 letter to <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION>, Deputy Assistant Attorney General <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bransdorfer </PERSON> said that legal representation by the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> `` is available only in situations where the employee is subject to civil or state criminal proceedings as a result of actions taken within the normal scope of that employee's authority `` If there are no such underlying proceedings then representation is not available,'' <PERSON> Bransdorfer </PERSON> said. There are no civil or state criminal proceedings against <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON>. According to <PERSON> Bransdorfer </PERSON>'s determination, <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> said it was recommending that <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON>'s request be denied.
