<HEAD>White House Status Quo as Republicans Search for Compromise</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 House Republicans frustrated by a lack of guidance from the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> searched Monday for a compromise on raising the minimum wage in the hope of avoiding a partisan fight as an election year looms. The White House did n't publicly rule out a compromise, but said that for now it stood by its offer to raise the hourly minimum wage from $ 3.35 to $ 4.25 by January 1992 _ a year later than the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> proposal due for a vote Wednesday. `` We are not changing our position at this point,'' <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said. Chief of Staff <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Sununu </PERSON> is discussing the issue with congressional leaders, <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said. But even <ORGANIZATION> Republicans </ORGANIZATION> said the White House was doing little more than listening, and it appeared the administration was losing the support of some conservative Democrats and moderate Republicans who helped <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> win a veto battle on the issue earlier this year. One of those conservative Democrats, Rep. <PERSON> Timothy </PERSON> <PERSON> Penny </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION>, said it appeared the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> had abandoned thoughts of striking a deal. `` It sounds like they're digging in their heals again,'' he said. `` Picking another fight like this is causing a lot of us to question their sincerity because a deal is within reach.'' House Speaker <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Foley </PERSON>, D-Wash., said the discussions were continuing, but added: `` I do n't know how fruitful they are. Even an administration official close to the negotations complained of `` a lack of focus'' from the White House that had `` left dangling'' the <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> leadership. The Republicans had hoped to strike a compromise to avoid another veto fight, a potential issue in 1990 congressional elections. Because of the White House position, the Republican leadership was mulling a number of proposals of its own, with a whip count planned for Tuesday likely to determine the final shape of the measure it will offer as an alternative to the Democrats' plan. The Democrats also planned a head count, and were mulling changes designed to win back enough conservative Democrats to override a second <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> veto. Even the administration official said the Democratic leadership was within reach of winning a veto-proof majority in the House. `` Some of the votes we got last time we got with the message very clear that it was ` this time and this time only,''' said the official, speaking on the condition of anonymity. `` Right now it's probably five or six votes either way. The current bill would increase the minimum wage to $ 3.80 on Jan. 1 and to $ 4.25 on Jan. 1, 1991. It also would allow workers with fewer than two months job experience to be paid a subminimum wage. <PERSON> Penny </PERSON> and other conservative Democrats want the two 45-cent increases pushed back to April 1, 1990, and April 1, 1991, and the `` subminimum'' period extended to three or four months. `` That would make a big difference to several members,'' he said. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has insisted that to get his signature a minimum wage bill also would have to allow employers to pay all new workers a subminimum for up to six months regardless or prior job experience. Democrats have said they would never accept such language. In addition to next year's elections, two other factors have strengthened the Democrats' hand. The $ 4.25-an-hour target is more acceptable to many conservative Democrats than the $ 4.55 level in the measure <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> vetoed. Also, the fight over <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s attempt to cut the capital gains tax has allowed the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> leadership to shape the issue as one of rich vs. poor.
