<SECOND>AM-Japan-Ivory,0439</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japan Joins International Ban on Ivory Trade</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, which buys more ivory than any other country, said Monday it would join a ban on the ivory trade that is intended to protect African elephants. The ban was adopted Oct. 17 at a meeting of the 91-nation Convention on Trade in Endangered Species and is to remain in effect at least until 1992. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> had until Jan. 18 to decide whether to file an appeal, which would allow it to continue trading ivory with other countries that did the same or with the more than 60 nations outside the accord. <PERSON> Hajime </PERSON> <PERSON> Tsujimoto </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> office acknowledged that international attention on <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> as the world's main ivory consumer had played a role in the decision He also told reporters the decision did not necessarily mean <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> was out of the market permanently, and that it `` may import if the circumstances in the world change.'' If the elephant is removed from the endangered species list, he said, `` the story will be different.'' <LOCATION> Zimbabwe </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Botswana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Malawi </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Mozambique </LOCATION> have objected to the ban on grounds their elephant herds are not endangered and they depend on ivory sales to finance successful conservation. By filing for exemptions, they may continue trade in ivory with other countries that do not accept the ban. A recent census estimated <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> now has about 600,000 elephants, fewer than half the total of a decade ago. About 30,000 people in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> are employed in the ivory industry, which carves elephant tusks into ornaments, jewelry and personal signature seals. <PERSON> Tsujimoto </PERSON> said some might have to find other jobs eventually, but <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> has enough ivory in stock to last about two years. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> regularly has taken about 40 percent of the world's ivory exports. Imports totaled 106 tons in 1988 and 143 tons in 1987. It is to be host of the next meeting of the convention, in April 1992. <PERSON> Tsujimoto </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> would like to study aid to African countries for better management of elephant populations. `` We are deeply concerned about the rapid decline in the number of elephants over the last 10 years,'' he said. `` We believe drastic measures should be taken to prevent further decline in the number and seek proper protection of the animals.'' In <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, up to 400 ivory traders and carvers marched through downtown streets Monday to protest the ban. <PERSON> Adeline </PERSON> <PERSON> Li </PERSON> of the <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Kowloon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ivory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manufacturers </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ' </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> said about 4,000 people worked in the industry in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>.
