<HEAD>Pravda Editor Meets the Press, With Himself the Target</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: One graf SUBS for 14th graf, ``After Politburo ... DELETING
extraneous quotation mark. Picks up 15th graf, It would ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> confidant who is now Pravda's editor met the foreign press Monday and made himself the target, a definite change at a paper that has bashed imperialists mercilessly for generations. Asked how he will stop a sharp decline in readership in President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s era of glasnost, or openness, <PERSON> Ivan </PERSON> <PERSON> Frolov </PERSON> said: `` We shall not seek to increase circulation at all costs.'' Although he offered some ideas for enlivening the gray columns _ interviews with members of the ruling Politburo, for instance _ the 60-year-old editor seemed to hold weak commitment by today's Communists as responsible as the party daily's content for its flagging fortunes `` I can ask the question even more directly: Do we need more genuine Communists, members of the <ORGANIZATION> CPSU </ORGANIZATION>, than the already known number of Pravda subscribers?'' <PERSON> Frolov </PERSON> said, implying that the real Communist today is one who dutifully reads the paper. Only one week into his new job, the white-haired former <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> adviser already has done something that would have been a surprise coming from his remote predecessor <PERSON> Viktor </PERSON> <PERSON> Afanasyev </PERSON>, who ran the paper for 13 years. <PERSON> Frolov </PERSON> opened Pravda's 8th floor conference room to foreign correspondents and sought their questions. It was a unique opportunity to hear the views of a member of the policy-making party <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> now in charge of the most authoritative, if no longer most widely read, Soviet newspaper. As is the custom in such confrontations, <PERSON> Frolov </PERSON> occasionally avoided straight answers _ on Pravda's circulation, for example. `` We do n't have definitive information; the circulation was once 10,700,000; it will probably be less,'' he said from the head of a rectangle of wooden tables pushed together to make room for more than 100 journalists, all but a few of them foreigners. Pravda, officially the organ of the party <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, now has tough competition from other dailies that have taken advantage of glasnost to publish more daring or spicier stories. Also, Soviet citizens no longer are required to take Pravda to get another publication they really want, such as a literary monthly or a magazine about movies. A Pravda official told a Westerner who visited the paper last month that only 3 million to 4 million people had subscribed for next year. <PERSON> Frolov </PERSON> said research would be used to determine why Pravda's readership has dropped He said there would be `` some innovations'' to tempt readers, among them exclusive publication of some <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> documents. `` After Politburo meetings, we shall publish interviews with the leaders of the party on what they personally think of the subjects raised there,'' he said. It would be a departure if Politburo members were persuaded to give their personal views on its decisions, customarily made in secret and always presented as unanimous. <PERSON> Frolov </PERSON> made clear Pravda will not become the pugnacious, Western-style newspaper some Soviets say is needed to safeguard the public interest. `` I must say, the decision about coverage of <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> or Politburo events is made by the appropriate bodies, and you will agree that it is quite proper and that they ought to have the authority to do it,'' he said, defending the party's right to do business behind closed doors. That was his response when asked why Pravda and other papers had not printed an account of the meeting earlier this month with ranking editors, in which <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> was said to have accused some of excesses or ideological errors. Western reporters found that many Soviet journalists who attended the technically secret meeting were ready to talk about it. How does <PERSON> Frolov </PERSON> see the future of the newspaper founded by <PERSON> Lenin </PERSON> in 1912 as a tool to whip up hostility to the czar among workers? `` We shall not become a non-serious, light paper,'' he said. `` We shall not chase hot news, publish non-verified facts or poorly analyzed materials. We shall not seek to increase circulation at all costs.'' Pravda, he said, will try to `` express the very essence of present-day party policies.'' That does not mean <PERSON> Frolov </PERSON> shuns making the paper more attractive. `` As far as I am concerned, there can be nothing more attractive than good analysis,'' said the editor, a graduate in philosopy from <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>.
