<HEAD>Slayings of Two Women Stun Small Community</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALD KNOB, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Police said they had some leads Monday in the deaths of two elderly women whose blood-drenched bodies were found in homes 500 yards apart, 12 hours after they returned from the same church service. The two women were beaten, stabbed and apparently robbed over the weekend, authorities said. `` We've got leads and we hope to make an arrest or arrests,'' said Cpl. <PERSON> R.A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Boone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sheriff </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. The slayings stunned people in the small community, about 25 miles south of <LOCATION> Madison </LOCATION>. `` This has tore everybody all to pieces,'' said <PERSON> Beth </PERSON> <PERSON> Kinder </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Charleston </LOCATION>, who was in <LOCATION> Bald </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Knob </LOCATION> on Monday visiting her mother. `` Now people are panicking. We've never had anything like this happen.'' The body of <PERSON> Faye </PERSON> <PERSON> Jarrell </PERSON>, 83, was found Sunday morning after a neighbor knocked on her door and got no answer. A short time later, another person spotted an open door next door and notified police, who found the body of <PERSON> Dorothy </PERSON> <PERSON> Daniels </PERSON>, 68. Both had last been seen Saturday night at the <LOCATION> Bald </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Knob </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Methodist </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Church </LOCATION>, where they attended a wake for a neighbor. Both victims' homes had been ransacked and were missing small items, <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said. But he said more valuable items usually taken during a robbery, such as televisions and prescription drugs, had not been touched. `` The motive we're looking at right now is robbery,'' <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said. `` We ca n't substantiate any other motive at this time.'' <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said an autopsy showed that both victims had been stabbed repeatedly and beaten. `` There is no evidence of gunshot wounds,'' <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said. `` ... There was a considerable amount of blood. The victims apparently lived modestly, and there was no indication of what prompted the attack, <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said. `` They did n't appear wealthy,'' he said. `` They were elderly and lived alone. Nothing extravagant. They were neat in their houses. It looked like one lady had done some quilting.'' <PERSON> Rose </PERSON> <PERSON> Belcher </PERSON>, who lives a half-mile from the two houses, said she had known the victims all her life. `` They were well thought-of in the community,'' she said. `` It's a big shock to all of us My only thought is someone must have thought they had some money. It's so sick.''
