<HEAD>Report 149 People Arrested During Demonstration to be Charged</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government news media said Monday that 149 of the 355 demonstrators arrested during an anti-government protest will be charged with violating public order. The Communist Party daily Rude Pravo said the 149 were detained for 48 hours and all of the others arrested during the demonstration Saturday in <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION> were released soon after they had been seized. Rude Pravo did not say if the 149 were still in jail and an <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> official said only that they had been held for 48 hours. At a regular news conference Monday, deputy goverment spokesman <PERSON> Marcel </PERSON> <PERSON> Jansen </PERSON> quickly told reporters he had no official statement on the demonstration and they should address questions to chief government spokesman <PERSON> Miroslav </PERSON> <PERSON> Pavel </PERSON>, who is on vacation. The party newspaper said the 149 would be charged under anti-demonstration laws passed earlier this year that impose fines of up to $ 2,000. More than 10,000 people gathered Saturday in <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Wenceslas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Square </LOCATION> to mark the 71st anniversary of Czechoslovak independence. They chanted calls for free elections, a new government and the removal of <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> leader <PERSON> Milos </PERSON> <PERSON> Jakes </PERSON>. Rude Pravo said five policemen and seven demonstrators were injured in clashes during the rally but all had been treated and none remained hospitalized. The state media provided no information about 17 foreigners reported detained during the rally, other than repeat the report and say the foreigners were from 11 different countries. Rude Pravo again accused the U.S.-funded Radio Free Europe and <ORGANIZATION> Voice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> radio stations for the anti-government demonstration. In <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> criticized the crackdown on the pro-democracy rally. Spokeswoman <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Tutwiler </PERSON> said, `` The people of <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION> know what democracy is and they want it now.'' `` The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> calls on the government of <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION> to respect the rights of its citizens and to institute the basic freedoms desired by the Czechoslovakian people.'' The newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Mlada </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fronta </ORGANIZATION>, published for Communist youths, did not take the hard line followed by Rude Pravo. Rude Pravo referred to the people surrounded and attacked by riot police in <LOCATION> Wenceslas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Square </LOCATION> as the `` aggressive'' core of the demonstration. <PERSON> Mlada </PERSON> <PERSON> Fronta </PERSON> said about 300 demonstrators were involved and they were peaceful. It noted the people chanted demands to police not to use violence and shouted, `` We have bare hands!'' raising their arms to show they were unarmed.
