<HEAD>St. Paul Fire Chief To Step Aside While Allegations Investigated</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENE LAHAMMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The city fire chief is stepping aside while officials look into allegations he had links to arsonists, Mayor <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Latimer </PERSON> announced Monday. Reports about Fire Chief <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Conroy </PERSON> are `` shocking and disturbing,'' <PERSON> Latimer </PERSON> said. `` If there was wrongdoing, it will be prosecuted and penalized,'' the mayor said in announcing <PERSON> Conroy </PERSON> would take paid administrative leave. <PERSON> Latimer </PERSON> also said firefighters have been barred from moonlighting for fire adjusting companies, a practice criticized by fire experts quoted in Sunday's report in the <ORGANIZATION> Star </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tribune </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Minneapolis </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Star </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tribune </ORGANIZATION> reported that properties owned by <PERSON> Conroy </PERSON> or his brother, <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON>, have had 11 fires in the past 25 years. It also noted that two associates of <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Conroy </PERSON> were convicted of arson in 1986. <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Conroy </PERSON> told the newspaper that he has no connections with any `` fire industry'' in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Paul </LOCATION>, and said his department `` is looked on as one of the better fire departments in the country.'' His brother denied any involvement in arson. `` We are confident that after a thorough investigation, we will be totally exonerated from any wrongdoing of any nature,'' said <PERSON> Earl </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gray </PERSON>, an attorney representing <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Conroy </PERSON>. <PERSON> Latimer </PERSON> said <PERSON> Conroy </PERSON> requested an examination by outside investigators so he could clear his name. He added that the chief agreed to cooperate fully with the investigators, and volunteered to take the administrative leave. `` I did not have to urge him. He made the offer,'' the mayor said. `` He obviously is in a lot of pain and is very sad today.'' <PERSON> Latimer </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Ramsey </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Foley </PERSON> has agreed that the investigation into the allegations should be handled by an outside agency, The newspaper report said the fire chief has allowed firefighters to moonlight for an adjusting company that has represented alleged arsonists in fire insurance claims. It also said shoddy investigations by the department have helped arson thrive. The newspaper said its report focused on more than 200 fires in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Paul </LOCATION> over the past 25 years that in some way involved <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> or <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Conroy </PERSON>, public adjuster <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Whelan </PERSON>, or their friends and associates. The newspaper said <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Conroy </PERSON> gave $ 10,000 to set <PERSON> Whelan </PERSON> up in business as a public adjuster before becoming chief. It also said that <PERSON> Whelan </PERSON>'s most frequent contractor has been <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Conroy </PERSON>, and that companies owned by <PERSON> Whelan </PERSON> and <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Conroy </PERSON> have received millions of dollars in insurance money from <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Paul </LOCATION> fires. Asked why many of his cases involved arson fires, <PERSON> Whelan </PERSON> said, `` I have no idea.'' He said arsonists who have worked on his staff were not known arsonists at the time. The <ORGANIZATION> Star </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tribune </ORGANIZATION> said its reporters examined more than 10,000 pages of documents and interviewed hundreds of people. City police and the state <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Criminal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Apprehension </ORGANIZATION> raised questions about <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Conroy </PERSON> 10 years ago, but their investigation died amid political squabbles, the newspaper said. <PERSON> Latimer </PERSON> said Deputy Fire Chief <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Colonna </PERSON>, 43, who has been with the department for 18 -LCB- years, will serve as acting chief while <PERSON> Conroy </PERSON> is on leave. <PERSON> Colonna </PERSON> said he hopes the latest allegations can be cleared up quickly. `` It's easy for anyone to see that these kinds of articles would affect the morale of the Fire Department,'' he said. `` That's why it's so important that this be brought to a public conclusion.'' <PERSON> Latimer </PERSON>, who has served as mayor since 1976, is not seeking re-election in next Tuesday's general election.
