<HEAD>Amnesty Reports Unabated Use of Torture in Turkey</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday that anyone detained in <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> for suspected political offenses is in danger of being tortured. The worldwide human rights organization said use of torture to obtain information or confessions from political prisoners continued unabated on a wide scale in violation of international treaties signed and ratified by <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> last year. London-based <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> said in a new report that more than 500 political prisoners alleged they were tortured in <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> so far this year and 10 such prisoners were said to have died in custody as a result of being tortured. Amnesty said most of the allegations relate to initial interrogations in police custody while detainees were routinely denied access to lawyers or relatives. It said that while its report does not discuss torture of criminal prisoners, `` they, too, are frequently reported to have been ill-treated and tortured.'' Amnesty reported `` the government ... has consistently denied that torture is systematic in <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> and has described those instances of torture which it admits as the isolated actions of individuals.'' The organization welcomed as a step in the right direction draft amendments to the Turkish Criminal Procedure Code announced in September. But it said they fall short of international standards that require all detainees be brought before a judge soon after detention and have prompt access to lawyers, doctors and relatives. The proposals, which still must be approved by the <ORGANIZATION> Turkish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Grand </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION>, would shorten the maximum detention period to four to 10 days and grant lawyers access to detainees. The maximum detention period permitted before a detainee is either formally charged or released now is 24 hours. In political cases it may be extended to 15 days, however, and under emergency legislation up to 30 days. Specific cases cited by <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> include 21 students held incommunicado at <LOCATION> Ankara </LOCATION> police headquarters on the day the government announced the draft amendments. The students later said they were tortured while being interrogated. One, 20-year-old <PERSON> Yusuf </PERSON> <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Yildiz </PERSON>, said that during six days in custody he was stripped naked, hosed down with pressurized cold water, beaten and given electric shocks. The report also cited the death of <PERSON> Seyhmus </PERSON> <PERSON> Orhan </PERSON> from <LOCATION> Yoncali </LOCATION> village in southeastern <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION>. It said he died on July 18 after 24 hours of interrogation at the Command of the 118th Gendarmerie Regiment. Officials said he was shot trying to escape. Other detainees and relatives said he was killed under torture and shot afterward. Amnesty, winner of the 1977 Nobel Peace Prize, said statements extracted under torture are used as evidence against political prisoners. It said the <ORGANIZATION> Maltaya </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> convicted four people in September of belonging to the illegal organization Devrimci Yol -LRB- Revolutionary Path -RRB- without investigating their allegations that their confessions were extracted under torture. The defendants told the court they were stripped, hosed with ice-cold water, beaten and given electric shocks, <PERSON> Amnesty </PERSON> said. One said he confessed when police threatened to torture his wife. Amnesty said it repeatedly urged the Turkish government to take effective steps to prevent torture and to meet its obligations under European and <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> conventions for the prevention of torture. It said it also asked <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> to establish independent and impartial procedures to investigate allegations of torture and to ensure that statements extracted under torture are not used as evidence against defendants.
