<HEAD>Energy Prices Raised up to 150 Percent</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government imposed steep increases on energy prices, effective Wednesday, in conjunction with a revised budget passed by Parliament that slashes coal subsidies. The price increases and spending cuts were the latest exercise in fiscal toughness from the 2-month-old government led by Prime Minister <PERSON> Tadeusz </PERSON> <PERSON> Mazowiecki </PERSON> of Solidarity in its effort to control the economic crisis. A <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> statement Monday said electricity would go up 150 percent, natural gas 100 percent and bills for heat and hot water 50 percent. `` Low retail prices of electricity, heat and gas fuels in relation to the cost of production and to other fuels make it necessary to increase retail prices,'' it said. `` This increase is a logical result of the recent increase in the price of coal.'' Similar price increases have brought down <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> governments and led to the birth of Solidarity in 1980s as the Soviet bloc's first independent trade union, but public forbearance toward <PERSON> Mazowiecki </PERSON> continues An official announcement Monday said donations to help support his government had reached $ 138,000, most of it from individuals. Foreign governments also have offered tens of millions of dollars' help in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s move toward democracy and a market economy. The first grain shipment donated by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> arrived off the <LOCATION> Baltic </LOCATION> port of <LOCATION> Gdynia </LOCATION> on Monday. <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> said three <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION> members would lead a delegation arriving in late November to determine how <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> aid can be used most effectively. Parliament approved the amended budget Monday by a vote of 301-4, with 35 abstentions. It reduces the projected deficit from 9.2 trillion zlotys -LRB- $ 3.8 billion -RRB- to 4.7 trillion -LRB- $ 1.96 billion -RRB- and trims subsidies for the coal industry by 1.2 trillion zlotys -LRB- $ 500 million -RRB-. It puts expenditures at 34.4 trillion zlotys -LRB- $ 14.3 billion -RRB- in 1989 and income at 29.7 trillion zlotys -LRB- $ 12.4 billion -RRB-. The government hopes partially closing the budget gap will reduce the amount of money in circulation and slow inflation, now at about 600 percent annually. Many food subsidies also have been trimmed, along with government-financed projects and spending on social services. On Oct. 16, <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> restricted an indexation plan that provides automatic pay increases to counteract inflation.
</TEXT>
