<HEAD>Pedro Vargas, Tenor of the Americas, Dead at 85</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Mexican singer <PERSON> Pedro </PERSON> <PERSON> Vargas </PERSON>, nicknamed `` the tenor of the <LOCATION> Americas </LOCATION>,'' died early Monday of heart failure, his family said. He was 85. `` He died in his sleep,'' his oldest son, <PERSON> Pedro </PERSON> <PERSON> Vargas </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, told reporters. <PERSON> Vargas </PERSON> had been suffering for several years from diabetes and heart problems. Known for his rich melodious voice, <PERSON> Vargas </PERSON>' singing career spanned more than 60 years and included performances at Carnegie Hall, Madison Square Garden and the White House. He sang for Presidents <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Roosevelt </PERSON> and <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Truman </PERSON>, shared the stage with <PERSON> Sammy </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, and counted <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Sinatra </PERSON> and <PERSON> Julio </PERSON> <PERSON> Iglesias </PERSON> among his friends and admirers. <PERSON> Vargas </PERSON> was considered one of the brightest starts in the `` Golden Age'' of Mexican music, which spanned the 1930s and'40s. <PERSON> Vargas </PERSON>, in partnership with composer Mexican <PERSON> Agustin </PERSON> <PERSON> Lara </PERSON>, popularized the `` bolero'' and the `` paso doble,'' the fast-paced Spanish double footstep dance. He also appeared in dozens of films, most of them produced in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>. It was considered one of the greatest musical partnerships in the Spanish-speaking world. <PERSON> Vargas </PERSON> was born in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Miguel </LOCATION> <LOCATION> de </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Allende </LOCATION>, in central <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, on April 29, 1904, the second of 13 children. He was a quiet and introverted child whose family wanted him to become a priest. Instead, he developed an early vocation for music and began singing in a chorus in high school in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> in 1917. After high school, he tried to become a bullfighter but failed, and turned to studying medicine. But singing remained his first love and his strong tenor voice gained him quick admission to the National Conservatory of Music. <PERSON> Vargas </PERSON> got his first break in 1928 when he was selected to sing the role of Turidu in the Italian opera Cavalleria Rusticana by <PERSON> Pedro </PERSON> <PERSON> Mascagani </PERSON>. The performance was so successful that it led to a tour of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Vargas </PERSON> then turned to popular ballads, eventually reaching an audience of millions in <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>. His rendition of `` Fleur-de-Lis'' was his hallmark throughout <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> in the 1930s. `` He was a personal friend of <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Sinatra </PERSON> and, although they never sang together, he did sing with a mutual friend, <PERSON> Sammy </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON>, <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>,'' his son recalled Monday. `` This morning, I received with great emotion condolences from my father's death from <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Sinatra </PERSON>, <PERSON> Julio </PERSON> <PERSON> Iglesias </PERSON> and <PERSON> Libertad </PERSON> <PERSON> Lamarque </PERSON>, among others,'' <PERSON> Pedro </PERSON> <PERSON> Vargas </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Vargas </PERSON> is survived by his wife <PERSON> Teresa </PERSON> <PERSON> Campos </PERSON>, four children and seven grandchildren.
