<HEAD>Security Council Finds Consensus on Namibia Resolution</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> ambassadors agreed Monday on a mild resolution that criticizes <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s administration in <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION> but does not claim that free and fair elections are impossible in the territory. Unanimous adoption was likely Tuesday after the 15 ambassadors consult their capitals, said Western and Third World diplomats on the council, speaking on condition of anonymity. Black African and non-aligned nations began circulating draft resolutions two weeks ago that castigated <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> for alleged abuses, and prepared to follow up with strong speeches before the Nov. 7-11 Namibian election. British diplomats said those resolutions invited vetoes from more than one of the five permanent <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> members _ the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. Western diplomats said Third World nations were trying to mount an 11th-hour campaign to boost the electoral chances of the <ORGANIZATION> South-West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Africa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>, known as <ORGANIZATION> SWAPO </ORGANIZATION>. Intense consultations resulted in language agreeable to all council members. `` This is a watered-down version that causes us no problems,'' said <PERSON> Aubrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Dwyer </PERSON>, spokesman for <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, which is not on the council. `` There's nothing in there that they can use to declare the elections null and void.'' The final draft `` welcomes'' Secretary-General <PERSON> Javier </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON>'s report on <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>, which outlined areas of concern but concluded that the territory is headed for a free and fair election. It `` demands immediate, full and strict compliance by all parties concerned, in particular <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>,'' in implementing council resolutions calling for <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>'s independence. It demands that all paramilitary and ethnic forces and commando units be disbanded, particularly the <ORGANIZATION> South-West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Africa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Territorial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Koevoet </ORGANIZATION>, a dreaded counterinsurgency unit. <ORGANIZATION> SWAPO </ORGANIZATION> has accused its main competitor, the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Turnhalle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alliance </ORGANIZATION>, of hiring <ORGANIZATION> Koevoet </ORGANIZATION> veterans to intimidate pro-SWAPO voters and break up campaign rallies. The resolution calls for decommissioning the 1,500 South African <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> soldiers still in <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>, now confined to base under U., N. supervision. It demands repeal of `` such remaining restrictive and discriminatory laws and regulations as inhibit the holding of free and fair elections,'' without specifying any. The resolution endorses <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON>'s opinion that law AG8, which establishes a racially segregated society in <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>, should be repealed. Namibians will vote for a constituent assembly to draft a constitution and organize the first independent, black majority-ruled government in the territory of 1.3 million. If <ORGANIZATION> SWAPO </ORGANIZATION> wins two-thirds of the votes, it will be able to unilaterally write the constitution and organize any form of government it chooses. The former German colony has been governed by <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> since 1915. Last December, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> signed accords with <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> agreeing to cooperate with a <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> plan for <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>'s transition to independence as <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> withdraws its 50,000 troops from <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>.
