 Seven explosions ripped through an oil-field service company Monday, injuring two workers, damaging 25 mobile homes and forcing the evacuation of about 200 people, authorities said. `` It was just like mortar rounds shot out in all directions,'' Police Chief Dean <PERSON> Akings </PERSON> said in this city of about 17,000 people 112 miles northwest of <LOCATION> Wichita </LOCATION>. The explosions and fire at <ORGANIZATION> Wire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tech </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> on the eastern edge of the city began at 7:50 a.m., and were caused by shaped charges, which are explosives used in the oil industry, officials said. A search for live charges and blasting caps was under way Monday night. `` There was over 1,000 of those projectiles inside the business,'' <PERSON> Akings </PERSON> said. `` They all went somewhere. We've had some of those projectiles located up to three-quarters of a mile away.'' The city police and fire departments, the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alcohol </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tobacco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Firearms </ORGANIZATION> and an <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> bomb squad from <PERSON> Fort </PERSON> <PERSON> Riley </PERSON> took part in the search. Residents were warned to call authorities if they spotted any charges, which can be set off by high heat or pressure. The first explosion was followed by six more blasts and a fire at the company. Firefighters standing outside the building put the blaze out within about 20 minutes, said Fire Chief <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Meisinger </PERSON>. `` I was n't going to send people in,'' <PERSON> Meisinger </PERSON> said, citing the danger of another explosion. About 200 residents within a quarter-mile of <ORGANIZATION> Wire </ORG