<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Prospective jurors in the trial of a <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> police officer who shot a black motorcyclist to death were asked Monday whether the threat of racial violence would influence their verdict. People were called into the courtroom one at a time from a jury pool created last week and questioned closely by attorneys about their knowledge of the Jan. 16 shooting that sparked three days of rioting. The trial of Colombian-born <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Lozano </PERSON>, 30, has raised concern among local officials about another violent reaction in the community, which has seen several racial eruptions this decade after the slayings of blacks by police and the acquittals of police officers after trials. <PERSON> Lozano </PERSON> is charged with two counts of manslaughter in the deaths of <PERSON> Clement </PERSON> <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON>, 23, who was shot in the head while being chased by police, and <PERSON> Allan </PERSON> <PERSON> Blanchard </PERSON>, 24, who suffered fatal injuries when the bike crashed. As the trial's second week began Monday, lead prosecutor <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Hogan </PERSON> estimated that seating a six-member jury and four alternates would take at least two weeks. But Monday's relatively brisk pace could mean a jury will be seated more quickly. `` I assumed we'd have a lot more trouble than this,'' <PERSON> Hogan </PERSON> said. When the session ended for the day, nine people were retained as prospective jurors and five were excused. Among those excused were three people who said they had formed strong opinions on the case. Most of the people questioned said they knew very little about the case. Attorneys for both sides questioned prospective jurors on the past riots and asked if they could remain impartial despite the threat of violence looming over this trial. A white woman in her 50s, who said she followed the case in newspapers and on television, said she could n't put aside her fears of possible violence. `` It's frightening,'' she said. `` You're afraid that if you were on the jury and brought in a verdict the black community did n't want to hear, there'd be rioting. She was dismissed. A black woman, who works as a bus-maintenance clerk, said she had not formed an opinion about the <PERSON> Lozano </PERSON> case. Asked about past riots, she said, `` I do n't believe in violence. We all suffer from it.'' But she indicated that the threat of violence would not affect her verdict if she were on the jury. `` Whatever happens, happens,'' she said. She was told to remain as the jury-selection process continued. The shooting, which occurred on the birthday of the Rev. <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Luther </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> during the week leading up to the Super Bowl, left one person dead and caused millions in property damage. The defense says <PERSON> Lozano </PERSON> shot in self-defense. His attorney, <PERSON> Roy </PERSON> <PERSON> Black </PERSON>, won the acquittal of then-Miami officer <PERSON> Luis </PERSON> <PERSON> Alvarez </PERSON> in the 1982 shooting of a young black man at a video arcade in <LOCATION> Overtown </LOCATION>, just blocks from where <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> and <PERSON> Blanchard </PERSON> were killed. That slaying and the innocent verdict in 1984 triggered racial violence, as did the acquittal of five <ORGANIZATION> Metro-Dade </ORGANIZATION> officers tried in 1980 in the beating death of a black motorcyclist after a chase.
