<SECOND>PM-German Homeless, Adv 03,0724</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv03</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Friday PMs, Nov. 3, or Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Severe Housing Shortage Afflicts Wealthy West Germany</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOGNE, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Affluent young executives flocking to West German cities like this scenic <LOCATION> Rhine </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> metropolis have a problem in common with the poor immigrants crowding in from the East. Hundreds of thousands of them can find no place to live. <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, one of the world's wealthiest nations, has been plunged into a housing crisis by its own prosperity. Demographic and economic warps have coincided to flood the market with homeseekers at a time when the supply of new public and private housing is virtually nil due to a construction lag five years ago. `` Our postwar baby boom came along a little later than in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, and we are now seeing hordes of young people with good educations and good incomes flooding the housing market,'' said <PERSON> Stefan </PERSON> <PERSON> Kampmann </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> German </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tenants </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, which monitors rental conditions nationwide. `` They can afford better housing, and they want it, but it just is n't there.'' The housing shortage loomed long before a wave of East European refugees hit this year, but that influx expected to reach 500,000 by year's end has greatly aggravated the problem. The nation is now short about 800,000 homes. A million other households are in need of major renovation. Thousands of recent arrivals from <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> sleep on cots in converted concert halls or in makeshift metal housing erected on sports fields. The hundreds of thousands of upmarket homeless usually crowd in with relatives or friends during the hunt for housing, which can take years. <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Munich </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Hamburg </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION> suffer the most acute shortages, but officials concede the problem has reached crisis proportions in virtually every city. Chancellor <PERSON> Helmut </PERSON> <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON> has declared housing the No. 1 budget priority for next year and has promised special funds for new construction this year and a review of tax and rent-control laws. Paradoxically, hundreds of thousands of potential apartments are kept off the market by landlords in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> because of tax consequences or building restrictions that prevent conversion of attics and lofts. Pressure from all income brackets is mounting, and tales of apartment-hunting woes abound. Desperate homeseekers advertise any way they can. A man in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> painted an appeal on the back of his leather jacket. Many put up notices on trees and light standards. `` Desperate, well-paid two-income couple with small child will pay 800 marks -LRB- $ 420 -RRB- for information leading to obtaining a three-room or larger apartment,'' said one of hundreds of such notices posted in the <LOCATION> Suedstadt </LOCATION> neighborhood in <LOCATION> Bonn </LOCATION>, the capital. `` Non-smoking medical student seeks any room for 1989-90 study year,'' a <LOCATION> Heidelberg </LOCATION> man, <PERSON> Rainer </PERSON> <PERSON> Schimpf </PERSON>, has likewise announced. <PERSON> Heike </PERSON> <PERSON> Schneider </PERSON>, a 29-year-old journalist in <LOCATION> Bonn </LOCATION>, said the apartment shortage allows landlords to pick and choose tenants to the point of discrimination. `` Landlords wo n't rent to students and single people because they think you're going to wreck the place,'' said Ms. <PERSON> Schneider </PERSON>, who shares an apartment with two roommates. While West Germans have more money to invest as their economy booms, housing construction is a long-term investment with lots of risks. Crowded with industry and covered with a spider's web of freeways from the <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> to the <LOCATION> Bavarian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Alps </LOCATION>, little open land is available for new suburban housing. Environmental codes strictly limit construction in urban areas, and building and labor costs have risen so sharply that rents double the going rate would have to be charged to recover construction costs. A rent-control law has kept prices relatively stable at the equivalent of about $ 600 to $ 725 a month for a 1,000 square feet of living space. About 60 percent of West German households are renters. The German Home, Apartment and <ORGANIZATION> Land </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Owners </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Duesseldorf </LOCATION> contends the government will have to loosen regulations to encourage owners to rent second homes and spare rooms. Its president, <PERSON> Theodor </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON>, says 225,000 more dwellings could be brought into the market if owners could see a profit in it.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Friday PMs, Nov. 3</NOTE>
