<HEAD>In Peruvian Port, Shopkeepers Speak Russian</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW SCOTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CALLAO, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Dirty, decayed, haunted by hoodlums, prostitutes and drug addicts, this fogbound seaport is not much different from any other <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> port of call _ except here, the shopkeepers speak Russian. More than 200 ships of the Soviet fishing fleet operating in the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> off <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION> use <LOCATION> Callao </LOCATION> as a resupply point under a contract signed by the two countries in 1971. For the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Callao </LOCATION> represents an important but controversial foothold in a region where Soviet influence has been limited. About 30,000 Soviet crewmen a year, on six-month stints, shuttle in and out on <ORGANIZATION> Aeroflot </ORGANIZATION> flights to nearby <LOCATION> Lima </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION>'s capital. The sailors, the most visible sign of the Soviet presence in <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION>, have become prominent targets for leftist terrorists, however. On July 5, a terrorist bomb tossed beneath a tour bus wounded 20 sailors from the fleet on a shopping and sightseeing trip. Many of the wounded were badly maimed and burned. Six Soviet fishermen also were wounded in 1986 when a bomb hidden under a pile of sweaters went off in a clothing shop frequented by the sailors in <LOCATION> Callao </LOCATION>. Police attributed the attacks to the Shining Path, a leftist insurgent group fighting since 1980 to topple <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION>'s government and install a workers' and peasants' state patterned on the ideas of the late Chairman <PERSON> Mao </PERSON> <PERSON> Tse-tung </PERSON> of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. The group also has attacked the <ORGANIZATION> Aeroflot </ORGANIZATION> office in downtown <LOCATION> Lima </LOCATION> and a Peru-Soviet cultural center. On Oct. 25 rebels in a passing car hurled dynamite at the <ORGANIZATION> Soviet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION>, damaging a diplomat's car but causing no injuries. It was the second attack on the embassy in three years. In 1986 the Maoist guerrillas assaulted it with explosives and submachine guns. One rebel penetrated the embassy compound but was blown up when a bomb exploded in his hands. The Shining Path views the current Soviet and <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> governments as traitors to true Marxism and regards the Soviets as enemies because they have been a major supplier of arms to the Peruvian armed forces for the past two decades. Just before the July 5 bus bombing, the government announced it had purchased four Soviet helicopter gunships for its fight against the insurgents. Close relations between <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> go back to the late 1960s, when the leftist military dictatorship of Gen. <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> Velasco </PERSON> realigned Peruvian foreign relations toward the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> bloc. <PERSON> Velasco </PERSON> outfitted his army and air force with Soviet arms and aircraft, and despite subsequent changes in government <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION> remains dependant on the Soviets for training and spare parts. Today the country is the third largest purchaser of Soviet military hardware in the <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hemisphere </LOCATION>, after <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>. `` They are inhibited from turning away from the Soviet influence because of decisions made 20 years ago,'' said a <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> diplomat. `` They're hooked onto the chain.'' Although staggered by a huge budget deficit and a $ 17 billion foreign debt, the government is planning to buy 14 more helicopters for use by its counterinsurgency forces. The government uses the fishing contract to help pay its debts with the Soviets, almost all of which is for arms purchases. The agreement allows Soviet trawlers to harvest 400,000 tons of fish a year inside <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION>'s 200-mile territorial-water limit. <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION> takes 17.5 percent of the catch. Critics complain the Soviets take as much as $ 1.5 billion worth of fish each year without paying taxes and accuse the government of doing little to control the take. `` They can fish where, when and as much as they want,'' said Sen. <PERSON> Felipe </PERSON> <PERSON> Osterling </PERSON>, who submitted a formal complaint to the government in April charging the fishing contract was unconstitutional. The left-leaning government of President <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Garcia </PERSON> has not responded to the complaint. But businesses in blighted <LOCATION> Callao </LOCATION> welcome the tall blond fishermen. `` Sweaters _ the cheapest; blue jeans, imported watches, and they carry away lots of brown leather jackets,'' said <PERSON> Angelica </PERSON> <PERSON> Casana </PERSON>, owner of a store that sells Peruvian handicrafts. `` They take special sizes because they are very big.'' The terrorist threat, however, has caused business to drop off in <LOCATION> Callao </LOCATION> as the sailors try to maintain a low profile, she added. `` It's affected them, the fear,'' she said. `` They do n't come like they used to, and some shops have closed up and left.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Tuesday PMs Nov. 7</NOTE>
