<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 In the early decades of the century, it was the gathering place of artists and writers, bon vivants and aspiring models, American expatriates and Russian political exiles. <LOCATION> Montparnasse </LOCATION>, on the left bank of the <LOCATION> Seine </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>, was a neighborhood of remarkable creativity and unflagging revelry. Today it is the site a cult art form in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>. But it is <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>' lone skyscraper, the sleek <ORGANIZATION> Montparnasse </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tower </ORGANIZATION>, that is perhaps the clearest symbol of a new age. `` Now, there are just one or two painters. It's not like before,'' says <PERSON> Aime </PERSON> <PERSON> Duhauvel </PERSON>, a house painter who for 51 years lived at 8 <ORGANIZATION> Rue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> de </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> la </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Grande </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chaumiere </ORGANIZATION>, where <PERSON> Modigliani </PERSON> had his atelier. <PERSON> Duhauvel </PERSON>, forced out of his apartment by high prices in 1984, returns daily to chat with his friend, the local shoemaker. Ms. <PERSON> Goddard </PERSON>, who has lived on the Isle of Wight since 1935, says she `` ran away'' to escape what was becoming the incestuous smallness of the quarter. The gentrification of <LOCATION> Montparnasse </LOCATION> was inevitable, says <PERSON> Billy </PERSON> <PERSON> Kluver </PERSON>. `` The artists create the community and the real estate people move in.'' For <PERSON> Kluver </PERSON>, who spent 10 years gathering documentation for his book, the spirit of <LOCATION> Montparnasse </LOCATION> is dead. Not everyone agrees. `` This neighborhood inspires me,'' says <PERSON> Alice </PERSON> <PERSON> Mouradian </PERSON>, a clothes designer who lives two doors from <LOCATION> Hemingway </LOCATION>'s former <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> abode. `` Each building here possesses a soul.'' Mrs. <PERSON> Kowalezyk </PERSON> says her clients at <LOCATION> Wadja </LOCATION> are the same as before, just younger. `` For us, things have n't changed,'' she says. `` It's difficult with our prices, but people still need to eat. `` To make a long story short,'' <PERSON> Kluver </PERSON> quotes <PERSON> Kiki </PERSON>'s memoirs, `` <LOCATION> Montparnasse </LOCATION> is a village that's as round as a circus. You get into it and you do n't know just how, but getting out again is not so easy!'' <PERSON> Kiki </PERSON> simply `` burned herself out,'' says <PERSON> Kluver </PERSON>, collapsing and dying at age 52, not far from the boulevard.
