<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Nov. 12</HEAD>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<HEAD>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&amp;w photo.
ColorFoto subscribers get 1 35mm slide.)    </HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 It requires a special talent to take an obscure wedding dance by <PERSON> Edvard </PERSON> <PERSON> Grieg </PERSON> and turn it into a Hit Parade smash like `` Strange Music'' or transform the exotic themes of <PERSON> Borodin </PERSON> into songs like `` Stranger in Paradise'' and `` Baubles, Bangles and Beads.'' For much of their careers, <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Forrest </PERSON> and <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> have used that talent, adapting someone else's music, usually a classical composer, and spinning it into something new. They did it in <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION>, working on dozens of films like `` Maytime,'' `` Sweethearts'' and `` I Married an Angel,'' and on <LOCATION> Broadway </LOCATION> with shows like `` Song of <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION>,'' `` Magdalena'' and `` Kismet.'' `` Writing original music is 10 or 20 times easier than the things for which we are best known,'' <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> was saying the other day. `` The first thing you have to do as an adapter is learn everything a composer ever wrote. Then you have to assemble and assimilate the music. And finally, think the way he did.'' At 75, <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> is the talkative member of the songwriting team. <PERSON> Forrest </PERSON>, one year younger, nods in agreement. Their partnership has lasted some 60 years. It began at <ORGANIZATION> Miami </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> where they wrote their first song _ `` Hail to <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> High!'' _ and has continued into the present. Their latest musical, `` Grand Hotel,'' currently is on view at the <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Beck </PERSON> Theater. `` Grand Hotel,'' directed and choreographed by <PERSON> Tommy </PERSON> <PERSON> Tune </PERSON>, focuses on the guests at a large luxury hotel in <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION>. It's based on the 1920s best-selling <PERSON> Vicki </PERSON> <PERSON> Baum </PERSON> novel that later became a successful movie starring <PERSON> Greta </PERSON> <PERSON> Garbo </PERSON> and <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Barrymore </PERSON>. The musical, using an original <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> and <PERSON> Forrest </PERSON> score, takes place in 1928, a year its composer and lyricist remember very well. `` We were both working musicians by that time,'' <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> says. `` I had won an amateur contest playing the Rachmaninoff ` C Sharp Minor Prelude' when I was 9 and went into vaudeville. I found out very young that there was money in music, so I never touched the piano unless I was paid. `` I played for <PERSON> Helen </PERSON> <PERSON> Morgan </PERSON>, <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON> <PERSON> Rose </PERSON> and <PERSON> Sally </PERSON> <PERSON> Rand </PERSON>, all in the same year. I think it was 1933.'' Two years later, at ages 21 and 20, <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> and <PERSON> Forrest </PERSON> went to <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION> and found work at <ORGANIZATION> Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, the studio associated with the classiest of the movie musicals. They were signed to write original music and lyrics. But the team found little work until a disaster nearly derailed a film version of <PERSON> Sigmund </PERSON> <PERSON> Romberg </PERSON>'s `` Maytime,'' starring <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> <PERSON> Eddy </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jeanette </PERSON> <PERSON> MacDonald </PERSON>. <PERSON> Irving </PERSON> <PERSON> Thalberg </PERSON>, the legendary producer, died with only half the film musical completed. A new director started over, and <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> and <PERSON> Forrest </PERSON> were assigned to come up with new musical material. Much of it was taken from music already in the public domain, pieces like <PERSON> Tchaikovsky </PERSON>'s `` Fifth Symphony'' and pieces of operas. The movie was a big success, and <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> and <PERSON> Forrest </PERSON> stayed in <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION> for seven years, participating in some 50 movies, often anonymously. `` We worked on anything they asked,'' <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> says. `` You're slaves in <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION>, very happy slaves, but they owned us body and soul We always did our very best and worked as artistically as we possibly could.'' Finally, they quit. <PERSON> Herbert </PERSON> <PERSON> Stothart </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> MGM </ORGANIZATION>'s famous musical director and their mentor, told them: `` They'll keep you forever. People will never know who you are.'' Before they left they wrote a small musical revue called `` Thank You, <LOCATION> Columbus </LOCATION>,'' that opened _ and closed _ in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>. But through it, they met producer <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Lester </PERSON> who vowed to put on their next show. `` Once you write anything for the stage and you put it in front of an audience and you hear them react, then the movies become very dreary and dull,'' <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> says. The team traveled to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> to write for cabaret, nightclubs and radio. The work included special club material for performers like <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> <PERSON> Durante </PERSON>, <PERSON> Ella </PERSON> <PERSON> Logan </PERSON>, <PERSON> Sophie </PERSON> <PERSON> Tucker </PERSON>, <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON>, <PERSON> Jane </PERSON> <PERSON> Froman </PERSON> and <PERSON> Carmen </PERSON> <PERSON> Miranda </PERSON>. <PERSON> Lester </PERSON> reappeared in their lives in 1944, with an idea for a stage musical based on the life of <PERSON> Edvard </PERSON> <PERSON> Grieg </PERSON>, using the composer's own melodies. The idea became `` Song of <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION>.'' It was a big success for <PERSON> Lester </PERSON> in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, and he brought it to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> where it ran for over two years. <PERSON> Lester </PERSON> also was responsible for `` Kismet,'' the team's other big <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> hit. This musical, a sort of Broadway meets the Arabian Nights, won them a Tony Award in 1954. Besides `` Stranger in Paradise'' and `` Baubles, Bangles and Beads,'' the songs included `` This Is My Beloved'' and `` Rhymes Have I.'' The musical version of `` Grand Hotel'' has had a 20-year history. It began in 1958 with <PERSON> Luther </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> who adapted the book for the great Yiddish comedian <PERSON> Menasha </PERSON> <PERSON> Skulnik </PERSON>. It was called `` At the Grand.'' But by th time the musical went into production, it starred <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Muni </PERSON> and <PERSON> Joan </PERSON> <PERSON> Diener </PERSON>. Muni got sick, and the musical never got beyond tryouts in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>. Two years ago, <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> resurrected the idea and took it to <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> and <PERSON> Forrest </PERSON>. He told them, `` I would like to start all over again and really do <PERSON> Vicki </PERSON> <PERSON> Baum </PERSON>'s novel,'' <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> recalls. `` Our other version was set in <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION> and was about movies and opera. We went back to the original.'' <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> and <PERSON> Forrest </PERSON> began reworking their score, and <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> extensively revised the book. `` The most important part of a musical is the book, not the music and lyrics,'' <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> says. `` Once the book tells a story that is interesting, then the music and lyrics have something to say. Up until then, they are just songs.'' `` The book is more important because most of the critics are literary critics; they are not music critics,'' <PERSON> Forrest </PERSON> adds. `` What they criticize is the book.'' At ages when most people have been retired for a decade, <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> and <PERSON> Forrest </PERSON> keep writing. They are revising `` The Anastasia Game,'' a new version of their 1965 musical `` Anya,'' which recently had a production in <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>, and working on `` Uncle <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON>,'' a musical based on the <PERSON> Eudora </PERSON> <PERSON> Welty </PERSON> novella `` The Ponder Heart.'' `` You ca n't stop working,'' <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> says. `` Besides, most of our working consists of sitting and thinking,'' <PERSON> Forrest </PERSON> adds. `` You sit and you wish.''
