<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Nov. 5, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Corazon Aquino's Philippines, A Nation Still Troubled</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: an accompanying item is BC-Philippines-Glance, b0580.</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Corazon </PERSON> <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> of the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> visits the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> this week in hopes of attracting more trade and investment to her country and improving conditions for her 60 million people. Here is a report on the state of the nation she has led since 1986.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT H. REID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Nearly four years ago, <PERSON> Corazon </PERSON> <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> stood before television cameras and proclaimed that a `` dark night of tyranny'' had come to an end in the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Ferdinand </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> and his wife, <PERSON> Imelda </PERSON>, had been driven into exile in <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION> by the `` people power revolution'' that brought Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> to power. The `` night of tyranny'' she referred to in taking her oath as president on Feb. 25, 1986, may have ended, but poverty, insurgency, crime and social inequities remain. Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> arrives in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> on Tuesday, after visiting <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, in search of more trade and investment in the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> to cope with those problems at home. From Vancouver, <LOCATION> Toronto </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Ottawa </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, she is scheduled to visit <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> for a meeting with President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, and <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>, before heading home via either <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>. She'll confer with businessmen in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>. But the struggle to deal with economic problems, armed insurgencies and coup attempts has sapped the euphoria and political vitality that in 1986 drove <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> to <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION>, where he died Sept. 22 at the age of 72, and vaulted Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> to the office that many thought should have been her husband's. It was the assassination of the husband, Sen. <PERSON> Benigno </PERSON> <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, on Aug. 21, 1983, that set off the chain of events that led to the `` people power revolution'' in the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON>, who had been imprisoned by <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> for seven years before being allowed to leave for exile in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, was returning home that August day to challenge <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>; he was shot to death as he stepped off a plane at <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION>'s airport. But today in <PERSON> Corazon </PERSON> <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON>'s <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>, a feeling persists that nothing has changed since the <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> years. Recently, the <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Weather </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stations </ORGANIZATION> polling service said only 35 percent of 300 Manilans surveyed were satisfied with Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON>, down from a high of 77 percent two years ago. `` There is a growing number of people who are dissatisfied with her,'' said Rev. <PERSON> Joaquin </PERSON> <PERSON> Bernas </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Ateneo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> and an Aquino supporter. `` Satisfaction is going down steadily. Halfway in her fourth year she has not rebounded.'' Inflation today is 12 percent. Allegations of corruption abound. Cardinal <PERSON> Jaime </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sin </PERSON>, the Roman Catholic archbishop and the nation's leading churchman, often comments that Filipinos rid themselves of `` <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Baba </PERSON>, but the 40 thieves remain.'' By <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Baba </PERSON> he means <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>. `` Because of poverty and lack of education, people end up being victims of injustice,'' said <PERSON> Luis </PERSON> <PERSON> Villafuerte </PERSON>, chairman of the Governors League of the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>. `` If you can not improve that situation, you can say you have a democracy, you have elections, you have a <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, but it means nothing to people who are poor and suffering.'' Human rights abuses continue, as do killings by Communist insurgents. The killings include the assassination in April of Col. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Rowe </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> and the slayings of two other Americans in September. Ordinary Filipinos are threatened by rising crime, much of it committed by police and soldiers, including car thefts, murders and bank robberies. Police say the crime rate has increased by 6.5 percent since Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> took office. For the first six months of this year, the monthly crime index stood at 20.17 incidents per 100,000 people. More than 15 percent of the nation's 72,730 recorded crimes occurred in greater <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION>. The Social Weather Stations survey said 25 percent of the 300 <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION> residents polled reported they had been victims of crime. But no groundswell of opposition appears to be building against Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON>, known affectionately as <PERSON> Cory </PERSON>. Attempts by the left and right to organize huge street demonstrations have largely fizzled. Filipinos appear more concerned with the struggle for a decent living. But there is a feeling Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> might be missing a historic opportunity to transform the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> into a model of progressive <LOCATION> Asian </LOCATION> democracy. Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> can point to significant accomplishments. She has restored democratic institutions, unshackled the press and held back Communist and Moslem insurgents. The economy has grown steadily and is expected to increase by about 6 percent this year. But economic gains have mostly benefitted upper middle class entrepreneurs with little filtering down to the masses. Government figures indicate the lowest third of society controls only 9 percent of the national income, virtually the same as under <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>. Millions subsist on incomes barely adequate for food and lodging.
</TEXT>
