<HEAD>$adv05</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Nov. 5, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>MANILA: and lodging.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Among those millions is <PERSON> Aurora </PERSON> <PERSON> Mendoza </PERSON>, who supports an unemployed husband and two children on a monthly salary of 1,543 pesos -LRB- $ 73.50 -RRB- as a clerk in the Education Department. Her expenses average about 2,925 pesos -LRB- $ 139.30 -RRB- a month, she said. She makes up the difference by borrowing money from colleagues. Others like her supplement their salaries by selling home-grown foods or other items to fellow office workers. In <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION>, wealthy Filipinos live in spacious homes in plush, well-guarded `` villages.'' But government figures indicate that Filipinos in 25 of the 73 provinces receive few state services. In <LOCATION> Sulu </LOCATION>, a largely Moslem province 600 miles south of <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION>, 133 of every 1,000 infants die before their first birthday. Life expectancy for males in <LOCATION> Basilan </LOCATION> province is 52.9 years _ 10 years years below the national average. `` There is always the expectation of better things,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> said in a recent interview with The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>. `` And there have been better things. But I suppose what people would like is for all these good things to happen yesterday.'' Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON>, who is American-educated and a member of a wealthy family, did not set out to recast Philippine society but to restore the institutions that the <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> years had destroyed or corrupted. Hers was to be an `` institutional revolution,'' the success or failure of which would show whether U.S.-style democracy can work in a poor country. But those values were imposed on an Asian society in which family ties, paternalism and respect for authority sometimes lead to nepotism, corruption and entrenched `` warlord'' families. Longtime colonial domination _ first by Spaniards, then by Americans _ established a tradition of armed struggle such as the 20-year-old Communist insurgency and the Moslem revolt that flares and subsides. Colonialism also produced a class of landed elite, which prospered through war, revolution, dictatorship and democracy. Many of the old families _ the Laurels, the <ORGANIZATION> Lopezes </ORGANIZATION>, the Cojuangcos, the <ORGANIZATION> Aquinos </ORGANIZATION> _ were at the forefront of the anti-Marcos campaign. Early in her administration, Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> tried to pursue reformist goals. Her fledgling steps faltered with the rise of military influence and the re-emergence of powerful political clans. Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> freed 300 political prisoners and offered peace talks to Communist and Moslem rebels. Her first human rights commissioner, the late <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Diokno </PERSON>, promised to prosecute soldiers for human rights abuses committed under <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>. The peace talks with the rebels failed. But the overtures and the threat of prosecution alarmed the military, setting the stage for the six coup attempts against Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON>. The coups failed because of the loyalty of Gen. <PERSON> Fidel </PERSON> <PERSON> Ramos </PERSON>, the chief of staff and now the <ORGANIZATION> defense </ORGANIZATION> secretary. But military influence increased, and most liberals were dropped from Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON>'s Cabinet. Talk of human rights trials and reconciliation with rebels ended. Early in her administration, Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> fired all officials elected under <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> and appointed `` officers-in-charge.'' That led to turmoil in local administrations and a rift in the ruling coalition after factions claimed they were shortchanged in appointments. To end the turmoil, Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON>'s allies struck agreements with many former <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> supporters in the May 1987 congressional elections and the regional balloting in January 1988. That enabled representatives of more than 30 `` warlord'' families to regain power. The influence of traditional politicians in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> slowed reform. Land reform languished in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> nearly a year before emerging with so many pro-landlord loopholes that the agrarian reform secretary, <PERSON> Miriam </PERSON> <PERSON> Defensor </PERSON> <PERSON> Santiago </PERSON>, fears it will be unworkable.
</TEXT>
