<FIRST>s i BC-Philippines-Glance Adv05   10-30 0379</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Philippines-Glance, Adv 05,0385</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv05</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Nov. 5, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>The Philippines at a Glance</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Cory's Philippines, b0578-b0579</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 THE LAND _ The <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> is a tropical archipelago of 7,100 islands about 500 miles east of the <LOCATION> Asian </LOCATION> mainland, but its actual land area is about the size of <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION>. Only 7 percent of the islands are larger than one square mile and two-thirds are unnamed. The largest islands are <LOCATION> Luzon </LOCATION>, which includes <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Mindanao </LOCATION> in the south.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 THE PEOPLE _ The 60 million Filipinos are mostly of Malay ethnic stock with mixtures of Chinese, Spanish, <PERSON> Arab </PERSON>, American and other European ancestry. They are descendants of Malays who began arriving in the islands about 2,000 years ago from what are now <LOCATION> Indonesia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Malaysia </LOCATION>. About 85 percent are <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION>. The rest include Protestants, Moslems and adherents of tribal religions. English and Filipino, a Malay language based on <LOCATION> Tagalog </LOCATION>, are the official languages. But more than 80 other languages and dialects also are spoken.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 THE GOVERNMENT _ <PERSON> Corazon </PERSON> <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> took office as president on Feb. 25, 1986, after a popular uprising toppled <PERSON> Ferdinand </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> and forced him into exile in <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION>. Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> restored the U.S.-style bicameral legislature, which <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> had abolished. Elections for the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> and House of Representatives were held in May 1987 and balloting for regional officials took place the following January.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 THE HISTORY _ <ORGANIZATION> Negritos </ORGANIZATION> migrated from <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION> over a land bridge thousands of years ago. When the Portugese explorer <PERSON> Ferdinand </PERSON> <PERSON> Magellan </PERSON> reached the islands in 1521, he found descendants of Malay people who began arriving about 2,000 years ago. A Spanish expedition returned 21 years later and named the islands for King <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>. The Spanish ruled until the Americans seized the islands in 1898 in the Spanish-American War. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> invaded the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> in 1941, defeating a joint U.S.-Filipino force. Gen. <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> <PERSON> MacArthur </PERSON> returned with a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> invasion force in October 1944 and recaptured <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION> in February 1945. Full independence from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> was granted on July 4, 1946. <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> declared martial law in 1972 and lifted it Jan. 17, 1981. But he retained vast powers until he was ousted in 1986.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Nov. 5</NOTE>
