<FIRST>s a BC-RememberChina? Adv05-2Takes   10-30 0901</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Remember China?, Adv 05-2 Takes,0934</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv05</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Nov. 5, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>What Happened to the Outrage Over China?</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL HIRSH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Events in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, which roused the world to a frenzy of outrage in June, seem more recently to have lulled it to sleep. What was once high drama on television has dwindled to a daily grind of repression and arrests since the bold `` democracy movement'' in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Tiananmen </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Square </LOCATION> was snuffed out in blood. But what happened to the horror that swept the world in June? Where are the tens of thousands of expatriate Chinese students and sympathizers who joined in strident protest? And beyond the mild sanctions announced months ago, where are the threatened boycotts, the embargoes? On Oct. 1, only about 3,500 people joined fugitives from the Chinese democracy movement for a demonstration in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> to counter the regime's 40th anniversary celebration. Organizers had hoped to draw nearly 10 times that many. Other disturbances of global impact _ such as the 1979 Soviet invasion of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> or the'76 <LOCATION> Soweto </LOCATION> massacre in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> _ provoked lasting reaction from the West, either by arousing Cold War passions or prompting endless demonstrations on college campuses. Yet the world seems to do little more than frown at <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> while its hard-line Communist government zealously smothers human rights. `` All the great intentions about making <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> realize the cost of oppression have faded,'' said <PERSON> Sidney </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>, executive director of <ORGANIZATION> Asia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Watch </ORGANIZATION>, a human rights committee in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. `` The Western European governments, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> ... none has said <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> has to lift martial law in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> before we'll lift the freeze on <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> loans. No one has said anyone involved in the violence must resign before we resume high level contacts.'' <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> watchers point to several reasons for the muted response: _ Foreign governments do not want to disturb <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s tentative orientation toward the West, so carefully nurtured since the <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> years _ The Cold War has faded, and with it fears of communist excesses _ <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> activists suffered a sharp emotional letdown after seeing their hopes crushed so abruptly; they recognize, bleakly, the current regime is just continuing that country's age-old habit of dictatorial repression _ The number of <LOCATION> Americans </LOCATION> and other Westerners involved with <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, whether economically or politically, is still small Only since <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> diplomatic relations were resumed in 1979 have firm ties been established after years of alienation. But the simplest reason may be out of sight, out of mind. With dozens of arrests and at least 12 executions over the summer, the <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> government apparently has succeeded in extinguishing the democracy movement _ or at least driving it underground. `` There's no one to carry the torch,'' said <PERSON> Jonathan </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Spence </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> scholar at <ORGANIZATION> Yale </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. `` If there was some kind of opposition in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> like the unions or the church in <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, they could carry the story.'' Foreign news media, getting scant information from frightened Chinese sources, have largely dropped <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> to the back pages. In its place are more exciting _ and visible _ developments in <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. `` The Chinese government has really done a very good job of managing the story,'' said <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> <PERSON> Naughton </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> expert at the <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Relations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Studies </ORGANIZATION> at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION>. `` In particular they have carefully avoided any sensational event that could be a rallying cry. There is an ambiguity about it. `` They have begun to carry out a policy of systematic limitation on intellectual freedom. That's a major story but they do it in a way that is incremental. They're nickle and diming it.'' That strategy suffered a minor setback Oct. 5 when the 1989 Nobel Peace Prize was awarded to the <PERSON> Dalai </PERSON> <PERSON> Lama </PERSON>, the exiled leader of <LOCATION> Tibet </LOCATION>, for his non-violent struggle to free his country from <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s occupation. It was a glancing commentary on Tiananmen Square. But there may be deeper reasons why the emotions stirred by the deaths of hundreds, perhaps thousands of Chinese on June 3-4 now seem stilled. In some ways, the times are not ripe for outrage. The Cold War has ebbed; some say ended. With it has gone the fear of communism that aroused the right-wing `` <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> Lobby'' of the 1950s and lingered long enough to prompt President <PERSON> Carter </PERSON>'s grain embargo and boycott of the 1980 <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> Olympics. Instead, today's news is filled with smiling Soviet leaders and widening gaps in the Iron Curtain. A poll published by Business Week magazine in August found that, by a 3-to-1 margin, Americans are more concerned by the economic threat from <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> than the military threat from the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. Economics, indeed, seems to be replacing ideology as the driving force behind <ORGANIZATION> East-West </ORGANIZATION> relations, blurring distinctions. President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> has staked his future on it. So apparently have <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s leaders, despite the lurch back into totalitarianism. `` The burden of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> relations has to some extent fallen on businessmen, who are not exactly altruists,'' commented <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dernberger </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> specialist at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Michigan </ORGANIZATION>. For the record, <ORGANIZATION> Chinese </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> leader <PERSON> Jiang </PERSON> <PERSON> Zemin </PERSON> opened celebrations marking the regime's 40th anniversary with a blast of Cold War rhetoric. He condemned the West's `` rotten lifestyles'' and predicted the triumph of socialism over capitalism.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
