<HEAD>On Show: Museum and Gallery Exhibits and Shows</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Terra-cotta works created by artists a millennium ago are featured in a new exhibit, `` Icons: Ideals and Power in the Art of <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>,'' at the <ORGANIZATION> Smithsonian </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Museum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Art </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. The exhibition of 125 sculptures, watercolors, oils, etchings and banners explores the various ways in which various African societies and civilizations have viewed the icons of mother and child, male and female, the male, the rider, and the stranger. `` Unlike European religious icons that focused on Christian imagery, these five African symbols represent powerful, shared cultural ideals and values central to the lives of African peoples,'' said <PERSON> Andrea </PERSON> <PERSON> Nicholls </PERSON>, assistant curator. `` The ideals are embodied in the images as attributes of physical beauty, power or accomplishment in the social, political, religious or economic realm.'' The exhibit includes a pair of Yoruba palace doors by the sculptor <PERSON> Areogun </PERSON> with images of a king and his wives, bicyclists, colonial clerks, soldiers and equestrians to reflect late 19th - century Yoruba life `` Icons'' opened Oct. 25 and will run through Sept. 3, 1990. Here is a list of other current shows this season at some museums and galleries in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>:
