<HEAD>Music Makers: From Hoops to Platinum</HEAD>
<HEAD>Laserphoto LA1 of Oct. 30</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANNE M. PETERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 When <PERSON> Paula </PERSON> <PERSON> Abdul </PERSON> was a child, she dreamed of following in the footsteps of such singing and dancing legends as <PERSON> Gene </PERSON> <PERSON> Kelly </PERSON>, <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Astaire </PERSON> and <PERSON> Judy </PERSON> <PERSON> Garland </PERSON>. Today, it looks as if the diminutive 26-year-old vocalist and choreographer could be well on her way. <PERSON> Abdul </PERSON>'s debut album, `` Forever Your Girl,'' has sold more than 2 million copies with three No. 1 singles: `` Straight Up,'' `` Forever Your Girl'' and `` Cold Hearted.'' A fourth single, `` The Way You Love Me,'' is also burning up the charts. To top it off, she recently won three MTV awards for her music and videos, and even more recently won an Emmy for her choreography of `` The <PERSON> Tracey </PERSON> <PERSON> Ullman </PERSON> Show.'' She is understandably overwhelmed. `` I feel redundant when I keep saying, ` I'm overwhelmed' or ` I'm excited,' but it's really something you ca n't explain,'' she said `` It's just an inner feeling that you have. You smile and you laugh and you think, ` I'm a real lucky girl.''' <PERSON> Abdul </PERSON> has come a long way from her days cheerleading for the <ORGANIZATION> Los </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Angeles </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lakers </ORGANIZATION>, considering it was an opportunity she almost missed. She heard about the audition and went with her girlfriends, but became discouraged when she saw hundreds of Laker Girl hopefuls milling about waiting for their chance to perform. `` I drove the girls that were auditioning with me so I had to wait for them. And at the very last second, after hours, I said, ` What the heck, I'm just gon na go ahead.' `` I was a big basketball fan,'' she said. `` I was a huge Laker fan and we each would get two season seats. What more could you want? The Lakers were really hot.'' Soon after being selected as one of the 12 cheerleaders in 1981, the choreographer left to get married. She asked a very young <PERSON> Abdul </PERSON> to take over the job. Like everything she commits herself to, <PERSON> Abdul </PERSON> devoted herself to getting the Laker Girls noticed. She incorporated traditional cheerleading with jazzy dance steps and savvy street moves. The fans did notice _ and the offers started pouring in for <PERSON> Abdul </PERSON> to choreograph. She helped smooth out dance steps for a music video by the <ORGANIZATION> Jacksons </ORGANIZATION> and did some commercial work. Then she choreographed the videos for <PERSON> Janet </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s `` What Have You Done for Me Lately?'' and `` When I Think of You,'' among others. `` I was n't looking to become a choreographer really,'' <PERSON> Abdul </PERSON> said. `` These were little jobs that came my way and it was something that was good money and it was fun.'' Besides choreographing videos for <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> ZZ </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Top </ORGANIZATION> and the Pointer sisters, <PERSON> Abdul </PERSON> arranged dance steps for <PERSON> Aretha </PERSON> <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON>, <PERSON> Kool </PERSON> and the Gang and <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> concert tours. She also choreographed two films, `` The Running Man'' and `` Coming to <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>.'' She became so busy she had to say goodbye to the Laker Girls. But with the looming examples of <PERSON> Kelly </PERSON>, <PERSON> Garland </PERSON> and <PERSON> Astaire </PERSON>, <PERSON> Abdul </PERSON> still was drawn to song. <PERSON> Abdul </PERSON> laughed as she talked recently about her break into the recording business. She said the record company executives who worked with her on music videos kept asking, `` So what do you want to do when you grow up, <PERSON> Paula </PERSON>?'' She would respond: `` I want to be an artist on your label.'' Finally two executives took her seriously and signed her to a recording deal. `` Forever Your Girl'' was the result. `` I remember thinking when I was making the album: ` Look, I'm having a good time doing this but it would be really wonderful if I really sold albums It would be wonderful if I had hit songs,''' she said. The album has since produced the three hits, and probably will generate a few more. `` You feel like, ` Well gosh, I have a No. 1 single, that's really great. Then you have another single that comes out and it goes No. 1 and you freak out,'' she said. `` I freaked out. I could n't believe it. Then you have a third one that goes No. 1 and you go, ` Oh my God! I'm dreaming!''' <PERSON> Abdul </PERSON> never expected such quick success when she was a young girl taking `` hours and hours'' of dancing lessons and dreaming of <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION> in her <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Fernando </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> neighborhood. Her dark good looks come from a Brazilian and Syrian father, and a French Canadian mother. She said when she was little, her mother warned her about the perils of show business and urged her to have another dream. <PERSON> Abdul </PERSON> seriously took the advice and went to <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Northridge </LOCATION>, where she entered the radio-TV-film program. `` I still had a strong love of song and dance and acting, but I knew in case it never worked for me then I would maybe have a career as a sports commentator.'' Unfortunately for the sports world, she never took that career track _ and now juggles choreography and singing while trying to find time for herself. After a recent early morning photo shoot, <PERSON> Abdul </PERSON> admitted she was pressed for time because she had to catch a plane to <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>. `` It gets draining,'' she said. `` When it gets to be a little bit too much that's when I have to back off, at least for a day, because I do n't want it ever to be tedious. I want to always feel the way I'm feeling now.'' She had been scheduled to choreograph the film version of the musical `` Evita,'' but got a reprieve of the four-month project in <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> when <PERSON> Meryl </PERSON> <PERSON> Streep </PERSON> dropped out as lead. With that shelved, <PERSON> Abdul </PERSON> wants to take a week off, then immerse herself in a second album, which may include some surprises. `` Musically, I'm more involved now and I have different ideas of where I want to go,'' she said. `` I'm not going to deviate too much from what I've done, with what's been successful for me, but I plan on stretching a lot.'' Her success has not stifled her ambition. She eventually wants to break into acting, much like her <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION> idols, and is currently considering several prospects. `` I definitely want to act,'' she said. `` But I definitely want to continue making music and I'll never give up choreography.''
