<HEAD>Books and Authors: Letters of Passion, Encouragement, Strength</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY15 of Oct. 30</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HILLEL ITALIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Vladimir </PERSON> <PERSON> Nabokov </PERSON> liked to write standing up, waking in the early morning and starting work at a blue lectern. By the afternoon, the author would be seated in an armchair, a wooden board across his lap. He usually wrote until bedtime. With books taking up most of his day, letters were written only for specific reasons: business, a line to his publisher or a legal matter that required his signature. There were also notes to his family: passionate letters to his wife, <PERSON> Vera </PERSON>, when they were apart for a time; messages slipped under the hotel room door of his son, <PERSON> Dmitri </PERSON>, in <LOCATION> Montreaux </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION>; words of encouragement to his brother, <PERSON> Kirill </PERSON>, an aspiring poet. Not every writer could be creative at all times, but as <PERSON> Dmitri </PERSON> <PERSON> Nabokov </PERSON> said in a recent interview, even the most casual memo by his father was something special, graced by the touch that produced `` Lolita,'' `` The Gift,'' `` Ada'' and many others. `` It was a thrill, I loved it,'' recalled <PERSON> Nabokov </PERSON>, 55, who helped compile `` The Letters of <PERSON> Vladimir </PERSON> <PERSON> Nabokov </PERSON>: 1940-1977'' -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Harcourt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brace </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jovanovich </ORGANIZATION>, $ 29.95 -RRB-. `` I knew, that as in his fiction, around the corner of every sentence there would be a nice little surprise, a linguistic surprise,'' he said. `` Whether he was writing to a publisher, writing to a son, making up a grocery list _ there was always something original in how he phrased it. The receptors of my spinal cord were always ready for his language.'' <PERSON> Nabokov </PERSON> admits that a certain settling of accounts was in mind upon issuing his late father's letters. <PERSON> Vladimir </PERSON> <PERSON> Nabakov </PERSON>'s stern, precise image represented just one side, his son insists. Consider what the author wrote to Vera in May 1937 after his recovery from a recent illness: `` You know _ now I can tell you frankly _ the indescribable torments in February, before these treatments, drove me to the border of suicide _ a border I was not authorized to cross because I had you in my luggage. My love, is it really true that I shall soon see you _ if fate does not let me down? `` Try not to worry too much, my love. We shall be together soon anyway. Tell Mother I embrace her and am not writing her only because I am spending all my epistolary energy on you.'' `` Lolita,'' of course, touched off dozens of letters, ranging from amusement to anger as frightened publishers suggested changes or backed away, and governments attempted censorship. <PERSON> Nabokov </PERSON> knew his story of a middle-aged man's passionate affair with a 12-year-old girl would create controversy and this 1950s best seller became the usually apolitical author's most passionate cause. On March 6, 1956, he wrote to <PERSON> Morris </PERSON> <PERSON> Bishop </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Romance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Literature </ORGANIZATION> at <ORGANIZATION> Cornell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, where <PERSON> Nabokov </PERSON> also taught: `` I know that ` Lolita' is my best book so far. I calmly lean on my conviction that it is a serious work of art, and that no court could prove it to be ` lewd and libertine.' `` All categories raid, of course, into one another: a comedy of manners written by a fine poet may have its ` lewd' side; but <PERSON> Lolita </PERSON> is a tragedy. ` Pornography' is not an image plucked out of context; pornography is an attitude and an intention. The tragic and the obscene exclude each other.'' Those writers <PERSON> Nabokov </PERSON> found inferior are spared nothing. Poet T.S. <PERSON> Eliot </PERSON> and author <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Mann </PERSON> are dismissed as `` big fakes.'' Nobelist <PERSON> Saul </PERSON> <PERSON> Bellow </PERSON> is `` a mediocrity.'' Poet <PERSON> Ezra </PERSON> <PERSON> Pound </PERSON> is `` disgusting and entirely second-rate.'' Critic <PERSON> Edmund </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>, a onetime supporter, feuded openly with <PERSON> Nabokov </PERSON>. In the 1950s, after many years of a warm friendship, these two great literary figures drifted apart. It started on a professional level, with <PERSON> Nabokov </PERSON> attacking <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>'s attempts at Russian translation and ended with bitter, personal attacks in the early 1970s, shortly before the critic's death `` As you perhaps know, the warm friendship between EW and VN, which began in 1941, was later obliterated by minor and major clashes,'' <PERSON> Nabokov </PERSON> would sadly note. He preferred the Russian poet <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> Pushkin </PERSON>, spending years on the English translation of his novel in verse, `` <PERSON> Eugene </PERSON> <PERSON> Onegin </PERSON>.'' <PERSON> Nabokov </PERSON> also admired <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Joyce </PERSON>, whose `` Ulysses'' was labeled `` pornographic'' as well, and <PERSON> Marcel </PERSON> <PERSON> Proust </PERSON>, author of the classic `` Remembrance of Things Past,'' whose gift for intricate detail had a powerful influence. `` Proust was very visual and chromatic in his approach and so was father,'' <PERSON> Dmitri </PERSON> <PERSON> Nabokov </PERSON> said. `` Father in his youth wanted to a painter. At the age of 15, he received lessons in the house. He had talent, but his teacher read the first of my father's attempts at poetry and prose and said, ` You have to a writer, or a poet.''' <PERSON> Vladimir </PERSON> <PERSON> Nabokov </PERSON>, the son of a prominent liberal in pre-revolutionary <LOCATION> Russia </LOCATION>, was born 1899 in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Petersburg </LOCATION> -LRB- now <LOCATION> Leningrad </LOCATION> -RRB-. He read <PERSON> Tolstoy </PERSON> and <PERSON> Turgenev </PERSON> as a child, played chess and collected butterflies, a lifelong fascination. Unhappy with the Bolshevik government, he emigrated in 1919 and lived in several countries before settling in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in 1940. Twenty years later, the author and <PERSON> Vera </PERSON> moved to <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION>, where they remained until his death in 1977. <PERSON> Vera </PERSON> <PERSON> Nabokov </PERSON> still lives in <LOCATION> Montreaux </LOCATION>. `` He was a wonderfully warm guy,'' said <PERSON> Dmitri </PERSON> <PERSON> Nabokov </PERSON>, who translated several of his father's books. `` He was my best friend, as is mother. But he was intransigent with bad art and second-hand ideas. Intransigent with those who mutilated his art. And very, very jealous with his time. `` His time and strength were finite. He felt he had a gift that he had to utilize to the fullest and he wanted to write. He did not go on bookstore tours and was very parsimonious in giving interviews.'' In 1964, <PERSON> Nabokov </PERSON> did agree to a rare interview, and conducted it in even rarer style. The reporter filled a stack of paper with questions and handed them to <PERSON> Nabokov </PERSON>, who walked to his lectern and composed the answers. Always, his son observed, the author knew how he best communicated. `` In his own words, ` I think like a genius, I write like a distinguished author, I speak like a child.' He also said that he was a wretched public speaker, which was n't true. He was a wonderful speaker, he did a lot of ` off-the-Nabokov-uffing,' as he called it. `` He was such a precisionist with language. He felt that everything he published should be up to the best level or the right thought.''
