<FIRST>a a BC-PRI--Nepal-Jesuit Adv02   10-30 0825</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-PRI--Nepal-Jesuit, Adv 02,0844</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv02</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Thursday, Nov. 2, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>A Solitary Voice from the Himalayas</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BINAYA GURUACHARYA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GODAVARI, Nepal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Rev. <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Moran </PERSON> has talked with <PERSON> Mahatma </PERSON> <PERSON> Ghandi </PERSON> and drove <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s first prime minister, <PERSON> Jawaharlal </PERSON> <PERSON> Nehru </PERSON>, around in a jeep. But to most of those who know him, he's simply `` <PERSON> Mickey </PERSON> <PERSON> Mouse </PERSON>.'' `` I want to continue as long as I find people wanting to talk to me,'' said the 83-year-old Chicago-born Jesuit, ham license 9N1MM, the only private radio operator in this tiny Himalayan kingdom sandwiched between <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>. Since he started out on the radio he built himself, <PERSON> Moran </PERSON> estimates he's talked to more than 80,000 ham operators. `` I used to talk to captains of ships at sea. They used to respond saying, ` Your signal is not good.''' In 1961, the <ORGANIZATION> Maritime </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> sent him the radio he's used since. <PERSON> Moran </PERSON> learned to make receivers from a friend in school. `` When I was 13, I used to sell them to my friends. The parts would cost me $ 90 ... I would sell it for $ 100. In those days $ 10 was good money.'' Those were also the days when broadcasting was young and no one had heard of television. `` I saw the development of radio and television from the very beginning. I was lucky to see the beginning.'' <PERSON> Moran </PERSON> set sail from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in 1929, in search of a new homeland in <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>. He settled first in <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>, and became principal of <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Xavier </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Patna </LOCATION> in the eastern Indian province of <LOCATION> Bihar </LOCATION>. It was there, in 1939, `` while I was in the middle of putting a high school in <LOCATION> Patna </LOCATION>, I met <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> _ the great man ... After a half hour talk with him I agreed to work for him,'' <PERSON> Moran </PERSON> recalls. `` In 1946, just before the end of the Second World War, I was going to shillong to give a retreat lecture before Christmas,'' he said, and <PERSON> Jawaharlal </PERSON> <PERSON> Nehru </PERSON>, who a year later would become prime minister, was on the train. `` Nehru was then president of the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- Party -RRB-. Large crowds would come to see and hear him when the train stopped at railway stations, and when his microphone did not work his voice stopped and I went up to the speakers and connected the wires,'' <PERSON> Moran </PERSON> said. `` Nehru asked me, ` What is the name of your company which takes so good care of loudspeakers?' `` I said, ` I am sorry I am a Jesuit priest and an American missionary.''' <PERSON> Moran </PERSON> met Nehru again in 1947 and drove him around <LOCATION> Bihar </LOCATION> in his jeep during Hindu-Muslim rioting before the partition of <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>. Two years later, as principal of <PERSON> St. </PERSON> <PERSON> Xavier </PERSON>'s in <LOCATION> Patna </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Moran </PERSON> made his first trip to <LOCATION> Nepal </LOCATION>, to conduct examinations for <ORGANIZATION> Patna </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. He moved to the mountain kingdom in 1951 so settle, intent on starting a boarding school. At the time, there was no airport, so he took a train to <LOCATION> Raxaul </LOCATION>, the last Indian township on the border, and made his way to <PERSON> Bhimphedi </PERSON> at the base of the Himalayan foothills. `` There were eight porters waiting for me with an ulinkath -LRB- an open palanquin -RRB-. Four of them carried me on it and four others followed, running behind them, changing turns every 10 minutes,'' he said. `` This was the only means of transportation system in those days to enter into the Nepalese capital. ... I saw even cars being carried by men on their shoulder along the trail. At <LOCATION> Bhimphedi </LOCATION>, people took off the wheels of a car and they put the car on top of two long logs with nine planks strapped sideways and 36 people in rows of four men carried it on the trail to Thankot.'' When <PERSON> Moran </PERSON> brought his own car into <LOCATION> Nepal </LOCATION> that in 1951, however, he did it by air. Even so, he said, it was a Herculean effort. `` The door of the DC-3 was so narrow that I had to take off the back and front bumpers first. The car was pushed into the plane with barely an inch to spare to fit it in.'' Some of the plane's hinges had to be removed, and `` When I asked the pilot for his permission he said, ` I ca n't give permission to do so but if I go and take a cup of tea, I might not see it Hurry up.''' That year, <PERSON> Moran </PERSON> met Nehru a third time. The prime minister was visiting as a state guest, `` saw me at a civic reception standing among the huge crowd and told <ORGANIZATION> King </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tribhuvan </ORGANIZATION>, pointing at me, ` This is my most favorite driver.''' It was also the year that <PERSON> Moran </PERSON> established St. Xavier's, in an old maharaja's summer palace 5,000 feet up in the <LOCATION> Himalayan </LOCATION> <LOCATION> foothills </LOCATION>, where he still teaches five days a week _ when he does n't have his `` ears on.''
</TEXT>
