<SECOND>BC-PRI--Gardening, Adv 02,0783</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv02</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Thursday, Nov. 2, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Getting Pleasure out of Intrigue</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Walters </PERSON> worked for the <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> as a reporter and editor from 1947 until he retired in 1984.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By JAMES E. WALTERS</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 For 40 years, when <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Warriner </PERSON> saw a rose he ticked off its development possibilities. Now he grows them mainly for pleasure. In fact, Pleasure, his 1990 All-American, is the best in mass plantings. `` One of the main reasons people do n't grow roses is they do n't want to take care of them, so if you remove that reason you get more customers,'' said <PERSON> Warriner </PERSON>, 67, who retired from <ORGANIZATION> Jackson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Perkins </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> `` I do think it's a shame more people, especially retirees, do n't enjoy the pleasure of gardening. There are about 60 rose bushes growing in the 90-by-90-foot landscape of his home in <LOCATION> Tustin </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, a <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> suburb where he's lived the past 20 years. There's also a small vegetable garden and a couple each of avocado, orange, lemon, lime and persimmon trees. It's all pretty low-key. Of his roses, <PERSON> Warriner </PERSON> says, `` Now I just like to look at them, smell them, enjoy them. What I'm looking for is beauty in the landscape.'' Pink-blooming Pleasure was propagated before his 1987 retirement as vice president of research at <ORGANIZATION> Jackson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Perkins </PERSON>, the rose-selling giant. So were his 1989 All-Americans _ Tournament of Roses and Class Act. It can be eight years from propagation to possible designation by <ORGANIZATION> All-America </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Selection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a non-profit organization of most <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> rose producers, so there may be more <PERSON> Warriner </PERSON> winners. He has 15, more than anyone in the 50-year-old competition. Announcements are n't made for two years after the selection to give growers time to produce plants for sale. Pleasure will be available this spring. I planted two test plants in March. The desert climate is a severe test but Pleasure, a floribunda, produced numerous flowers and good foliage. Compared to others, however, the flowers dropped their petals quickly after being cut. `` Sometimes a rose that holds too long makes a poor landscape subject because the flowers dry and stay on the <PERSON> bush </PERSON>,'' said <PERSON> Warriner </PERSON>. <PERSON> Warriner </PERSON>, who grew up in <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>, has never been sure why he's always had a keen interest in flowers He went to <ORGANIZATION> Michigan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> because of its horticuture reputation. He also made the boxing team as a middleweight, `` which probably cut off a lot of joking about my love of flowers.'' He still can make the weight, `` although the pounds are distributed a lot differently.'' As a hybridizer, he patented about 110 rose varieties. <ORGANIZATION> Jackson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Perkins </PERSON> estimates 41 million of his roses have been sold. Besides the 1989 and 1990 All-Americans, they include such standbys as Simplicity, Cherish, Love, Honor, Intrigue, Impatient, Sun Flare, Medallion, French Lace and Color Magic. <PERSON> Warriner </PERSON> never developed a personal favorite and says it's a thrill to see any of his growing somewhere `` because it means you did something right. `` I look on each variety in a different way. The variety that more people have grown than anything else is Simplicity. But it's certainly not the most beautiful variety I've created And so it's hard to say what the favorite is It would change every year, depending on my goals in hybridizing at the time.'' The most difficult part of hybridizing, he feels, is deciding which roses to use for the crosses. One parent of Pleasure is Intrigue, but <PERSON> Warriner </PERSON> said he never used it in hybridizing because `` it does n't really bloom enough to be a good parent, although it's a very clean plant and fragrant. But when he saw a certain seedling he recalled Intrigue's strong points and thought the combination had possibilities. He does n't recall now what it was that grabbed his attention `` We rarely had less than 150,000 seedlings. `` You go through them in the spring and summer on almost a daily basis and pick out those that look like they might have potential, and discard those with none. The first year we'd select perhaps 1,000 seedling varieties for further propagation. The next year more would be eliminated. After going through the procedure about three times, what's left are just a few varieties.'' How possible is it that the `` perfect rose'' is growing somewhere, but the owner does n't realize it and no one else sees it? `` I certainly would n't go looking for it. Roses have to be developed. I do n't see how the natural process can produce a winning specimen.''
</TEXT>
