<HEAD>Consumer Information on Audiocassette for Visually Impaired</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 More than two dozen publications on consumer issues now are available on audiocassette from regional libraries for the blind. The cassettes are being made available without charge by the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Retired </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Persons </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> for the Blind. More than half the foundation's 170 regional and sub-regional libraries are circulating tapes of <ORGANIZATION> AARP </ORGANIZATION>'s most requested publications, covering subjects such as medical care, consumer issues, financial matters, health and nutrition and long-term care. The project is designed to improve access to information for the nearly 2 million older Americans with visual impairments, <ORGANIZATION> AARP </ORGANIZATION> said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The nation's nursing homes need new ways to watch over `` wanderers,'' the thousands of patients _ especially <PERSON> Alzheimer </PERSON>'s victims _ who are prone to walking around, says a researcher seeking a high-tech solution. In three months of study at an <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> nursing home, <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Martino-Saltzman </PERSON> identified two patterns _ `` meandering,'' in which patients wander aimlessly, and `` circuiting,'' in which they walk laps around a defined area. The challenge for researchers is to find a way for nursing homes to deal with the problem without physical restraints or drugs, said <PERSON> Martino-Saltzman </PERSON>, a behavior specialist at the <ORGANIZATION> Veterans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> here. His study involved pressure-sensitive floor mats that would detect electronic tags worn by patients. The computerized system allowed the patients to wander, but alerted workers when the patients were where they should n't be. Such systems can be prohibitively expensive for small nursing homes, he said. `` Small nursing homes ca n't afford a $ 100,000 system. It behooves us to come up with something that's affordable.
</TEXT>
