<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> has resigned from the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wildlife </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION>'s corporate advisory board, calling the conservation group unfair in its criticism of the <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> oil spill. The unrepentant federation responded by calling <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> `` a corporate pariah.'' The federation, with 5.8 million members nationwide, accused <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> on Friday of repeatedly ignoring requests to meet and discuss the spill from the tanker <PERSON> Exxon </PERSON> <PERSON> Valdez </PERSON>.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 The stock market capped off a week-long run of losses with another broad decline amid worries over weakness in corporate earnings. The Dow Jones industrial average fell 17.01 to 2,596.72 Friday, extending its loss for the week to 92.42 points. The dollar weakened substantially against all major currencies except the British pound. Bond prices sagged. Gold futures prices surged to their highest levels in 3 -LCB- months; silver and platinum futures rose sharply; copper advanced; oil prices rose; livestock and meat were mostly lower; and grains and soybeans were mixed.
