<SECOND>PM-Channel One,0337</SECOND>
<HEAD>Whittle Signs 500 Schools for Channel One</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 About 500 schools with nearly 345,000 students have signed up for the launch of the advertiser-supported Channel One daily news show for the classroom set to debut this spring, the project sponsor said. <ORGANIZATION> Whittle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> Knoxville </LOCATION>, Tenn.-based media company, said Sunday the subscriptions during the first eight weeks of active recruitment of schools puts the project halfway toward its goal of having 1,000 schools equipped to receive the show at launch in March 1990. It now expects to have 1,000 schools signed up by the end of this year. The Channel One project has come under fierce attack by national educational groups, state officials in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and others who object to giving advertisers a platform for pitching products to students in the classroom. Channel One plans to send a 12-minute news show geared toward students to participating schools every weekday. Each show will contain two minutes of paid advertising. In exchange for the running the show, schools get about $ 50,000 each in television monitors, videocassette recorders and satellite dishes. <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> Whittle </PERSON>, chairman of <ORGANIZATION> Whittle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION>, said his salesmen have approached about 1,290 school districts representing 3,855 schools in 24 states so far. He said 10 percent of the districts have rejected the offer, schools in 238 districts have signed up and talks continue in the rest. He said he expects to have no trouble meeting the longer-term goal of having 7,000 to 8,000 schools participating in the program by the end of 1990. `` This documents what we thought: that local educators would view this very differently than national ones,'' he said. `` Some critics are going to be very surprised.'' Installation of equipment is expected to begin in January. Whittle has previously said it had signed contracts with advertisers who have bought 56 percent of the available commercial time on Channel One for the first year of programming.
</TEXT>
