<FIRST>r f PM-Bounced-CheckFees     10-30 0390</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bounced-Check Fees,0405</SECOND>
<HEAD>Average Cost of Bouncing Checks Going Up, Newsletter Reports</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PALM BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The average fee banks charge for bouncing a check has increased in the past two years, and it varies widely from city to city, according to a survey by an industry newsletter. Today's edition of Bank Rate Monitor says the average fee for writing a check on insufficient funds in a checking account was $ 16.13 on Oct. 25. That's up from $ 15.30 in April 1987, when it last did the survey. The highest fees were found in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>, where some banks charge as much as $ 30 for a bounced check, while the lowest were reported in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, where some charge customers less than $ 10, according to the Palm Beach-based newsletter's survey of 110 institutions in major markets. The publication said it found much the same variance in 1987. <PERSON> Cynthia </PERSON> <PERSON> McGeever </PERSON>, a vice president of <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Financial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> in <PERSON> Bala </PERSON> <PERSON> Cynwyd </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, gave competition as the reason Philadelphia-area banks charge more. <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Financial </ORGANIZATION> raised its fee from from $ 25 to $ 30 on Oct. 1. `` We perceived the whole market was moving upward,'' she told the newsletter. `` People who had been at $ 20 were going to $ 25. People at $ 25 were going to $ 30. I think it was a competitively driven decision.'' But she thought $ 30 would be the upper limit, at least for awhile. `` You may see some people below $ 30 coming up to $ 30, but I do n't think you'll see a lot who will go higher than that.'' The newsletter also reported that the number of banks and thrifts charging more than $ 15 per bounced check increased to 44 from 34. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Allen </PERSON>, a vice president of <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>, which raised its bounced-check fee from $ 17.50 to $ 20 last year, said banks need to consider the fact that bouncing a check is against the law, not just what it costs to reprocess the check. `` If you write checks in excess of the amount in the account, you are attempting to get an interest-free loan from the bank,'' he told the publication. He suggested customers have an account with overdraft protection, perhaps covered by a credit card. Bank Rate Monitor tracks average interest rates, fees and charges by major banks, thrifts and credit unions nationwide on a weekly basis.
</TEXT>
