<FIRST>r f PM-IATA-Airlines     10-30 0507</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-IATA-Airlines,0525</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congestion Problems Grow With Record Number of Passengers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Airlines carried a record number of passengers last year, boosting worldwide profits to $ 1.6 billion, the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> said in a report for release today. <ORGANIZATION> IATA </ORGANIZATION>'s annual report, released on the eve of its general assembly in the Polish capital, predicted another bumper year in 1989, but warned that air congestion would limit future expansion, especially in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. In a bid to improve security and safety measures, <ORGANIZATION> IATA </ORGANIZATION> said it planned to step up checks on airport security and review the problem of human error in air crashes. Air congestion and security are expected to be the main themes at <ORGANIZATION> IATA </ORGANIZATION>'s annual meeting. The report said <ORGANIZATION> IATA </ORGANIZATION>'s 187 member airlines carried 632 million passengers last year, a 2 percent rise over the record set in 1987. Of these, 190 million flew on international scheduled flights, more than 6 percent more than in 1987. A further 22 million people flew on domestic and international charter flights. It predicted international scheduled passenger traffic would grow 8 percent in 1989 and 1990, although it should drop back to about 7 percent in the following three years. The report said the most rapid expansion should be in <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION>. Air traffic in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> is expected to grow at a rate of about 6 percent a year. Insufficient airport capacity could limit growth in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, where congestion problems are most acute, it said. `` The lack of adequate airport and air space capacity to meet current and future demand continues to be the major problem facing the air transport industry today,'' the report commented. <ORGANIZATION> IATA </ORGANIZATION> has identified 35 airports in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> as `` congested,'' and has said that <LOCATION> Sydney </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Bombay </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> and the Japanese cities of <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Osaka </LOCATION> also are suffering from lack of airport space. The report said that the bomb explosion aboard <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> Flight 103 over <LOCATION> Lockerbie </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>, showed flaws in the implementation of security measures. It said that <ORGANIZATION> IATA </ORGANIZATION> planned to increase the number and frequency of airport surveys around the world under its Intensified Aviation Security Program. There were 20 plane crashes in 1988, five more than the previous year. Human error was the main cause of 16 of the crashes. The statistics did not list losses caused by terrorism or sabotage. <ORGANIZATION> IATA </ORGANIZATION> is to hold a conference within the next two years to overhaul the industry's approach to the problem of the `` human factor,'' it said. It said recent accidents have led to growing concern about the structural safety of older aircraft. But excess demand for new planes was forcing many airlines to modify rather than replace older aircraft. This would add to costs and impose yet another constraint on the industry's growth, it added. The increase in demand for air travel boosted total profits of airlines belonging to the Geneva-based association to $ 1.6 billion last year, up from $ 900 million in 1987 and compared with a loss of $ 300 million in 1986.
</TEXT>
