<FIRST>r f PM-China-Business     10-30 0566</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Business,0583</SECOND>
<HEAD>Foreign Business Executives Find Chinese Managers Cautious, Scared</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Foreign business executives who attended an international forum here found Chinese managers preoccupied with the government's current ideological campaign and imbued with a `` wait-and-see, cover-your-back attitude.'' Foreign executives who attended the 9th symposium in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> of the Geneva-based World Economic Forum also said it was clear during the three-day session last week that Chinese leaders were willing to let many private and collective business enterprises `` go down the drain.'' The sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the Chinese also said they were studying devaluation of the yuan and for the first time in 1990 may roll over some the nation's foreign debt. They said that in meetings with Communist Party General Secretary <PERSON> Jiang </PERSON> <PERSON> Zemin </PERSON> and other officials the Chinese emphasized that the nation's economic reforms and open-door policy were unaffected by the June crackdown on pro-democracy dissent and the subsequent conservative backlash against Western liberalism. They said the Chinese urged the delegates from 65 foreign companies to see for themselves that <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> remains eager to do business with the outside world. But they said that during the meetings, which ended Friday, there was constant reference to upholding the socialist line, and that `` everyone was quite careful to put themselves in an ideological framework.'' They said this was quite different from past meetings, when politics was never mentioned. The sources said the more than 100 Chinese managers who attended the forum were preoccupied with the question of increased <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> interference in the workplace, one aspect of the campaign to assure the party a leading role in all areas of society. `` The relationship of party and manager was clearly foremost in their minds,'' one of the sources said. They said they received conflicting signals on whether increased party authority would apply to joint Chinese-foreign ventures, and whether employees of joint ventures would be subject to government plans to have recent college graduates work at the grass-roots level for several years. The sources said the Chinese were generally more subdued than in previous years and were cautious in their statements. `` They are very scared to say anything that might backlash on them,'' one said. They said the central role of state companies was repeatedly emphasized, and that, in contrast to previous years, only one private entrepreneur participated in the forum. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s conservative leaders, in stressing that <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> must remain a socialist state, have relegated the nation's thriving non-government companies to a minor role in the economy. Higher taxes and the inability to obtain credit have driven many smaller enterprises out of business. The sources said party chief <PERSON> Jiang </PERSON> was convincing in his pledges that <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> will remain open, although he was blunt in stating that the nation's open-door policy will always have a socialist framework. Chinese officials said the government might resort to taking out new loans to repay loans due next year. They said <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, which has a foreign debt of more than $ 40 billion, owes somewhere between $ 4 and $ 9 billion next year. Officials also said the current austerity program designed to curb economic growth and slow inflation could last two to five years more. The squeeze on credit and cutback on building projects has affected many joint ventures, and the business executives were told foreign investors will have to bring their own money.
</TEXT>
