<SECOND>BC-Petroleum Waste,0282</SECOND>
<HEAD>EPA Official Warns Petroleum Producers of Oil Field Waste Hazards</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Petroleum producers are n't doing enough to protect the environment from potentially hazardous oil field wastes and in some cases are n't using common sense, an <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> official said. `` The oil and natural gas industry is way behind in waste management both in the volume and the toxicity of wastes generated,'' <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Tonetti </PERSON>, acting deputy director for the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION>'s waste management division, said Sunday <PERSON> Tonetti </PERSON> also said the industry needs more regulation at all government levels, especially in the area of commercialized waste management facilities. He spoke to the <ORGANIZATION> Independent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION>. The conference in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Antonio </LOCATION> lasts through Tuesday. Oil producers, in some cases, are not using `` common sense'' when disposing of exploration and production wastes, allowing non-hazardous materials to be mixed with toxic chemicals, <PERSON> Tonetti </PERSON> said. If not disposed of properly, oil field wastes threaten public health and safety because wastes generated during oil exploration and production can wipe out groundwater supplies and contaminate soil, <PERSON> Tonetti </PERSON> said. Under the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION>'s Resource Conservation and Recovery Act, those wastes are exempt from hazardous waste regulations. But the act applies the exemption only to drilling fluids, produced waters and other wastes associated with crude oil or natural gas production. The exemption does not include unused chemicals, spent solvents, empty drums, used lubrication oils or acidic cleaners. These chemicals sometimes get mixed with non-hazardous wastes and create a hazardous substance and a health risk, <PERSON> Tonetti </PERSON> said. `` A lot of misunderstanding exists among producers about what is exempt and what is not,'' he said.
