<HEAD>Corn, Soybeans Open Lower On Harvest; Wheat Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Corn and soybean futures prices were mostly lower in early trading today on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> while wheat futures were narrowly mixed. The slight drop in corn and soybean values partly reflected ideas that mild, dry weather allowed harvesting of those crops to continue at a rapid pace over the weekend. Rain forecast for later this week in the Corn Belt could hamper harvest activity. But with most of the crop already in, traders are focusing more on foreign demand and on the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> soybean crop, which is now being planted, said <PERSON> Victor </PERSON> <PERSON> Lespinasse </PERSON>, a trader with <ORGANIZATION> Dean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Witter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reynolds </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. `` They're behind normal and they need rain,'' he said of soybean producers in <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>. The soybean market also was pressured by expectations that a large number of deliveries will be posted against the November soybean contract on Tuesday, the first day for traders to declare their intentions to deliver soybeans against the contract. Wheat futures were supported by expectations that the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> will soon make a major purchase of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> wheat, <PERSON> Lespinasse </PERSON> said. In early trading, wheat futures were 1 -RCB- cents lower to 1 cent higher with the contract for delivery in December at $ 3.99 -LCB- a bushel; corn was -LCB- cent lower to 1 cent higher with December at $ 2.41 \ a bushel; oat futures were -LCB- cent lower to -LCB- cent higher with December at $ 1.43 \ a bushel; soybeans were 1 cent to 2 -LCB- cents lower with November at $ 5.60 a Livestock and meat futures were mixed in early trading on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. Live cattle were .10 cent lower to .15 cent higher with December at 74.10 cents a pound; feeder cattle were unchanged to .23 cent higher with November at 82.45 cents a pound; live hogs were unchanged to .27 cent lower with December at 45.90 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .10 cent to .45 cent higher with February at 52.20 cents a pound. Livestock and meat futures settled lower on Friday.
