<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two more Wall Street brokerages said Monday they would limit their program trading, joining other major firms that have backed away from the strategy under pressure following the recent stock market volatility. <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> said that effective immediately it would not execute index arbitrage for its clients. <ORGANIZATION> Kidder </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Peabody </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> said it had ceased index arbitrage for its own accounts but would continue using the strategy for its customers. The announcements followed similar moves by large brokerages last week. On Friday, <ORGANIZATION> Morgan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stanley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Bear </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stearns </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, two of the biggest users of program trading, said they would stop using index arbitrage to trade for their own accounts; <ORGANIZATION> PaineWebber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> stopped using all forms of the strategy. Index arbitrage is a computerized trading strategy aimed at profiting on brief and minute differences between prices of stocks and stock-index futures, which are traded on <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> futures exchanges. The trading tactic, in which millions of shares can be bought or sold in seconds, often is geared to make short-term profits during excitable markets. Critics say it can accentuate market movements, leading to sharp price swings such as the 190-point drop in the <ORGANIZATION> Dow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jones </ORGANIZATION> industrial average on Oct. 13. <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynch </ORGANIZATION> halted index arbitrage for its own account nearly two years ago following the Black Monday stock market crash, which critics said was worsened by program trading. In Monday's statement, <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Schreyer </PERSON> and President <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Tully </PERSON> said `` the causes of excess market volatility are far more complex than any particular computer trading strategy.'' But they conceded that `` index arbitrage has been clearly identified in the investing public's mind as a contributing factor to excess market volatilty.'' <PERSON> Merrill </PERSON> would stop executing such trades until the firm is `` satisfied that effective controls are in place,'' the statement read. <PERSON> Kidder </PERSON> was the third most active index arbitrage firm during September, trading 34.6 million shares with the strategy during the month, while <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynch </ORGANIZATION> ranked seventh with 12.8 million shares, according to the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Morgan </PERSON> <PERSON> Stanley </PERSON> led all firms with volume of 53.1 million shares. The brokerage houses have come under considerable pressure to eliminate the strategy. Last week, <ORGANIZATION> Kemper </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Financial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Keystone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, two major institutional investors, said they would no longer buy or sell stock through brokerages that conduct index arbitrage. <ORGANIZATION> Phoenix </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mutual </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Life </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Hartford </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>, followed suit Friday. On Monday, the investment management firm <ORGANIZATION> Neuberger </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Berman </PERSON> took out a full-page <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> advertisement imploring: `` Stop the numbers racket on Wall Street.'' The ad urged investors to voice their concerns in writing to <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Breeden </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON>. According to <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> figures, program trading of all kinds accounted for a record 13.8 percent of average daily volume in September, the most since the exchange began keeping such figures in July 1988.
