<HEAD>Miller Introducing Its First Non-Alcoholic Brew</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Miller </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brewing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> on Monday introduced its first non-alcoholic brew, a product it said was spurred by growing anti-drinking sentiment in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> also announced plans for a 12-week Super Bowl advertising campaign featuring two celebrity-coached teams battling on a football field over rival `` taste great'' and `` less filling'' claims for <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> <PERSON> Lite </PERSON> beer. <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>'s <PERSON> Sharp </PERSON>'s brand non-alcohol brew will be introduced for sale nationwide Jan. 1 and will be backed by a national marketing effort but no test-marketing, <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> officials said. Non-alcoholic beers have been popular in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> for some time, and other <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> brewers, including <ORGANIZATION> Anheuser-Busch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cos. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Pabst </PERSON> and <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Heileman </PERSON>, already sell non-alcohol or low-alcohol brands <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> touts <PERSON> Sharp </PERSON>'s as having a taste like real beer due to a new brewing process the company developed. <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> experimented in 1984 with a low-alcohol beer, also called <PERSON> Sharp </PERSON>'s, but the brew did not advance beyond test marketing. Annual <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> production of non-alcoholic beers is about a million barrels a year, compared with the national beer market of more than 182 million barrels. But the non-alcoholic segment is growing at the rate of 10 percent to 15 percent a year while the overall beer market has been stable, analysts said. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Krishock </PERSON>, new products category director for <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>, said growth in the non-alcoholic beer market prompted <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> to bring <PERSON> Sharp </PERSON>'s out nationwide without test marketing. The new brew will have 74 calories per 12-ounce serving _ about half the calories of regular beer _ and will be sold in bottles, cans and kegs. <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Steinman </PERSON>, publisher of the industry newsletter Beer Marketer's Insights, said <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>'s introduction of a non-alcohol beer was not surprising in view of an anti-alcohol atmosphere he said prevailed in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Steinman </PERSON> said non-alcoholic beers had not proven widely popular in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> largely because they lacked the taste of regular beer, and because brewers had found it difficult to brew a non-alcohol beer with real beer taste. <PERSON> Krishock </PERSON> said most brewers produced a non-alcoholic product by using a normal brewing cycle and then removing the alcohol along with the `` real beer'' taste. Under <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>'s new brewing process, when the yeast is added to the wort _ the end product of the barley-cooking process _ the temperature is kept low so that fermentation is slow and produces minimal alcohol, at the same time that the yeast contributes its taste to the brew. <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said its Super Bowl ad campaign, which will begin Nov. 5, will feature 12 weeks of television, radio and print advertising and a consumer sweepstakes offering expense-paid trips to Super Bowl XXIV in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION>. The celebrity teams will be coached by pro football Hall of Famer <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Csonka </PERSON> and actor <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Wendt </PERSON>, of television's `` Cheers,'' while actor <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Moll </PERSON> of television's `` Night Court'' will referee Last year, <ORGANIZATION> Anheuser-Busch </ORGANIZATION> ran a Super Bowl ad campaign featuring battling teams of animated helmet-clad beer bottles pitting its Budweiser and Bud Light brands against each other.
