<HEAD>Oil Futures Dip</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Oil futures prices drifted lower in moderate trading Monday led by weakness in the wholesale gasoline market. On the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the November contract for unleaded regular gasoline fell 1.21 cents to 53.41 cents a gallon. The contract gained nearly a penny on Friday amid reports about possible problems at a <ORGANIZATION> Chevron </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> refinery in <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Segundo </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Chevron </ORGANIZATION> confirmed late in the day that a catalytic cracking unit with an output of 60,000 barrels a day of gasoline had been closed for repairs The company said, however, that the closure would not seriously affect output. `` -LRB- Gasoline -RRB- gained Friday on news about the <ORGANIZATION> Chevron </ORGANIZATION> refinery. It should n't have gained and today it came back off,'' said <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Prudential-Bache </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. Weakness in the gasoline market dragged other oil prices lower, traders said. The December contract for <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> Intermediate, the benchmark grade of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> crude oil, closed at $ 19.72 a barrel, down 5 cents. January WTI fell 10 cents to $ 19.47 a barrel. No. 2 heating oil for November delivery settled 0.04 cent lower at 57.64 cents a gallon, while December heating oil rose 0.07 cent to end at 58.03 cents a gallon. Analysts said crude prices, which have weakened in recent days, could drift lower in advance of the Nov. 25 meeting of the <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exporting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Countries </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION>. Traders have attributed the decline to concern about higher <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> production in the face of slackening <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> demand. Various estimates have put the cartel's total output at around 23 million barrels a day, well in excess of its official quota of 20.5 million barrels a day. And while various <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> members have suggested that increasing worldwide demand supports the higher output, some analysts argue that world oil prices could weaken if the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, the largest consumer of oil, can not absorb some of the excess.
