<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Copper futures prices fell sharply Monday on <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, extending the market's two-week-old slide amid new selling prompted by a continued easing of supply fears On other futures markets Monday, precious metals retreated; pork bellies surged while livestock futures were mixed; oil futures fell; grains and soybeans slipped; and stock-index futures were narrowly mixed. Copper settled .30 cent to 3.35 cents lower with the contract for delivery in December at $ 1.128 a pound, its lowest price since Aug. 10. Copper traders began selling at the opening bell in reaction to the <ORGANIZATION> London </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Metal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>'s report of a smaller-than-expected 550 metric ton decline in warehouse stocks of copper last week. The market had expected a drawdown of as much as 4,000 tons. The report reinforced perceptions that pressure on copper supplies is easing following the recent settlement of a two-month Canadian mine strike and the expected reopening of <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s largest copper mine after a two-month shutdown. `` Two-thirds of the near-term production problems seem to have been resolved,'' said metals economist <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Demler </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, referring to the Canadian and Mexican mines. A third major copper mine, in <LOCATION> Papua </LOCATION> <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Guinea </LOCATION>, has been shut down since mid-July due to terrorism in the area. The market appeared to ignore news of a potential new supply threat in <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION>, where workers at two mines, two mills and a smelter operated by an <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </