<HEAD>Iacocca: Chrysler Plant or Plants Likely To Close by End of 1990</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 At least one of <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s 12 North American assembly plants will have to close by the end of next year and some projects may be delayed as the automaker wrestles with a smaller market, <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Iacocca </PERSON> says. <PERSON> Iacocca </PERSON>, in an interview published in Monday's <ORGANIZATION> Automotive </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION>, did n't say which plants would be closed, but speculation centers on the company's <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION> car plant as being the most likely. That plant makes the <ORGANIZATION> Dodge </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Daytona </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> LeBaron Coupe and convertible. Last year, when the company renovated its <LOCATION> Newark </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Del. </LOCATION>, plant for <ORGANIZATION> Dodge </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Spirit </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Plymouth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Acclaim </ORGANIZATION> production, it modified tooling to enable it to make the two LeBarons as well. `` You have got too much capacity chasing too few customers in the richest market in the world,'' <PERSON> Iacocca </PERSON> said. `` It will only be solved one of two ways. The way we will probably have to do it is that <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> will have to close some plants. Period. `` Or there would be a trade bill, and we would shut our borders,'' he said. `` But we wo n't do that and I do n't advocate that.'' <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> plans to idle its <LOCATION> Lakewood </LOCATION> assembly plant in <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> in March. The company already has closed plants in <LOCATION> Framingham </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass. </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Pontiac </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> officials have said they will deal with overcapacity by trimming overtime, which has been high in some <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> factories `` We definitely will have to close more than we have closed to date, which is a 100-year-old plant called <LOCATION> Kenosha </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Iacocca </PERSON> said. `` There is a plant or two that probably will be closed.'' <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> inherited the plant in <LOCATION> Kenosha </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wis. </LOCATION>, when it bought <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION>. Besides the plant closing, <PERSON> Iacocca </PERSON> said some projects may be delayed, but that the company's new LH and LX car programs will continue. Cars derived from the two platforms will be introduced in the early 1990s. `` That one is not going to be deferred because it is in the heart of the market,'' he said, `` and we would like some strengthening there.'' <PERSON> Iacocca </PERSON> indicated that the No. 3 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> car company may abandon parts of the automobile or truck market if it determines that it is n't profitable. `` I do n't think we can afford to be in every car and truck segment,'' he said. `` In this world market now, you can not go it alone and you can not be all things to all people. ... `` So we're going to have to continue to try to develop car niches that are profitable to us.''
</TEXT>
