<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Quotron </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Systems </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> said Monday it will lay off 400 of its 2,500 employees because demand for financial information has plunged due to Wall Street cutbacks and consolidations since the October 1987 stock market crash. The layoffs will affect a wide range of job levels at <ORGANIZATION> Quotron </ORGANIZATION> offices around the world, said the Los Angeles-based subsidiary of <ORGANIZATION> Citicorp </ORGANIZATION>, the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> banking company. Quotron provides financial information such as stock prices through a network of more than 100,000 computer terminals in 23 countries. Its competitors include <ORGANIZATION> Telerate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Reuters </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Holding </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Knight-Ridder </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Quotron </ORGANIZATION>'s president and chief executive, <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Hann </PERSON>, said in a statement that the layoffs `` will continue to keep operating expenses in line with revenues in response to changing conditions in the retail securities industry, which has been contracting since October 1987. Quotron revenues had been growing at the rate of 25 percent a year when <ORGANIZATION> Citicorp </ORGANIZATION> acquired the company two years ago for $ 680 million, about three times <ORGANIZATION> Quotron </ORGANIZATION>'s annual revenues at that time. <ORGANIZATION> Citicorp </ORGANIZATION>, the nation's largest bank holding concern, does not provide financial results for <ORGANIZATION> Quotron </ORGANIZATION>.
