<HEAD>Boeing Reports Strong 3rd Quarter Profits, But Says Strike Will Hurt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf, `Boeing released ...,' with talks ending for
day.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE TIBBITS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> enjoyed record third-quarter profits 68 percent higher than in the same period in 1988, but the jet builder warned Monday that a lingering strike by <ORGANIZATION> Machinists </ORGANIZATION> will hurt badly the rest of the year. The company also said it is having `` substantial'' losses on some government and defense programs. <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> released its earnings statement as its negotiators met with those of the <ORGANIZATION> Machinists </ORGANIZATION> union in an attempt to end the four-week-old strike. Six hours of talks produced only an agreement to meet again Tuesday. Federal mediator <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> <PERSON> Hammond </PERSON>, who called Monday's session, said he hoped to keep the two sides at the table until a new contract offer can be worked out. <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Shrontz </PERSON> said the higher profits for the quarter and first nine months were due mostly to higher sales volume and lower research, development and other new business costs for commercial aircraft and computing. But he said that performance was partially offset by losses and higher research and development costs for defense programs, and a higher effective federal tax rate. Net earnings for the quarter ending Sept. 30 were $ 242 million, or $ 1.05 a share, on revenue of $ 6.36 billion, compared with profits of $ 144 million, or 63 cents a share, on revenue of $ 3.72 billion a year earlier. <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Binder </PERSON> said both profits and sales for the most recent quarter were records for the company. For the first nine months of 1989, <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION>'s profits were $ 598 million, or $ 2.60 a share, on revenue of $ 15.43 billion, compared with net earnings of $ 440 million, or $ 1.92 a share, on revenue of $ 12.09 billion. `` While that looks good at first glance, closer inspection indicates our net profit was only 3.9 percent'' for the first nine months, <PERSON> Binder </PERSON> said. `` Our profit margin is approximately 1 percent less than the average of all <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> manufacturing companies and we simply must do better to remain competitive.'' Union spokesman <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Daniels </PERSON> read it differently: `` That falls into line with our contention that their profits indicate they should make a better offer to the <ORGANIZATION> Machinists </ORGANIZATION> union.'' Stock analysts said <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION>'s performance was about what they anticipated, although they took special note of the downbeat forecasts for defense work and strike effects. `` That's the first time I've seen any indication they feel there will be a severe impact on the fourth quarter,'' said <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Nisbet </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Prudential-Bache </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. `` At the end of the second quarter, they mentioned matter of factly that the company's defense and space programs would not be profitable at the end of 1989,'' said <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Deatherage </PERSON>, analyst at <ORGANIZATION> Dean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Witter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reynolds </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. `` Now they're saying it's a significant loss. <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> announced on Friday a major reorganization of its defense division. The third-quarter figures do n't show effects of the strike by about 57,800 union Machinists who walked out Oct. 4 after rejecting a 3-year contract offer. `` The strike by the <ORGANIZATION> Machinists </ORGANIZATION> union will have a serious adverse impact on fourth-quarter sales and earnings and on the company's cash and short-term investment position,'' <PERSON> Shrontz </PERSON> said in the earnings statement That was one of the strongest acknowledgments from <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> about damages from the strike, which has severely slowed aircraft deliveries. When the strike began, <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> had hoped to deliver another 94 aircraft by the end of the year. So far, it has delivered only 15.
